1d53d394 [deepseek-v4] #I see the issue you're describing. In `sloppybot.ts`, the code alternates between two listener
1d53d394 [deepseek-v4] #ports (8081 for "sloppy", 8082 for "riff") by toggling a flag `sloppyListen`. When the first
1d53d395 [deepseek-v4] #connection arrives on port 8081, it sets `riffPromise` and then switches to listen on 8082. This
1d53d395 [deepseek-v4] #means only one connection is active at a time – the other person is left waiting for a
1d53d395 [deepseek-v4] #connection that never arrives because the listener is swapped.
1d53d395 [deepseek-v4] #
1d53d396 [deepseek-v4] #The "ping pong" break is likely because the Discord bot:
1d53d396 [deepseek-v4] #
1d53d396 [deepseek-v4] #1. Connects on port 8081 (sloppy)
1d53d396 [deepseek-v4] #2. A second process or retry arrives on port 8082 (riff)
1d53d397 [deepseek-v4] #3. The listener flips back to 8081, but the original fountain connection is now not being
1d53d397 [deepseek-v4] #read – the `receivePromise` for the first connection may be overwritten or lost.
1d53d397 [deepseek-v4] #
1d53d397 [deepseek-v4] #Root cause:
1d53d398 [deepseek-v4] #The `listenService()` function in `slopprompt.ts` sets up a single listener (on 8081) and
1d53d398 [deepseek-v4] #then alternates. But `slopPail` and the relay code in `relay.ts` expect a reliable, permanent TCP
1d53d398 [deepseek-v4] #connection. The alternation is designed for two‑way separate processes (sloppy and riff),
1d53d398 [deepseek-v4] #but it doesn't handle concurrent or reconnecting peers.
1d53d399 [deepseek-v4] #
1d53d399 [deepseek-v4] #Suggested fix:
1d53d399 [deepseek-v4] #Implement a single persistent listener or maintain both ports independently. In `slopprompt.ts`,
1d53d399 [deepseek-v4] #change `listenService` to start both ports in parallel:
