1d5717a6 [roha] [ASSISTANT] {"role":"assistant","mut":"deepseek-v4","emoji":"🐋","name":"deepseek-v4-flash","content":"The files appear to be the core of the Slop Relay project – a research tool for connecting and testing multiple LLMs behind a unified relay interface. The code covers:\n\n- **relay.ts** – main application with command processing, model switching (DeepSeek, Gemini, Anthropic, OpenAI), shared file handling, history management, and a raw-mode chat loop.\n- **slopprompt.ts** – a raw-mode stdin replacement that also accepts remote connections (TCP 8081–8083) for multi-user / bot integration.\n- **sloppybot.ts** – a Discord client that bridges messages to the fountain relay.\n- **slopsearch.ts** – a short snippet using the Exa API for web search.\n\nI notice the MIT license and the version `1.8.0`. Is there a specific area you'd like to discuss – perhaps the relay logic, the tool‑call handling, the unicode width quirks, or something else?","elapsed":7.705433500000001,"price":0.008352960000000001}
1d5717a6 [roha] [ASSISTANT] {"role":"assistant","mut":"deepseek-v4","emoji":"🐋","name":"deepseek-v4-flash","content":"It sounds like you’re testing the Discord bot integration and suspect the TCP connections aren’t working. Let’s isolate the common issues.\n\n## Quick checks\n\n1. **Is the Discord bot online?**  \n   In the terminal running `sloppybot.ts`, you should see `sloppy 0.10 🦜 splurt:...` and then `[SLOPPY] discordClient online <bot name>`. If not, either the token is missing (env `DISCORD_BOT`) or the bot is not invited to the server.\n\n2. **Are the TCP ports free?**  \n   The fountain (relay) listens on 8081, 8082, 8083 when `listen` config flag is enabled. The bot connects to port 8081 by default.  \n   Run `netstat -an | findstr :8081` (Windows) or `lsof -i :8081` (macOS/Linux) to see if something is already listening.  \n   If you start the fountain after the bot (or vice versa), you’ll get `Address already in use` errors (check stderr of both processes).\n\n3. **Logs from the bot** (sloppybot)  \n   It writes debug messages to `console.error` (splurt). Look for lines like:  \n   - `connected with noDelay localhost:8081` – connection succeeded.  \n   - `Connection Refused` – the fountain is not listening yet.  \n   - `Connection Error` – something else (e.g., firewall, port blocked).  \n\n4. **Logs from the fountain**  \n   When a TCP client connects, `slopprompt.ts` prints:  \n   `[PROMPT] listening for slop <port> <name>`  \n   and later:  \n   `connection received for <name>`  \n   If you see these, the link is up.\n\n## Common pitfalls\n\n- **Double‑listen in `slopprompt.ts`**  \n  In `slopPrompt()` it calls `listenPort(8081...)` again, even if `listenService()` already opened the port. This will fail silently (or throw) because the port is already bound. I recommend removing the listen calls inside `slopPrompt` – the listeners should only be created once, either in `listenService()` or inside `slopPrompt`, not both.\n\n- **Bot‑fountain ordering**  \n  The bot waits 20 seconds before trying to connect. If the fountain starts later, the bot will keep retrying (only once, unfortunately). Consider adding a reconnection loop in `connectFountain()`.\n\n- **Firewall / antivirus**  \n  On Windows, Deno may need explicit permission to listen on localhost ports. Check Windows Defender notifications.\n\n- **Missing `listen` config flag**  \n  In `relay.ts`, `listenService()` and `acceptThread()` are only called if `roha.config.listen` is true. Make sure you set that flag (e.g., `/config listen` command) before trying to use the bot.\n\n## Next steps\n\n1. **Start the fountain first** with `listen` enabled, then start the bot (or vice versa).  \n2. **Watch stderr** of both processes for any error lines.  \n3. Try a simple TCP test – use `telnet localhost 8081` or `nc localhost 8081` to see if the fountain accepts connections.  \n4. If you see `connection received` on the fountain side but no messages flowing, check that the bot is actually `@mentioning` the bot user in the Discord channel (the bot only responds to mentions in the `openChannel` – by default channel ID `1473539274384211999`).\n\nOnce you have the error messages (if any), share them and we can drill down.","elapsed":14.652093700000005,"price":0.010240776000000002}
