1d5927cd [deepseek-v4] #I’ve reviewed the current listen/accept flow in `relay.ts` and `slopprompt.ts`. Here’s a breakdown
1d5927cd [deepseek-v4] #of how it works and the pain points I see:
1d5927cd [deepseek-v4] #
1d5927cd [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1d5927ce [deepseek-v4] #
1d5927ce [deepseek-v4] #Current architecture
1d5927ce [deepseek-v4] #
1d5927ce [deepseek-v4] #1. `relay.ts` – `listenService()` opens listeners on ports 8081–8083. It also calls
1d5927cf [deepseek-v4] #`acceptThread()` which only accepts on `sloppyListener` (port 8081) in a loop.
1d5927cf [deepseek-v4] #2. `slopprompt.ts` – Exports its own `listenService()` that also opens the same
1d5927cf [deepseek-v4] #three ports (duplicate). The `slopPrompt()` function, when called, also opens port 8081 and 8082
1d5927cf [deepseek-v4] #via `listenPort()` and then races an accept promise against the user input and existing connection
1d5927d0 [deepseek-v4] #read promises.
1d5927d0 [deepseek-v4] #3. Bot connector (`sloppybot.ts`) – Opens a TCP connection to port 8081 and sends NDJSON
1d5927d0 [deepseek-v4] #messages. The relay receives them via `readNamedConnection()`, which stores promises in
1d5927d0 [deepseek-v4] #`receivePromises`.
1d5927d1 [deepseek-v4] #4. Race handling – In `slopPrompt()`, a `Promise.race()` races the stdin reader, a timer,
1d5927d1 [deepseek-v4] #the listener accept promise, and all `receivePromises`. When a connection arrives, it’s stored in
1d5927d1 [deepseek-v4] #`slopConnections` and a new read promise is created.
1d5927d2 [deepseek-v4] #
1d5927d2 [deepseek-v4] #Major issues
1d5927d2 [deepseek-v4] #
1d5927d2 [deepseek-v4] #╭───────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1d5927d3 [deepseek-v4] #│  Issue                                        │  Impact                                                                                                                                                                           │
1d5927d3 [deepseek-v4] #├───────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1d5927d3 [deepseek-v4] #│  **Duplicate listener creation**              │  `relay.ts::listenService()` and `slopprompt.ts::listenService()` both open the same ports. If both run, the second will throw "Address already in use".                          │
1d5927d3 [deepseek-v4] #│  **`acceptThread()` only handles port 8081**  │  Ports 8082/8083 are never accepted in `relay.ts`. The bot bridge only uses port 8081, so this hasn’t broken anything, but it blocks expansion.                                   │
1d5927d4 [deepseek-v4] #│  **Race promise growth**                      │  Every new connection adds a promise to `receivePromises`. If many bots connect, the `Promise.race()` array grows unbounded — no cleanup for disconnected peers.                  │
1d5927d4 [deepseek-v4] #│  **No connection identity handshake**         │  Bots are identified only by the name assigned on accept (`"connectionN"`). There’s no way to know which bot (sloppy, riff, foggy) is talking.                                    │
1d5927d4 [deepseek-v4] #│  **Error handling on writes**                 │  `slopBroadcast()` catches write errors and removes the connection, but the associated `receivePromises` entry is not deleted, causing stale promises to remain in the race set.  │
1d5927d4 [deepseek-v4] #╰───────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1d5927d5 [deepseek-v4] #
