1d67612d [nitro@ryzen5] how is llm column calculated in accounts output
1d67624a [deepseek-v4] #The term "LLM" in accounting outputs is not a universal standard, but in many accounting software
1d67624a [deepseek-v4] #systems (e.g., Tally ERP, QuickBooks, or custom ERP reports), LLM commonly stands for
1d67624a [deepseek-v4] #"Last Ledger Month" or "Last Month's Ledger" – representing the closing balance of
1d67624b [deepseek-v4] #an account as of the end of the previous month.
1d67624b [deepseek-v4] #
1d67624b [deepseek-v4] #Calculation (assuming Last Month’s Ledger)
1d67624b [deepseek-v4] #1. Identify the time period – The LLM column refers to the immediately preceding complete
1d67624c [deepseek-v4] #month (e.g., if the report is for February, LLM shows January’s closing balance).
1d67624c [deepseek-v4] #2. Opening balance – Use the opening balance of the current financial period (or month).
1d67624c [deepseek-v4] #3. Net transactions – Sum all debit and credit entries for the account from the opening
1d67624c [deepseek-v4] #date up to the end of the previous month.
1d67624d [deepseek-v4] #4. Closing balance – Compute the closing balance for that preceding month:
1d67624d [deepseek-v4] #   `Closing Balance = Opening Balance + Debits – Credits`
1d67624d [deepseek-v4] #   (or appropriate sign convention based on account type).
1d67624d [deepseek-v4] #5. LLM value – That closing balance becomes the LLM figure displayed in the current month’s
1d67624e [deepseek-v4] #report.
1d67624e [deepseek-v4] #
1d67624e [deepseek-v4] #	Example:* For a Sales account with an opening balance of ₹0 in April, if March sales total
1d67624e [deepseek-v4] #₹10,000 (credit) and no debits, the LLM column in the April report would show ₹10,000 (the March
1d67624f [deepseek-v4] #closing balance).
1d67624f [deepseek-v4] #
1d67624f [deepseek-v4] #Alternative interpretations
1d67624f [deepseek-v4] #- Ledger Line Mark – A system-generated flag indicating the last transaction line for that
1d676250 [deepseek-v4] #account.
1d676250 [deepseek-v4] #- Loan Loss Model – In banking/finance, LLM may refer to a provisioning model, but that is
1d676250 [deepseek-v4] #rare in standard accounts output.
1d676250 [deepseek-v4] #
1d676251 [deepseek-v4] #For a precise answer, please confirm:
1d676251 [deepseek-v4] #- Which software or report you are using (e.g., Tally, QuickBooks, Zoho Books).
1d676251 [deepseek-v4] #- Whether the column appears in a trial balance, ledger report, or profit & loss statement.
1d676251 [deepseek-v4] #
1d676252 [deepseek-v4] #If you provide the exact context, I can give a more specific calculation method.
1d676252 [deepseek-v4] #
