1d67d261 [roha] [ASSISTANT] {"role":"assistant","mut":"deepseek-v4","emoji":"🐋","name":"deepseek-v4-flash","content":"The term \"LLM\" in accounting outputs is not a universal standard, but in many accounting software systems (e.g., Tally ERP, QuickBooks, or custom ERP reports), **LLM** commonly stands for **\"Last Ledger Month\"** or **\"Last Month's Ledger\"** – representing the closing balance of an account as of the end of the previous month.\n\n### Calculation (assuming Last Month’s Ledger)\n1. **Identify the time period** – The LLM column refers to the immediately preceding complete month (e.g., if the report is for February, LLM shows January’s closing balance).\n2. **Opening balance** – Use the opening balance of the current financial period (or month).\n3. **Net transactions** – Sum all debit and credit entries for the account from the opening date up to the end of the previous month.\n4. **Closing balance** – Compute the closing balance for that preceding month:  \n   `Closing Balance = Opening Balance + Debits – Credits`  \n   (or appropriate sign convention based on account type).\n5. **LLM value** – That closing balance becomes the LLM figure displayed in the current month’s report.\n\n> **Example:** For a Sales account with an opening balance of ₹0 in April, if March sales total ₹10,000 (credit) and no debits, the LLM column in the April report would show ₹10,000 (the March closing balance).\n\n### Alternative interpretations\n- **Ledger Line Mark** – A system-generated flag indicating the last transaction line for that account.\n- **Loan Loss Model** – In banking/finance, LLM may refer to a provisioning model, but that is rare in standard accounts output.\n\nFor a precise answer, please confirm:\n- Which software or report you are using (e.g., Tally, QuickBooks, Zoho Books).\n- Whether the column appears in a trial balance, ledger report, or profit & loss statement.\n\nIf you provide the exact context, I can give a more specific calculation method.","