1d7dc9df [deepseek-v4] #`messageSloppy()` for each message, sending it to the same Discord channel.
1d7dc9df [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9df [deepseek-v4] #This means that when the relay broadcasts a model response (a “general message”), all three bots –
1d7dc9e0 [deepseek-v4] #sloppy, riff, and foggy – each send that response to the Discord channel. That results in
1d7dc9e0 [deepseek-v4] #triple‑posting, which is probably not what you want.
1d7dc9e0 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e0 [deepseek-v4] #The Need for Name Guarding
1d7dc9e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e1 [deepseek-v4] #You said “guard against names that don’t match”. I think you mean:
1d7dc9e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e2 [deepseek-v4] #- Only one bot should handle general (non‑announce) messages, likely `foggy` (since it’s
1d7dc9e2 [deepseek-v4] #already the announcer).
1d7dc9e2 [deepseek-v4] #- The other bots (sloppy, riff) should either ignore general messages or handle different message
1d7dc9e2 [deepseek-v4] #categories (e.g., status, debug, or specific `from` identifiers).
1d7dc9e3 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e3 [deepseek-v4] #Currently there is no such guard – every bot sends everything. So you need a way to decide which
1d7dc9e3 [deepseek-v4] #bot is responsible for each message type.
1d7dc9e3 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e4 [deepseek-v4] #Design Options (Discussion, No Code)
1d7dc9e4 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e4 [deepseek-v4] #Option A: Single dispatcher bot
1d7dc9e4 [deepseek-v4] #Make `foggy` the sole handler for all messages (announce + general). Other bots only serve as
1d7dc9e4 [deepseek-v4] #bridged sources (e.g., they receive input from Discord and forward it to the relay, but never write
1d7dc9e5 [deepseek-v4] #back to Discord). This is simple and avoids duplicates, but loses the potential for per‑bot
1d7dc9e5 [deepseek-v4] #personalities or separate channels.
1d7dc9e5 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e5 [deepseek-v4] #Option B: Route by `from` field
1d7dc9e6 [deepseek-v4] #The relay already includes a `from` field in each message (e.g., the emoji like `🐋` or the bot
1d7dc9e6 [deepseek-v4] #name). Each bot could compare its own identifier against the `from` value:
1d7dc9e6 [deepseek-v4] #- Only send a message to Discord if the `from` matches the bot’s own emoji/name.
1d7dc9e6 [deepseek-v4] #- For example, `riff` would only relay messages where `from === "🐶"`; `foggy` where `from ===
1d7dc9e6 [deepseek-v4] #"🐸"`.
1d7dc9e7 [deepseek-v4] #This gives each bot a dedicated voice and avoids duplicates.
1d7dc9e7 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e7 [deepseek-v4] #Option C: Route by message type
1d7dc9e7 [deepseek-v4] #Tag messages with a category (e.g., `announce`, `reply`, `status`) and let each bot subscribe to
1d7dc9e7 [deepseek-v4] #certain categories. `foggy` gets everything, `riff` gets only replies, `sloppy` only status –
1d7dc9e8 [deepseek-v4] #flexible but adds complexity on both relay and bot sides.
1d7dc9e8 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e8 [deepseek-v4] #Option D: Use a dedicated channel per bot
1d7dc9e8 [deepseek-v4] #Instead of all bots writing to one channel, give each bot its own Discord channel. Then there’s no
1d7dc9e8 [deepseek-v4] #conflict – every bot sends everything it receives. This means the user would see three parallel
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #channels with the same content, which might be desired for testing but not for normal operation.
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #What I recommend for now
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #Given you’re testing and want to avoid duplicates, the simplest guard is option A: let only
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #`foggy` send non‑announce messages to Discord. The other bots will still receive and forward user
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #messages to the relay, but when the relay broadcasts a response, only `foggy` writes it out. That
1d7dc9e9 [deepseek-v4] #matches your statement “making foggy the default message announce for app messages”.
1d7dc9ea [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9ea [deepseek-v4] #You could also combine with option B for clarity: set `sloppy` and `riff` to ignore all
1d7dc9ea [deepseek-v4] #broadcasts unless the `from` specifically matches their identifier.
1d7dc9ea [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9eb [deepseek-v4] #Next step
1d7dc9eb [deepseek-v4] #
1d7dc9eb [deepseek-v4] #If you’d like, I can help you review where in `onFountain()` (or `messageSloppy`) the guard should
1d7dc9eb [deepseek-v4] #be placed, without writing code – just discussing the logic. Otherwise, if you’re ready to
1d7dc9ec [deepseek-v4] #implement, let me know and we can proceed.
1d7dc9ec [deepseek-v4] #
