1d7de3e3 [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing these files. The Slop Relay system is an impressive, many:many research tool
1d7de3e4 [deepseek-v4] #for interacting with multiple LLM providers. I’ve reviewed the core relay, prompt handler, Discord
1d7de3e4 [deepseek-v4] #bots, and the session log.
1d7de3e4 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3e4 [deepseek-v4] #A few observations:
1d7de3e5 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3e5 [deepseek-v4] #1. Architecture – The relay runs as a Deno process that connects to several API providers
1d7de3e5 [deepseek-v4] #(DeepSeek, OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, xAI, etc.) via accounts.json. It maintains a shared
1d7de3e5 [deepseek-v4] #conversation history (`rohaHistory`) and broadcasts output to Discord bots through a local TCP
1d7de3e6 [deepseek-v4] #server. This setup allows you to flip between models mid‑session.
1d7de3e6 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3e6 [deepseek-v4] #2. Prompt handling – `slopprompt.ts` implements raw‑mode input with shortcode replacement,
1d7de3e6 [deepseek-v4] #grapheme‑aware backspace, and history navigation. It also manages multiple bot connections using
1d7de3e7 [deepseek-v4] #`Promise.race`. This is a clever way to interleave keyboard input, incoming bot messages, and timer
1d7de3e7 [deepseek-v4] #ticks without blocking.
1d7de3e7 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3e7 [deepseek-v4] #3. Discord bots – Each bot (`foggy`, `sloppy`, `riff`) connects to the local relay and
1d7de3e8 [deepseek-v4] #relays messages to/from a Discord channel. The output log shows all three bots connected and
1d7de3e8 [deepseek-v4] #successfully passing a user query (“<@&…> you good?”) to the DeepSeek model and broadcasting the
1d7de3e8 [deepseek-v4] #reply.
1d7de3e8 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3e9 [deepseek-v4] #4. Session metadata – The status line printed after each relay call includes model name,
1d7de3e9 [deepseek-v4] #temperature, cost, history size, and elapsed time. This is useful for tracking usage across
1d7de3e9 [deepseek-v4] #different models.
1d7de3e9 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3ea [deepseek-v4] #5. File sharing – The `/share` and `/commit` commands allow attaching files (text, images)
1d7de3ea [deepseek-v4] #to the conversation. The `output.txt` shows 5 shares were active on startup.
1d7de3ea [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3ea [deepseek-v4] #The log also shows that the `foggy` bot reacts with 👍 to non‑bot messages in the channel, and all
1d7de3eb [deepseek-v4] #bots receive and forward the assistant’s response. The “Files shared. Feel free to comment if
1d7de3eb [deepseek-v4] #content is new or different.” line appears because the assistant (the relay tool) added a warning
1d7de3eb [deepseek-v4] #after a `/commit` call.
1d7de3eb [deepseek-v4] #
1d7de3ec [deepseek-v4] #Everything looks coherent and well‑structured for an experimental research tool. The code style
1d7de3ec [deepseek-v4] #(tabs, named functions) is consistent. If you have specific questions about any part—such as the
1d7de3ec [deepseek-v4] #raw prompt loop, the provider‑specific API adapters, or the async connection management—I’d be
1d7de3ec [deepseek-v4] #happy to discuss further.
1d7de3ed [deepseek-v4] #
