1d7e8665 [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for the detailed code and logs. I now have a clear picture of your setup.
1d7e8665 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e8665 [deepseek-v4] #You want Discord `!ping` (and the bot’s `pong!` reply) to appear in the main `forge.log`, not just
1d7e8666 [deepseek-v4] #in the slopbot’s stderr output. The logs you shared show that the bot responds with `pong!` and
1d7e8666 [deepseek-v4] #sets the `openChannel`, but those events are not written to `forge/forge.log`.
1d7e8666 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e8666 [deepseek-v4] #There are two different “ping/pong” concepts in Discord bots:
1d7e8667 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e8667 [deepseek-v4] #1. Gateway heartbeat (WebSocket keep‑alive) – these are internal to the Discord client and
1d7e8667 [deepseek-v4] #not normally surfaced.
1d7e8667 [deepseek-v4] #2. User‑triggered `!ping` command – which your `slopbot.ts` handles.
1d7e8668 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e8668 [deepseek-v4] #Based on your output, the `!ping` command is working, but the event is not flowing through the
1d7e8668 [deepseek-v4] #relay’s logging pipeline (`logForge`). The slopbot communicates with the relay via a TCP connection
1d7e8668 [deepseek-v4] #(local host, port 8081). Messages the bot sends to the relay are parsed by `slopprompt.ts` and then
1d7e8669 [deepseek-v4] #turned into user input in the main relay loop. However, the `!ping` response (the `pong!` reply) is
1d7e8669 [deepseek-v4] #sent directly to the Discord channel using `channel.send()`, and is not sent back
1d7e8669 [deepseek-v4] #to the relay. Therefore it never gets logged.
1d7e8669 [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866a [deepseek-v4] #What would you like to achieve?
1d7e866a [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866a [deepseek-v4] #- Option A – Log only the `!ping` command reception (i.e., when the bot hears `!ping`).
1d7e866a [deepseek-v4] #- Option B – Log both the incoming `!ping` and the outgoing `pong!` reply.
1d7e866b [deepseek-v4] #- Option C – Log any Gateway ping/pong events (more complex).
1d7e866b [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866b [deepseek-v4] #I suspect you want Option B – to have a record in `forge.log` that a ping/pong exchange
1d7e866b [deepseek-v4] #happened, perhaps for uptime monitoring.
1d7e866b [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866c [deepseek-v4] #One approach (without changing the architecture too much)
1d7e866c [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866c [deepseek-v4] #In `slopbot.ts`, you can modify the `!ping` handler to also send a JSON message to the relay via
1d7e866c [deepseek-v4] #the existing TCP connection. The message could be something like:
1d7e866c [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866d [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866d [deepseek-v4] #{"pingpong": {"command":"!ping", "channel": "1473539274384211999", "user": "scudmarks"}}
1d7e866d [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866d [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866d [deepseek-v4] #Then in `relay.ts` (or `slopprompt.ts` when processing incoming data), you would detect the
1d7e866e [deepseek-v4] #`pingpong` key and call `logForge()` directly, without pushing it into the conversation
1d7e866e [deepseek-v4] #history. That way the event is logged but doesn’t trigger an LLM response or appear in the Discord
1d7e866e [deepseek-v4] #channel.
1d7e866e [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866f [deepseek-v4] #Alternatively, you could simply forward the `!ping` message itself to the relay (as you already do
1d7e866f [deepseek-v4] #for mentions), but then you’d get an LLM answer, which you probably don’t want for `!ping`.
1d7e866f [deepseek-v4] #
1d7e866f [deepseek-v4] #Would you like me to elaborate on any of these options, or provide a code snippet for the specific
1d7e866f [deepseek-v4] #file you want to modify? I’ll hold off on writing code unless you ask.
1d7e8670 [deepseek-v4] #
