1d818487 [deepseek-v4] #Based on your shared session, I see a few significant problems in the relay system that cause
1d818487 [deepseek-v4] #degraded operation:
1d818487 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818487 [deepseek-v4] #• 1. Unnecessary raw byte echo broadcasts to all bots*
1d818488 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818488 [deepseek-v4] #In `slopprompt.ts`, `readNamedConnection` logs raw byte arrays via `echo()`:
1d818488 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818488 [deepseek-v4] #echo("[STATUS] readNamedConnection",name,n,bytes);
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #This `echo()` goes through the output buffer and gets broadcast to all connected slop clients. You
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #can see the effect in `output2.txt`:
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #[STATUS] readNamedConnection connection0 88 123,34,109,101,115,115,97,103,101,115,34,58,91...
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818489 [deepseek-v4] #This should use `echoInfo()` instead, which bypasses the broadcast pipeline.
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #• 2. Stale receive promises accumulate without cleanup*
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #In `slopprompt.ts`, `receivePromises[name]` is set after each read but never removed on error or
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #disconnection:
1d81848a [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #receivePromises[name] = receiver;
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #When a connection returns `source` (either success or error), the promise is overwritten but the
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #connection object may be invalid. The `delete receivePromises[name]` call only runs in the success
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #path. If the connection errors, the throw at line:
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848b [deepseek-v4] #throw(error); // this will cause a crash
1d81848c [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848c [deepseek-v4] #terminates the entire prompt loop, bringing down the relay.
1d81848c [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848c [deepseek-v4] #• 3. Connection error handling throws instead of recovering*
1d81848c [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #When a bot connection has an error, `readNamedConnection` returns `{source: connection, error,
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #name}`, but the handler in `slopPrompt` throws rather than cleaning up and retrying.
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #• 4. Duplicate echoInfo calls on every bot read*
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848d [deepseek-v4] #In `relay.ts`, the `readNamedConnection` line:
1d81848e [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848e [deepseek-v4] #echo("[STATUS] readNamedConnection", name, n, bytes);
1d81848e [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848f [deepseek-v4] #logs twice for the same message — once with `readNamedConnection 90 connection0` (just name and
1d81848f [deepseek-v4] #length) and once with the full byte dump. The two log statements appear in different places in the
1d81848f [deepseek-v4] #code.
1d81848f [deepseek-v4] #
1d81848f [deepseek-v4] #• 5. `remoteBuffer` processes stale entries silently*
1d818490 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818490 [deepseek-v4] #In `relay.ts`, `remoteBuffer` collects overridden `console.error` calls. The flush function
1d818490 [deepseek-v4] #processes them:
1d818490 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818491 [deepseek-v4] #for (const {line, from} of remoteBuffer) {
1d818491 [deepseek-v4] #    // muted on public channels
1d818491 [deepseek-v4] #    //      send.push(line);
1d818492 [deepseek-v4] #    // dont share just log remote chatter
1d818492 [deepseek-v4] #    //      rohaPush(line,from);
1d818492 [deepseek-v4] #    await logForge(line,from);
1d818492 [deepseek-v4] #}
1d818493 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818493 [deepseek-v4] #The code says "dont share" but still writes every error to forge.log. This can fill the log quickly
1d818493 [deepseek-v4] #with chatter messages that should be filtered.
1d818493 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818494 [deepseek-v4] #• Suggested fixes:*
1d818494 [deepseek-v4] #
1d818494 [deepseek-v4] #For issue 1 — change `echo` to `echoInfo` in `readNamedConnection`:
