1da93111 [deepseek-v4] #Thanks for sharing the full code and logs — very interesting to see the `nitrologic Relay` system
1da93111 [deepseek-v4] #in action. Here’s a review and commentary on what’s there.
1da93111 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93111 [deepseek-v4] #General Architecture
1da93112 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93112 [deepseek-v4] #The project is a multi-model chat relay with:
1da93112 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93112 [deepseek-v4] #- A central relay (`relay.ts`) that connects to multiple LLM providers (OpenAI, DeepSeek, Google,
1da93113 [deepseek-v4] #Anthropic, xAI, Z.AI, Moonshot, Ollama) via their respective APIs.
1da93113 [deepseek-v4] #- Two separate console workers (`slopbot.ts`) for Discord bots (`foggy`, `sloppy`, `riff`), each
1da93113 [deepseek-v4] #communicating with the relay over TCP (port `8081`).
1da93113 [deepseek-v4] #- A raw-mode terminal interface (`slopprompt.ts`) that handles Unicode, shortcode replacement, and
1da93114 [deepseek-v4] #async I/O.
1da93114 [deepseek-v4] #- A configuration system via `forge.json` that persists model metadata, share history, and
1da93114 [deepseek-v4] #counters.
1da93114 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93115 [deepseek-v4] #The logs (`output.txt`, `output2.txt`) show it working end‑to‑end:
1da93115 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93115 [deepseek-v4] #- Discord user `scudmarks` sends a message → relay sends it to DeepSeek‑V4 → reply is broadcast
1da93115 [deepseek-v4] #back to all Discord bots and the terminal.
1da93116 [deepseek-v4] #- The relay’s status line (`ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.1 ⛲ deepseek-v4 …`) appears in the terminal and
1da93116 [deepseek-v4] #is forwarded as a `> -` line to the bots.
1da93116 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93116 [deepseek-v4] #Notable Strengths
1da93117 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93117 [deepseek-v4] #- Provider independence: The code handles both OpenAI‑compatible APIs (DeepSeek, xAI,
1da93117 [deepseek-v4] #Moonshot, Ollama) and Google/Anthropic bespoke endpoints.
1da93117 [deepseek-v4] #- Tool calling: The relay supports `function` tools (`readtime`, `submitfile`,
1da93118 [deepseek-v4] #etc.) and handles recursive calls when a model requests tools.
1da93118 [deepseek-v4] #- Cost tracking: Credits are updated per request, and tokens are logged and displayed.
1da93118 [deepseek-v4] #- Raw‑mode terminal: `slopprompt.ts` handles backspace, multi‑byte UTF‑8, shortcode
1da93118 [deepseek-v4] #expansion, and ANSI sequences on Windows/macOS/Linux.
1da93119 [deepseek-v4] #- In‑memory session stack: `/begin` and `/finish` allow pushing/popping conversation
1da93119 [deepseek-v4] #context – useful for experimental branching.
1da93119 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93119 [deepseek-v4] #Potential Improvements / Issues Noticed
1da9311a [deepseek-v4] #
1da9311a [deepseek-v4] #1. Verbose Logging in `slopbot.ts`
1da9311a [deepseek-v4] #The `splurt` function sends debug output to `console.error` on every message. This is fine for
1da9311a [deepseek-v4] #development, but in production you might want to:
1da9311b [deepseek-v4] #- Use a configurable log level (e.g., `if (splurtEnabled)`)
1da9311b [deepseek-v4] #- Or redirect to a file / discard when not debugging.
1da9311b [deepseek-v4] #
1da9311b [deepseek-v4] #The logs show `channel dump` and `guild` info being dumped on every incoming message – this
1da9311c [deepseek-v4] #adds latency (the `sleep(1500)` after each send is already there) and clutter.
1da9311c [deepseek-v4] #
1da9311c [deepseek-v4] #2. Race Condition in `slopPrompt.ts`
1da9311c [deepseek-v4] #The `receivePromises` map is updated inside a loop while reading. When a connection closes, the
1da9311d [deepseek-v4] #deletion `delete receivePromises[name]` may happen while another `Promise.race` is still awaiting
1da9311d [deepseek-v4] #that promise, leading to a `undefined` result. Consider using `AbortController` or a more robust
1da9311d [deepseek-v4] #“cancellable promise” pattern.
1da9311d [deepseek-v4] #
1da9311e [deepseek-v4] #3. DeepSeek‑V4 “reasoning” tokens
1da9311e [deepseek-v4] #The log shows `completiontokensdetails.reasoning_tokens: 204`. The relay prints the
1da9311e [deepseek-v4] #reasoning content if `reasonoutloud` flag is on, but currently it seems not to be displayed in the
1da9311e [deepseek-v4] #terminal output (only the final answer). That’s configurable (`roha.config.reasonoutloud`).
1da9311f [deepseek-v4] #
1da9311f [deepseek-v4] #4. File Sharing / Blob Handling
1da9311f [deepseek-v4] #The `commitShares` function reads entire text or image files into memory and sends them as base64.
1da9311f [deepseek-v4] #This works for small files, but `MaxFileSize` is defined as 512 KB, which might be large for some
1da93120 [deepseek-v4] #providers (Gemini has a 20 MB limit, but OpenAI’s vision models accept images up to ~20 MB).
1da93120 [deepseek-v4] #Consider respecting per‑model limits stored in `modelSpecs`.
1da93120 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93120 [deepseek-v4] #5. Unicode Width Calculation
1da93121 [deepseek-v4] #The `stringWidth` and `discordStringWidth` functions have hard‑coded wide/unwide ranges. This is
1da93121 [deepseek-v4] #fragile – the Unicode standard evolves (e.g., `🪣` U+1FAD3 was added in Unicode 15.0; your ranges
1da93121 [deepseek-v4] #stop at `0x1FAFF` so it’s correctly marked as wide). Consider using a library like `wcwidth` or
1da93121 [deepseek-v4] #`@std/unicode` instead.
1da93122 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93122 [deepseek-v4] #6. Hard‑coded `rohaTools`
1da93122 [deepseek-v4] #The function tools are defined in code, not loaded from a file. This makes it impossible to add new
1da93122 [deepseek-v4] #tools without recompiling. A plugin system (e.g., scanning a `tools/` directory) would be more
1da93123 [deepseek-v4] #flexible.
1da93123 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93123 [deepseek-v4] #7. Error Handling in `relay()`
1da93123 [deepseek-v4] #The `try/catch` block is large and catches many specific error messages. Some errors (like `429
1da93124 [deepseek-v4] #ratelimiterror`) are handled, but many generic errors just echo the message and stack. This
1da93124 [deepseek-v4] #could lead to silent failures. Better to re‑throw or log with severity levels.
1da93124 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93124 [deepseek-v4] #8. `pushonshare` flag
1da93125 [deepseek-v4] #In `flagNames` the key is `pushonshare` (note the extra `s`). In `emptyConfig` it’s `pushonshare` –
1da93125 [deepseek-v4] #but in the actual code, `/push` calls `commitShares` and then checks `if
1da93125 [deepseek-v4] #(roha.config.pushonshare)`. There’s a mismatch: the flag name in `flagNames` is `pushonshare` (with
1da93125 [deepseek-v4] #'s'), but in the code it's referenced as `roha.config.pushonshare` (missing 's'?). Let’s
1da93126 [deepseek-v4] #double-check:
1da93126 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93126 [deepseek-v4] #- `flagNames` line: `pushonshare : "emit a /push after any /share",`
1da93126 [deepseek-v4] #- `emptyConfig` line: `pushonshare:false,`
1da93127 [deepseek-v4] #They match. But in `callCommand` under `/push` or `/commit`: the code never reads
1da93127 [deepseek-v4] #`roha.config.pushonshare`; it only calls `commitShares`. Did you intend to use it? It seems the
1da93127 [deepseek-v4] #flag exists but isn’t activated anywhere else. Maybe it’s a leftover from an earlier version.
1da93127 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93128 [deepseek-v4] #9. Logging `outputBuffer` in `flush()`
1da93128 [deepseek-v4] #`flush()` writes to `stdout` and also sends the output to all connected bots via `slopBroadcast`.
1da93128 [deepseek-v4] #It does both even when the output is from the model’s reply (which already gets sent via
1da93128 [deepseek-v4] #`slopBroadcast` inside `relay()`). This results in duplicate messages reaching the bots (the model
1da93129 [deepseek-v4] #reply + the echoed `> -` lines). The logs show:
1da93129 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93129 [deepseek-v4] #
1da93129 [deepseek-v4] #[SLOPBOT] result: { message: '{"messages":[{"message":"\\r\\n### I'm doing well…","from":"🐋"}]}' }
1da9312a [deepseek-v4] #[SLOPBOT] result: { message: '{"messages":[{"message":"> - ꔀ nitrologic…","from":"slop"}]}' }
1da9312a [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312a [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312a [deepseek-v4] #Both arrive at the bot. That’s by design? It might be noisy.
1da9312b [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312b [deepseek-v4] #Summary
1da9312b [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312b [deepseek-v4] #The system works and is well‑structured for a research playground. The main improvements would be:
1da9312c [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312c [deepseek-v4] #- Reduce verbosity in bot logging (make it configurable).
1da9312c [deepseek-v4] #- Clean up the duplicate broadcast of model replies.
1da9312c [deepseek-v4] #- Reconsider the race conditions in the raw‑mode prompt reader.
1da9312d [deepseek-v4] #- Consider using an external unicode width library.
1da9312d [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312d [deepseek-v4] #Overall, it’s a solid foundation for testing and comparing many LLMs side‑by‑side.
1da9312d [deepseek-v4] #
1da9312e [deepseek-v4] #If you have a specific problem (e.g., a model not connecting, a crash, or a feature request), feel
1da9312e [deepseek-v4] #free to ask!
1da9312e [deepseek-v4] #
