1da96e41 [deepseek-v4] #The provided files describe Slop Relay (v1.8.2), a multi‑user, multi‑model research tool
1da96e41 [deepseek-v4] #for interacting with large language models. It supports multiple backends (DeepSeek, OpenAI,
1da96e42 [deepseek-v4] #Anthropic, Google, Moonshot, xAI, etc.) via SDKs or custom API wrappers, and includes a CLI prompt,
1da96e42 [deepseek-v4] #file sharing, tool (function) calling, speech synthesis, Discord bot integration, and logging with
1da96e42 [deepseek-v4] #a custom hexadecimal timestamp format (slopmarks).
1da96e42 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e43 [deepseek-v4] #Key observations:
1da96e43 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e43 [deepseek-v4] #- Architecture: The main application (`relay.ts`) manages a shared conversation history as
1da96e43 [deepseek-v4] #an array of `Plop` objects, routes prompts to the currently selected model, and handles tool call
1da96e44 [deepseek-v4] #loops recursively. A separate service (`slopprompt.ts`) provides raw‑mode input, remote connections
1da96e44 [deepseek-v4] #(TCP port 8081), and short‑code expansion. Discord bots (`slopbot.ts`) connect to the relay via TCP
1da96e44 [deepseek-v4] #to bridge Discord messages.
1da96e44 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e45 [deepseek-v4] #- Model Management: Accounts and pricing are configured in `accounts.json` and
1da96e45 [deepseek-v4] #`modelspecs.json`. Models are discovered on startup by querying each provider’s API. The active
1da96e45 [deepseek-v4] #model can be switched via `/model` in the CLI. Pricing is tracked in `roha.lode` (per‑account
1da96e45 [deepseek-v4] #credit) and `roha.mut` (per‑model usage).
1da96e46 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e46 [deepseek-v4] #- File Sharing: Users can share files or directories with `/share`, and commit them to
1da96e46 [deepseek-v4] #context with `/push` or `/commit`. Supported types include images (base64) and text. The relay also
1da96e46 [deepseek-v4] #supports tool calls for `readtime`, `submitfile`, `fetchfile`, and `tagslop`.
1da96e47 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e47 [deepseek-v4] #- Output Handling: Markdown is rendered to ANSI (with a custom `mdToAnsi` function), tables
1da96e47 [deepseek-v4] #are drawn with Unicode box‑drawing characters, and long content is chunked for Discord. A `flush()`
1da96e47 [deepseek-v4] #function aggregates output, logs it, and broadcasts to connected Discord bots.
1da96e48 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e48 [deepseek-v4] #- Unicode & Emoji: Extensive support for emoji, wide characters, and hieroglyphs is
1da96e48 [deepseek-v4] #provided via `slopspec.json` and `shortcode.json`. The `stringWidth` and `discordStringWidth`
1da96e48 [deepseek-v4] #functions account for platform‑specific display widths.
1da96e49 [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e49 [deepseek-v4] #- Potential Improvements:
1da96e49 [deepseek-v4] #  - The code is monolithic (128k in `relay.ts`); breaking it into modules would improve
1da96e49 [deepseek-v4] #maintainability.
1da96e4a [deepseek-v4] #  - Global mutable state (e.g., `rohaHistory`, `roha.config`) complicates testing and concurrent
1da96e4a [deepseek-v4] #usage.
1da96e4a [deepseek-v4] #  - Error handling in the relay loop is broad; more granular recovery (e.g., token limit, rate
1da96e4a [deepseek-v4] #limit) could be helpful.
1da96e4b [deepseek-v4] #  - The raw‑mode prompt (`slopprompt.ts`) uses a busy‑wait loop with `Promise.race`; a more
1da96e4b [deepseek-v4] #event‑driven approach might reduce CPU usage.
1da96e4b [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e4b [deepseek-v4] #- Purpose: This is clearly a research tool – the packed style, custom timestamp, and
1da96e4c [deepseek-v4] #“dunking large language models” tagline suggest it is used for comparative testing, prompt
1da96e4c [deepseek-v4] #engineering, and exploring model behaviours across providers.
1da96e4c [deepseek-v4] #
1da96e4c [deepseek-v4] #If you have specific questions about any component (e.g., how model selection works, how tool calls
1da96e4d [deepseek-v4] #are resolved, or how the Discord bridge operates), I’d be happy to explain further or show relevant
1da96e4d [deepseek-v4] #code snippets on request.
1da96e4d [deepseek-v4] #
