1dab3249 [deepseek-v4] #The provided `chroma.pio` appears to be a PIO program for generating the chroma (color burst)
1dab3249 [deepseek-v4] #component of a PAL 576i video signal on a Raspberry Pi Pico 2, clocked at 166.5 MHz with 10656
1dab3249 [deepseek-v4] #cycles per horizontal line.
1dab3249 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3249 [deepseek-v4] #Observations
1dab324a [deepseek-v4] #
1dab324a [deepseek-v4] #- IRQ synchronisation (`wait 1 irq 0` / `irq clear 0`): The program waits for an external
1dab324a [deepseek-v4] #trigger (IRQ 0) before processing, then clears it. This aligns with line‑by‑line video generation
1dab324a [deepseek-v4] #where a separate sync program likely fires IRQ 0 at the start of each active line.
1dab324b [deepseek-v4] #
1dab324b [deepseek-v4] #- Loop counter (`out x, 32` then `jmp !x start [16]`): The OSR (output shift register) is
1dab324b [deepseek-v4] #expected to hold a 32‑bit value that is shifted into `x`. If `x` is zero, the program jumps back to
1dab324b [deepseek-v4] #`start` (with a 16‑cycle delay, possibly to pad to line length). Otherwise it enters the `loop3837`
1dab324c [deepseek-v4] #routine.
1dab324c [deepseek-v4] #
1dab324c [deepseek-v4] #- Output pattern (`out pindirs, 9/8`): The eight `out pindirs` instructions shift 9 or 8
1dab324c [deepseek-v4] #bits from the OSR (or possibly from a different source – see note below) into the pin direction
1dab324d [deepseek-v4] #register.
1dab324d [deepseek-v4] #  Important: In PIO, `out pindirs` sets pin direction (1 = output, 0 = input). It
1dab324d [deepseek-v4] #does not directly set pin output values. For chroma generation, one typically needs to
1dab324d [deepseek-v4] #toggle a GPIO output level at the color subcarrier frequency (4.43361875 MHz for PAL). Using
1dab324e [deepseek-v4] #`pindirs` alone would only enable/disable the pin driver, not produce a waveform unless the pin is
1dab324e [deepseek-v4] #already configured as open‑drain or pull‑up/pull‑down – which seems unlikely for a clean colour
1dab324e [deepseek-v4] #burst.
1dab324e [deepseek-v4] #
1dab324f [deepseek-v4] #  More common techniques for colour burst in PIO include:
1dab324f [deepseek-v4] #  - Using `out pins` to set output values directly.
1dab324f [deepseek-v4] #  - Using `set pins` with side‑set.
1dab324f [deepseek-v4] #  - Combining `out pindirs` with a known initial output value (e.g., pin high and direction out
1dab3250 [deepseek-v4] #toggles the output? – actually direction change does not change the pin level; it only
1dab3250 [deepseek-v4] #enables/disables the output driver).
1dab3250 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3250 [deepseek-v4] #  The pattern of alternating 9 and 8 bits hints at a duty‑cycle variation (9 bits out of a 17‑bit
1dab3251 [deepseek-v4] #sequence?), but without a clear understanding of how the OSR is loaded the intent remains
1dab3251 [deepseek-v4] #ambiguous.
1dab3251 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3251 [deepseek-v4] #- Loop body structure: The eight `out pindirs` lines produce a pattern of three `9`s and
1dab3252 [deepseek-v4] #five `8`s? Counting:
1dab3252 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3252 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 9   (1)
1dab3252 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 8   (2)
1dab3253 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 9   (3)
1dab3253 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 8   (4)
1dab3253 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 9   (5)
1dab3253 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 8   (6)
1dab3254 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 8   (7)
1dab3254 [deepseek-v4] #  out pindirs, 8   (8)
1dab3254 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3254 [deepseek-v4] #  That’s 3×9=27 bits and 5×8=40 bits, totalling 67 bits per iteration. The loop then decrements `x`
1dab3255 [deepseek-v4] #and jumps back. If the OSR is 32 bits, shifting 67 bits per iteration would drain the OSR quickly –
1dab3255 [deepseek-v4] #implying the OSR must be refilled (perhaps via `pull` hidden in a side‑set or separate state
1dab3255 [deepseek-v4] #machine).
1dab3255 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3256 [deepseek-v4] #- End of line (`set pindirs, 0`): After the loop, all pin directions are set to input. This
1dab3256 [deepseek-v4] #likely disables the chroma output, leaving the line in a known state.
1dab3256 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3256 [deepseek-v4] #Potential Issues
1dab3256 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3257 [deepseek-v4] #1. No OSR load – The program assumes the OSR is already filled with data. In a typical PIO
1dab3257 [deepseek-v4] #video implementation, the colour burst pattern is pre‑loaded or pulled from TX FIFO. Without
1dab3257 [deepseek-v4] #explicit `pull` or `mov` to OSR, the burst will not be generated.
1dab3257 [deepseek-v4] #
1dab3258 [deepseek-v4] #2. Pin direction vs. pin level – As noted, toggling pin directions does not produce a
1dab3258 [deepseek-v4] #colour waveform unless the pins are configured with pull‑ups/-downs that create a voltage change
1dab3258 [deepseek-v4] #when direction changes. This is non‑standard and likely to produce incorrect timing.
