1dad9c8c [gemini-3.1-lite] #To get "Red" in PAL, you need to modulate the subcarrier phase. In the PAL system, the Red color
1dad9c8d [gemini-3.1-lite] #difference signal (V) is represented by the phase of the subcarrier.
1dad9c8d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c8d [gemini-3.1-lite] #Since you are using a 2-pin DAC, you are effectively creating a Quadrature Amplitude Modulation
1dad9c8d [gemini-3.1-lite] #(QAM) vector. To get a stable Red, you need to output a specific phase that the TV's decoder
1dad9c8e [gemini-3.1-lite] #will interpret as Red.
1dad9c8e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c8e [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. The Red Phase
1dad9c8e [gemini-3.1-lite] #For a standard PAL signal, the Red vector is at approximately 104° from the burst.
1dad9c8f [gemini-3.1-lite] #If your burst (which is at 135°) is your reference, you need to shift your sine-wave table to hit
1dad9c8f [gemini-3.1-lite] #that 104° target.
1dad9c8f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c8f [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. The Updated `initChroma` for Red
1dad9c90 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Instead of `0x55555555` (which is just a high-frequency square wave that the TV will likely reject
1dad9c90 [gemini-3.1-lite] #as noise), use a table that approximates the sine wave for the Red phase.
1dad9c90 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c90 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c91 [gemini-3.1-lite] #void initChroma() {
1dad9c91 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    // 4-step sine approximation for 2-pin DAC: 00, 01, 11, 10
1dad9c91 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    // We shift the array to set the phase.
1dad9c91 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    uint32_t sine[4] = {0, 1, 3, 2};
1dad9c92 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    uint32_t burst = 0x23102310;
1dad9c92 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c92 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    // Phase shift for RED (approx 104 degrees)
1dad9c92 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    // By starting at index 1 of the sine array, we create a phase shift
1dad9c92 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    int red_phase_offset = 1;
1dad9c93 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c93 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    for(int i = 0; i < colorWords; i++) {
1dad9c93 [gemini-3.1-lite] #        if(i < 3) {
1dad9c93 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            evenRed[i] = burst;
1dad9c94 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            oddRed[i] = burst;
1dad9c94 [gemini-3.1-lite] #        } else {
1dad9c94 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            uint32_t even_w = 0;
1dad9c94 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            uint32_t odd_w = 0;
1dad9c95 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            for(int b = 0; b < 16; b++) {
1dad9c95 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                int phase = ((i * 16 + b) + red_phase_offset) % 4;
1dad9c95 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                even_w |= (sine[phase] << (b * 2));
1dad9c95 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c96 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                // PAL V-flip: Invert the phase for odd lines
1dad9c96 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                // Swap 1 (01) and 2 (10)
1dad9c96 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                int s = sine[phase];
1dad9c96 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                if(s == 1) s = 2; else if(s == 2) s = 1;
1dad9c97 [gemini-3.1-lite] #                odd_w |= (s << (b * 2));
1dad9c97 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            }
1dad9c97 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            evenRed[i] = even_w;
1dad9c97 [gemini-3.1-lite] #            oddRed[i] = odd_w;
1dad9c98 [gemini-3.1-lite] #        }
1dad9c98 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    }
1dad9c98 [gemini-3.1-lite] #}
1dad9c98 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c99 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c99 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. Why this works:
1dad9c99 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• The Phase Shift: By changing `redphaseoffset`, you rotate the color hue. If the
1dad9c99 [gemini-3.1-lite] #red looks "orange" or "magenta," simply increment or decrement this offset (0, 1, 2, or 3) until it
1dad9c9a [gemini-3.1-lite] #looks like true Red.
1dad9c9a [gemini-3.1-lite] #• The V-Flip: The swapping of `1` and `2` in the `odd_w` loop is the "PAL" part of
1dad9c9a [gemini-3.1-lite] #the signal. It ensures that the V-axis (Red component) is inverted every other line, which is what
1dad9c9a [gemini-3.1-lite] #the TV's color decoder uses to cancel out phase errors.
1dad9c9b [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c9b [gemini-3.1-lite] #4. Hardware Adjustment
1dad9c9b [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Saturation: If the Red is too pale, your 2-pin DAC isn't swinging enough voltage.
1dad9c9b [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Hue: If the color is wrong, change the `redphaseoffset`.
1dad9c9c [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Burst: Keep the `burst` constant as `0x23102310` (or whatever phase your TV likes for the
1dad9c9c [gemini-3.1-lite] #burst reference).
1dad9c9c [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dad9c9c [gemini-3.1-lite] #• One final check:* Ensure that `CHROMA330PIN` and `CHROMA100PIN` are correctly
1dad9c9d [gemini-3.1-lite] #wired to the 330Ω and 100Ω resistors. If you swap those wires, the "weights" of your bits will be
1dad9c9d [gemini-3.1-lite] #reversed, and you will get a completely different (and likely non-functional) color phase.
1dad9c9d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
