1daf1c4e [gemini-3.1-lite] #This code presents a sophisticated implementation of a PAL video signal generator for the RP2350,
1daf1c4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #utilizing PIO state machines to handle the tight timing requirements of analog video signals.
1daf1c4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf1c4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #Observations on the Implementation
1daf1c4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf1c50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  PIO Architecture: Your use of multiple PIO blocks (`pio0`, `pio1`, `pio2`) to separate
1daf1c50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #concerns (Video/WST, Chroma/Audio, Keyboard) is a robust approach for managing the different
1daf1c50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #time-bases required for PAL broadcast standards.
1daf1c50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Chroma Encoding: The `initChroma` function correctly identifies the need for
1daf1c51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #phase-alternating line (PAL) logic by swapping the sine phases (1 and 2) to maintain the "V-flip"
1daf1c51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #requirement, which is essential for canceling phase errors in analog PAL decoding.
1daf1c51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  DMA Synchronization: Relying on `dmachannelis_busy` to trigger the next field
1daf1c51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #is standard practice; however, ensure that the `evenWords` and `oddWords` constants are precisely
