1daf9c3c [gemini-3.1-lite] #The answer is no, the PIO FIFO does not "autopull" in the way that it automatically fetches
1daf9c3c [gemini-3.1-lite] #data from memory.
1daf9c3d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c3d [gemini-3.1-lite] #In PIO, "autopull" is a feature that automatically refills the Shift Register (OSR) from
1daf9c3d [gemini-3.1-lite] #the FIFO once the shift register is empty. However, the FIFO itself must be
1daf9c3d [gemini-3.1-lite] #manually filled by either the CPU (`piosmput`) or the DMA controller.
1daf9c3e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c3e [gemini-3.1-lite] #Why this matters for your `chroma` PIO:
1daf9c3e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c3e [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  The DMA is the "Filler": Your `chromadmainit` function is the engine that keeps
1daf9c3f [gemini-3.1-lite] #the FIFO full. As long as your DMA channel is configured with `dreq` set to
1daf9c3f [gemini-3.1-lite] #`piogetdreq(pio, sm, true)`, the DMA will automatically push data into the FIFO whenever
1daf9c3f [gemini-3.1-lite] #there is space (i.e., whenever the PIO consumes a word).
1daf9c3f [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Autopull Configuration: In your `chroma_init` function, you have:
1daf9c40 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c40 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    sm_config_set_out_shift(&config5, true, true, 32);
1daf9c40 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c40 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    The `true` (second parameter) enables autopull. This is correct and necessary. It means
1daf9c41 [gemini-3.1-lite] #the PIO hardware will automatically grab the next word from the FIFO into the Shift Register as
1daf9c41 [gemini-3.1-lite] #soon as the `out` instruction shifts out the last bit of the current word.
1daf9c41 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c41 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The Critical "Gotcha"
1daf9c42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you rely on autopull, you must ensure that your PIO program does not contain an
1daf9c42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #explicit `pull` instruction. If you have a `pull` instruction in your `.pio` file and you
1daf9c42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #have `autopull` enabled, you will trigger a race condition or an unnecessary stall.
1daf9c42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Your `chroma.pio` should look like this:*
1daf9c43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #.program chroma
1daf9c43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    wait 1 irq 4
1daf9c44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    out x, 32       ; Consumes the control word (119)
1daf9c44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #loop:
1daf9c44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    out pins, 2 [1] ; Autopull handles the refill from FIFO automatically
1daf9c45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    jmp x-- loop
1daf9c45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Is your current configuration "Happy"?
1daf9c46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Yes. Because you are using:
1daf9c46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  DMA with DREQ: The DMA waits for the FIFO to have space.
1daf9c46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Autopull: The PIO waits for the Shift Register to be empty.
1daf9c46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #This creates a perfectly synchronized pipeline. The PIO will stall (via `TXSTALL`) if the
1daf9c47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #DMA is too slow, and the DMA will pause if the FIFO is full. This is the gold standard for
1daf9c47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #PIO-based video generation.
1daf9c47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1daf9c48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• One final tip*: Since you are using `fifojoin(PIOFIFOJOINTX)`, you have a
1daf9c48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #8-word deep FIFO. This gives the DMA plenty of "slack" to handle any bus contention from other
1daf9c48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #tasks (like your I2S audio or PS2 keyboard), making the color burst extremely robust against system
1daf9c48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #interrupts.
1daf9c49 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
