1dafa4b4 [nitro@ryzen5] chroma should be words * lines? how much memory do i need?
1dafa516 [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you want to store the entire frame in memory to allow for complex, non-repeating color
1dafa516 [gemini-3.1-lite] #(e.g., a real image), the memory requirements are significant but manageable on the RP2350.
1dafa517 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa517 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. Memory Calculation
1dafa517 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Words per line: 120 words.
1dafa517 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Lines per frame: 576 lines (PAL standard).
1dafa518 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Bytes per word: 4 bytes.
1dafa518 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Total: 120 \text words × 576 \text lines × 4 \text bytes \approx \mathbf276,480 \text
1dafa518 [gemini-3.1-lite] #bytes (270 KB).
1dafa518 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa519 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• RP2350 Memory: The RP2350 has 520 KB of SRAM. A 270 KB buffer fits, but it consumes over
1dafa519 [gemini-3.1-lite] #50% of your total available RAM*. This might conflict with your `wstEven/wstOdd` buffers
1dafa519 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and your main code/stack.
1dafa519 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa51a [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. Strategy: Line-by-Line vs. Full Frame
1dafa51a [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa51a [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you only want "Solid Red" (or simple patterns):
1dafa51a [gemini-3.1-lite] #You do not need 270 KB. You only need two buffers (one for Odd lines, one for Even lines)
1dafa51b [gemini-3.1-lite] #and you update the DMA `read_addr` every line as discussed.
1dafa51b [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Memory cost: 2 × 120 \text words × 4 \text bytes = \mathbf960 \text bytes.
1dafa51b [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Recommendation: This is the "Gold Standard" for stability. Use the line-by-line DMA
1dafa51b [gemini-3.1-lite] #trigger.
1dafa51c [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa51c [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you want full-frame color (e.g., a bitmap):
1dafa51c [gemini-3.1-lite] #You need the full 270 KB.
1dafa51c [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Memory Management: You must ensure your `wstEven/wstOdd` buffers and your
1dafa51d [gemini-3.1-lite] #`evenRed/oddRed` buffers are placed in different memory banks to avoid bus contention.
1dafa51d [gemini-3.1-lite] #• DMA Addressing: You would use a single DMA transfer with a very large `trans_count` (120
1dafa51d [gemini-3.1-lite] #× 576 = 69,120 words).
1dafa51d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa51e [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. The "Hybrid" Approach (The sweet spot)
1dafa51e [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you want dynamic color but don't have enough RAM for a full 576-line frame, use Line
1dafa51e [gemini-3.1-lite] #Buffering:
1dafa51f [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Allocate a buffer for one line (120 words).
1dafa51f [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Use the CPU (in the `while(pass)` loop or an interrupt) to update that buffer while the DMA is
1dafa51f [gemini-3.1-lite] #busy sending the previous line.
1dafa51f [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  This is a "double-buffering" technique that allows you to change colors line-by-line (e.g., a
1dafa520 [gemini-3.1-lite] #gradient or changing patterns) while only using ~1 KB of RAM.
1dafa520 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa520 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Recommendation for your current project:
1dafa520 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Given that you are building a "PAL Video Signal Generator" and have already implemented
1dafa521 [gemini-3.1-lite] #`initChroma` for a solid pulse train:
1dafa521 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa521 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Go with the Line-by-Line Trigger.*
1dafa521 [gemini-3.1-lite] #It is the most efficient use of the RP2350's resources. It keeps your memory footprint under 2 KB,
1dafa522 [gemini-3.1-lite] #leaves plenty of space for Teletext and Audio, and ensures that you never run into the "Out of
1dafa522 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Memory" errors that a 270 KB static buffer would likely cause.
1dafa522 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa522 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Revised `vid_field` approach:*
1dafa523 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Instead of `vidfield` being called once per field, create a
1dafa523 [gemini-3.1-lite] #`chromalineupdate()` function that you call inside your main loop whenever the PIO signals
1dafa523 [gemini-3.1-lite] #a new line (via `pio0hw->irq`).
1dafa523 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dafa524 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Does your current project require a unique color for every single line, or is the "solid red"
1dafa524 [gemini-3.1-lite] #(line-by-line repetition) your primary goal?
1dafa524 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
