1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing these well-structured files. They demonstrate a mature PAL video generator
1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #using RP2350 PIO and DMA. A few observations and potential issues come to mind.
1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #
1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #PIO Programs
1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #
1dafdd74 [deepseek-v4] #`chroma.pio`
1dafdd75 [deepseek-v4] #- The timing comment `4 cycles/bit (1 out + 1 delay + 1 jmp + 1 ?)` likely refers to the `jmp`
1dafdd75 [deepseek-v4] #taking 2 cycles when the condition is true (`y != 0`). So the loop body is `out` (1) + `jmp` (2) +
1dafdd75 [deepseek-v4] #`set` at wrap (1?) – but `set` executes only after the loop exits. In practice the inner loop is 3
1dafdd75 [deepseek-v4] #cycles per iteration (out+delay+jmp), and the `set` runs once after the outer loop. The `?` might
1dafdd76 [deepseek-v4] #indicate uncertainty whether `jmp` is 1 or 2 cycles; it’s 2 when taken.
1dafdd76 [deepseek-v4] #- The constant `burst = 0x23102310` encodes the 2-bit‑per‑sample colour burst pattern `10,11,01,10`
1dafdd76 [deepseek-v4] #(DAC values). This matches PAL burst at 4×subcarrier.
1dafdd76 [deepseek-v4] #- In `chromainit`, line 10 uses `wstprogramgetdefaultconfig` instead of
1dafdd77 [deepseek-v4] #`chromaprogramgetdefaultconfig`. This will compile only if the
1dafdd77 [deepseek-v4] #`chromaprogramgetdefault_config` function symbol is also available (e.g. via a
1dafdd77 [deepseek-v4] #`#define` in the generated header), but it’s safer to use the correct function.
1dafdd77 [deepseek-v4] #
1dafdd77 [deepseek-v4] #`vidbit.pio`
1dafdd78 [deepseek-v4] #- The line‑by‑line timing appears carefully calculated: hsync 786 cycles, back porch 964, active
1dafdd78 [deepseek-v4] #8642, front porch 258, summing to 10650 cycles – but the comment says 10656. The final `[12]` in
1dafdd78 [deepseek-v4] #`jmp x--,line` plus the three instructions before `.wrap` probably account for the 6‑cycle
1dafdd78 [deepseek-v4] #difference.
1dafdd79 [deepseek-v4] #- The vsync pulse train is generated by a separate small state machine (`pulse`, `phase`) that
1dafdd79 [deepseek-v4] #counts down `x` edge‑widths. The `out y,31` loads the pulse width from FIFO, and the inner `phase`
1dafdd79 [deepseek-v4] #loop generates that many cycles of output high. This is elegant because it allows arbitrary vsync
1dafdd79 [deepseek-v4] #pulse patterns.
