1dafdd7c [deepseek-v4] #With `colorWords = 120` and `colorWords*2 = 240` words (= 960 bytes), a ring size of 9 bits means
1dafdd7c [deepseek-v4] #the DMA address wraps after 512 bytes. The transfer will read the first 128 words (512 bytes), then
1dafdd7c [deepseek-v4] #wrap and repeat those same 128 words for the remaining 112 transfers. The last 112 words of
1dafdd7d [deepseek-v4] #`colorWord` are never sent. This is almost certainly unintended.
1dafdd7d [deepseek-v4] #
1dafdd7d [deepseek-v4] #If you want a continuous ring with no wrapping, use `ring = 10` (1024 bytes boundary) – but then
1dafdd7d [deepseek-v4] #the buffer of 960 bytes is smaller than the ring size, so no wrap occurs; the DMA will read
1dafdd7e [deepseek-v4] #addresses 0…959 correctly, but after wrapping (address 1024) it would go out of bounds. For a
1dafdd7e [deepseek-v4] #finite transfer count, ring is unnecessary. If you intended the chroma pattern to loop
1dafdd7e [deepseek-v4] #indefinitely, you should set the transfer count to an infinite value (e.g.,
1dafdd7e [deepseek-v4] #`dmachannelsettranscount(chromadmachan, UINT32_MAX, false)`) and use a ring
1dafdd7f [deepseek-v4] #size that exactly matches the buffer length (e.g., `ring = 10` if buffer is 1024 bytes, or ring = 9
1dafdd7f [deepseek-v4] #for 512 bytes). Given `colorWords=120`, you could reduce it to `colorWords=64` to fit a 512‑byte
1dafdd7f [deepseek-v4] #ring, or increase the buffer to 1024 bytes and use ring=10.
