1daffc99 [deepseek-v4] #• Explanation*:
1daffc9a [deepseek-v4] #- With ring size 10, the DMA’s internal address wraps after every 1024 bytes. Your buffer is
1daffc9a [deepseek-v4] #exactly 1024 bytes, so the DMA will cycle through indices 0–127 (even line) then 128–255 (odd line)
1daffc9a [deepseek-v4] #repeatedly.
1daffc9a [deepseek-v4] #- The PIO waits for irq 4 each line, reads the first word as repeat count, then outputs the next
1daffc9a [deepseek-v4] #127 words. The ring ensures that after one line’s data is consumed, the address wraps gracefully
1daffc9b [deepseek-v4] #for the next line.
1daffc9b [deepseek-v4] #- Because the transfer count is `UINT32_MAX`, the DMA never stops; it will keep feeding the PIO as
1daffc9b [deepseek-v4] #long as the PIO requests data.
1daffc9b [deepseek-v4] #
1daffc9c [deepseek-v4] #One more thing: ensure `colorWord[1]` is initialised (currently it’s not). The PIO will output it
1daffc9c [deepseek-v4] #as part of the burst? The first word consumed is repeat count (index 0), then it outputs words from
1daffc9c [deepseek-v4] #index 1 onward. You may want to set `colorWord[1]` to something meaningful (e.g., burst
1daffc9c [deepseek-v4] #continuation). If you leave it uninitialised, it will be random. Consider initialising all words.
1daffc9d [deepseek-v4] #
1daffc9d [deepseek-v4] #Let me know if you need help with the rest of the timing or field alternation.
1daffc9d [deepseek-v4] #
