1db02f32 [gemini-3.1-pro] #To get your RP2350 outputting a red PAL image instead of monochrome, we need to address a few
1db02f33 [gemini-3.1-pro] #critical timing and phase alignment issues. The TV's "color killer" circuit is currently disabling
1db02f33 [gemini-3.1-pro] #color decoding because the subcarrier frequency and the PAL burst sequence do not match the
1db02f33 [gemini-3.1-pro] #expected analog standards.
1db02f33 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f34 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is a breakdown of the specific areas causing the monochrome output and how to fix them.
1db02f34 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f34 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. PIO Loop Timing & Clock Divisor
1db02f34 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Your comment in `chroma.pio` states: `Loop: 4 cycles/bit (1 out + 1 delay + 1 jmp + 1 ?) = 4 cycles
1db02f34 [gemini-3.1-pro] #per 90-degree phase`.
1db02f35 [gemini-3.1-pro] #However, the PIO code is currently executing in 3 cycles:
1db02f35 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f35 [gemini-3.1-pro] #loop:
1db02f35 [gemini-3.1-pro] #	out	pins, 2 [1]  ; 1 cycle out + 1 cycle delay = 2
1db02f35 [gemini-3.1-pro] #	jmp	x-- loop     ; 1 cycle jmp = 1
1db02f36 [gemini-3.1-pro] #                     ; Total = 3 cycles
1db02f36 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f36 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because `clkdiv` is set to `9.3885` (17.734475 MHz, which is exactly 4 × f_sc), your loop outputs a
1db02f36 [gemini-3.1-pro] #phase every 3 cycles instead of 4, dropping the subcarrier frequency to ~1.47 MHz.
1db02f37 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f37 [gemini-3.1-pro] #To achieve 4 cycles per phase, you should increase the delay by 1, and speed up the PIO clock to 16
1db02f37 [gemini-3.1-pro] #× f_sc (70.9379 MHz) so that 4 PIO cycles equal exactly one 90-degree phase (56.38 ns).
1db02f37 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f37 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. DMA Consumption & Word Count (`x`)
1db02f38 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Currently, `colorWord[0]` is set to `colorWords - 1` (127). This means `x = 127`, so the PIO loop
1db02f38 [gemini-3.1-pro] #runs 128 times, consuming 256 bits (8 words) per scanline.
1db02f38 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because the DMA ring is 256 words long, the PIO will fall out of sync on the second scanline by
1db02f38 [gemini-3.1-pro] #reading active pixel data as the next `x` loop counter.
1db02f39 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f39 [gemini-3.1-pro] #A PAL scanline requires color for the back porch plus active video (~57.7μ s). At 4.4336 MHz, this
1db02f39 [gemini-3.1-pro] #is exactly 64 words of data (64 × 16 \text phases = 1024 \text phases). If we set `x =
1db02f39 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1023`, the PIO will consume exactly 64 words per line.
1db02f39 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f3a [gemini-3.1-pro] #3. Hex Literal for the Burst
1db02f3a [gemini-3.1-pro] #The value `0x23102310` places your desired sequence (2, 3, 1, 0) into hex nibbles. However, `out
1db02f3a [gemini-3.1-pro] #pins, 2` shifts out raw 2-bit pairs. To output the levels `0, 2, 3, 1` sequentially, the bits must
1db02f3a [gemini-3.1-pro] #be packed as `01 11 10 00` in binary, which is `0x78` per byte, or `0x78787878`.
1db02f3b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f3b [gemini-3.1-pro] #4. PAL Burst Alternation
1db02f3b [gemini-3.1-pro] #PAL (Phase Alternating Line) requires the color burst phase to swing \pm 45^\circ on alternate
1db02f3b [gemini-3.1-pro] #lines. You are currently using the exact same burst for both lines. The TV detects this lack of
1db02f3c [gemini-3.1-pro] #alternation and disables color. Shifting the sequence by one 90-degree phase on alternate lines
1db02f3c [gemini-3.1-pro] #creates the required 90-degree difference.
1db02f3c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1db02f3c [gemini-3.1-pro] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
