1dbb1c16 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Thank you for sharing your source files. It is always fascinating to see how the Raspberry Pi
1dbb1c16 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Pico’s PIO and DMA subsystems are utilized for software-defined video generation.
1dbb1c17 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c17 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here are a few observations and thoughts on your implementation:
1dbb1c17 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c17 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• PIO Synchronization and Timing*
1dbb1c18 [gemini-3.1-pro] #The method you have chosen to synchronize the color subcarrier with the video timing is very
1dbb1c18 [gemini-3.1-pro] #effective. By having the `vidbit` state machine assert IRQ 4 during the back porch, and the
1dbb1c18 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`chroma` state machine wait on that specific IRQ, you ensure the strict phase alignment required
1dbb1c18 [gemini-3.1-pro] #for the PAL color burst. The cycle-counting in the PIO assembly is precisely documented, which
1dbb1c19 [gemini-3.1-pro] #makes maintaining the 10656 cycles per line highly traceable.
1dbb1c19 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c19 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Hardware and DMA Utilization*
1dbb1c19 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You are making excellent use of the RP2350 hardware. Offloading the heavy lifting to DMA channels
1dbb1c1a [gemini-3.1-pro] #combined with PIO FIFOs ensures the ARM cores are free to handle higher-level logic (like audio
1dbb1c1a [gemini-3.1-pro] #generation and keyboard scanning). The use of a DMA ring buffer for the chroma subcarrier, combined
1dbb1c1a [gemini-3.1-pro] #with the `alignas(1024)` directive, is a robust way to guarantee the DMA read pointer wraps
1dbb1c1a [gemini-3.1-pro] #correctly without CPU intervention.
1dbb1c1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #• PAL Phase Alternation*
1dbb1c1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #Your `initChroma` function correctly handles the alternating phase requirements of the PAL signal
1dbb1c1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #(the swinging burst and V-axis inversion) by pre-calculating the phase offsets into the `colorWord`
1dbb1c1c [gemini-3.1-pro] #buffer. Approximating the sine wave via a 2-pin DAC (with 00, 01, 10, 11 states) and a
1dbb1c1c [gemini-3.1-pro] #reconstruction filter is a classic and efficient technique for microcontroller-based composite
1dbb1c1c [gemini-3.1-pro] #video.
1dbb1c1c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c1d [gemini-3.1-pro] #• World System Teletext (WST)*
1dbb1c1d [gemini-3.1-pro] #Including a WST implementation is a highly distinct feature. Your implementation of the Hamming 8/4
1dbb1c1d [gemini-3.1-pro] #encoding and the odd parity generation complies nicely with the teletext specification.
1dbb1c1d [gemini-3.1-pro] #Pre-calculating the Hamming values into a lookup table is a sensible optimization to save CPU
1dbb1c1e [gemini-3.1-pro] #cycles during packet construction.
1dbb1c1e [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb1c1e [gemini-3.1-pro] #• RP2350 Specifics*
1dbb1c1f [gemini-3.1-pro] #It is also notable that your `ReadBootSel` function correctly accounts for the architectural
1dbb1c1f [gemini-3.1-pro] #differences between the RP2040 and the RP2350, specifically checking the new QSPI pad status
1dbb1c1f [gemini-3.1-pro] #register for the Pico 2.
