1dbb479f [gemini-3.1-pro] #The removal of the `[16]` delay has perfectly aligned your breezeway, but the persisting
1dbb479f [gemini-3.1-pro] #black-and-white image points to two classic analog video hurdles: the PAL swinging burst
1dbb47a0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #requirement and DC-coupling offsets.
1dbb47a0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb47a0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is a breakdown of why the TV's color killer is still engaging and how to adjust your synthesis
1dbb47a0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #to fix it.
1dbb47a1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb47a1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. The Missing PAL "Swinging Burst"
1dbb47a1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #In your current `initChroma`, the `burst` constant is fixed (`0x23102310`) for both even and odd
1dbb47a1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #lines.
1dbb47a2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #A standard NTSC TV expects a fixed burst phase, but a PAL TV strictly requires the burst
1dbb47a2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #phase to swing by ±45° relative to the -U axis on every alternating line (135° then 225°). If the
1dbb47a2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #TV detects a fixed phase, its color killer circuit will assume the signal is either NTSC or noisy
1dbb47a2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #monochrome, and it will disable color decoding.
1dbb47a3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb47a3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. The Back Porch DC Offset
1dbb47a3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because your `CHROMA100` and `CHROMA330` pins are DC-coupled to the video output through resistors,
1dbb47a3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #any sequence you output directly adds to the video line's DC voltage.
1dbb47a4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• During blanking, your PIO sets the pins to `00` (0V).
1dbb47a4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Your current sine wave uses states `0, 1, 3, 2`. The average DC value of this sequence is heavily
1dbb47a4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #weighted towards 3.3V.
1dbb47a4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• When the burst fires, it creates a massive +0.6V "bump" on the back porch. The TV uses the back
1dbb47a5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #porch to clamp its black level. This massive bump likely exceeds the white level, causing the TV's
1dbb47a5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Automatic Gain Control (AGC) to completely clip or ignore the burst.
1dbb47a5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb47a5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #The Solution: A Balanced, Alternating Sequence
1dbb47a6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #We can solve both problems simultaneously by changing the chroma waveform to a balanced sequence:
1dbb47a6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`0, 1, 1, 0`.
1dbb47a6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #This sequence has a much lower DC average (minimizing the back porch bump) and a more standard
1dbb47a6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #peak-to-peak amplitude.
1dbb47a7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1dbb47a7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #By defining two different burst words that are shifted by 90° (`0x00110011` and `0x10011001`), they
1dbb47a7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #become perfectly symmetric around the mathematical average. The TV's PLL will lock to this average
1dbb47a7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #as the -U axis, satisfying the ±45° swing requirement perfectly.
