1dbd8b1a [kimi-k2.6] #`smconfigsetoutpins(&config5, CHROMA100_PIN, 2)` tells the PIO state machine which
1dbd8b1a [kimi-k2.6] #physical GPIO pins to drive when executing an `out pins, N` instruction.
1dbd8b1a [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1b [kimi-k2.6] #Specifically for your case:
1dbd8b1b [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1b [kimi-k2.6] #╭───────────────┬────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1dbd8b1b [kimi-k2.6] #│  Parameter    │  Value                 │  Meaning                                                      │
1dbd8b1c [kimi-k2.6] #├───────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1dbd8b1c [kimi-k2.6] #│  `out_base`   │  `CHROMA100_PIN` (20)  │  The first GPIO pin affected is **GP20**                      │
1dbd8b1c [kimi-k2.6] #│  `out_count`  │  `2`                   │  The instruction spans **2 consecutive pins**: GP20 and GP21  │
1dbd8b1c [kimi-k2.6] #╰───────────────┴────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1dbd8b1d [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1d [kimi-k2.6] #What it sets in hardware
1dbd8b1d [kimi-k2.6] #It writes the `PINCTRL` register fields for this state machine:
1dbd8b1d [kimi-k2.6] #• `OUT_BASE` (bits 19:15) = 20
1dbd8b1e [kimi-k2.6] #• `OUT_COUNT` (bits 24:20) = 2
1dbd8b1e [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1e [kimi-k2.6] #What happens at runtime
1dbd8b1e [kimi-k2.6] #When your PIO program executes:
1dbd8b1f [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1f [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b1f [kimi-k2.6] #out	pins, 2 [2]
1dbd8b1f [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b20 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b20 [kimi-k2.6] #The state machine takes the bottom 2 bits from the output shift register and drives them
1dbd8b20 [kimi-k2.6] #onto:
1dbd8b20 [kimi-k2.6] #• Bit 0 → GP20 (CHROMA100_PIN)
1dbd8b21 [kimi-k2.6] #• Bit 1 → GP21 (CHROMA330_PIN)
1dbd8b21 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b21 [kimi-k2.6] #What it does NOT do
1dbd8b21 [kimi-k2.6] #Importantly, this function only maps the destination of the `out pins` instruction. It does
1dbd8b22 [kimi-k2.6] #not:
1dbd8b22 [kimi-k2.6] #1.  Select the pin function. You still need `piogpioinit(pio, 20)` and
1dbd8b22 [kimi-k2.6] #`piogpioinit(pio, 21)` so those pins are connected to the PIO block rather than the SIO
1dbd8b22 [kimi-k2.6] #(CPU-controlled GPIO).
1dbd8b23 [kimi-k2.6] #2.  Set pin direction. You still need to configure those pins as outputs. You can do this
1dbd8b23 [kimi-k2.6] #from C with:
1dbd8b23 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b23 [kimi-k2.6] #    pio_sm_set_consecutive_pindirs(pio, sm, CHROMA100_PIN, 2, true);
1dbd8b24 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b24 [kimi-k2.6] #    or from PIO with a `set pindirs, 3` instruction. Your current `chroma.pio` does not contain any
1dbd8b24 [kimi-k2.6] #`pindirs` instructions, so if you have not set directions from C, GP20/GP21 may still be input pins
1dbd8b24 [kimi-k2.6] #even though the state machine is trying to drive them.
1dbd8b25 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b25 [kimi-k2.6] #Relationship to your other mapping
1dbd8b25 [kimi-k2.6] #You also have:
1dbd8b25 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b26 [kimi-k2.6] #sm_config_set_set_pins(&config5, CHROMA100_PIN, 2);
1dbd8b26 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b26 [kimi-k2.6] #
1dbd8b26 [kimi-k2.6] #This means both `out pins` and `set pins` in your PIO program affect the same two
1dbd8b27 [kimi-k2.6] #pins (GP20–GP21). So when `chroma.pio` executes `set pins, 0` to blank the output, it also drives
1dbd8b27 [kimi-k2.6] #both GP20 and GP21 low.
1dbd8b27 [kimi-k2.6] #
