1dbe6324 [nitro@ryzen5] if i only set the header with no erase some tv may just display blank until full pages?
1dbe637a [gemini-3.1-lite] #Yes, that is correct. Teletext decoders in televisions are stateful. If you send only a header (or
1dbe637a [gemini-3.1-lite] #a header with no valid data) and do not set the "Erase Page" (C4) flag or provide a full page of
1dbe637a [gemini-3.1-lite] #data, the TV will behave in one of three ways depending on its firmware:
1dbe637b [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe637b [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. The "Blank Page" Effect
1dbe637b [gemini-3.1-lite] #Most TV teletext decoders maintain a memory buffer for the page being "received." If you transmit a
1dbe637b [gemini-3.1-lite] #header (e.g., Page 100) but provide no body text, the decoder expects the subsequent packets to
1dbe637c [gemini-3.1-lite] #contain the contents for that page. If it receives no data for that page, it will either:
1dbe637c [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Keep the previous page: If you were previously viewing a page, it stays on screen.
1dbe637c [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Show a "Searching" screen: It may display "Page 100" in the top corner but show a blank
1dbe637c [gemini-3.1-lite] #or black screen because the memory buffer for that page is empty (or contains nulls).
1dbe637d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe637d [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. The Role of the C4 Flag
1dbe637d [gemini-3.1-lite] #In your `wstHeader` function, you currently have:
1dbe637d [gemini-3.1-lite] #`packet[p++] = HAMMING_84[0]; // C4=1: Erase Page`
1dbe637e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe637e [gemini-3.1-lite] #In the WST specification, the C4 Control Bit (bit 4 of the control byte) is the "Erase
1dbe637e [gemini-3.1-lite] #Page" flag.
1dbe637e [gemini-3.1-lite] #• If C4=1: The decoder clears the existing page in memory and prepares to receive new data
1dbe637f [gemini-3.1-lite] #for that page.
1dbe637f [gemini-3.1-lite] #• If C4=0: The decoder treats the incoming data as an update to the existing page.
1dbe637f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe637f [gemini-3.1-lite] #• If you send C4=1 without sending the body packets, you are telling the TV: "Clear
1dbe6380 [gemini-3.1-lite] #the current page and wait for new content."* If no content arrives, the TV will clear its memory
1dbe6380 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and show you a blank page.
1dbe6380 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe6380 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. How to avoid the "Blank" issue
1dbe6380 [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you want the TV to display something immediately, you have two options:
1dbe6381 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe6381 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Option A: The "Update" approach (C4=0)*
1dbe6381 [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you already have a page in the TV's memory, set the C4 flag to `0`. The TV will keep what it has
1dbe6381 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and only update the specific lines you send. This is how "live" news tickers work.
1dbe6382 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe6382 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Option B: The "Repetitive" approach (The standard way)*
1dbe6382 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Teletext is designed to be broadcast in a loop. You shouldn't just send the header once; you should
1dbe6382 [gemini-3.1-lite] #cycle through the header and the body packets repeatedly.
1dbe6383 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• If you send the header and the body (rows 1–24) repeatedly, the TV will populate the page memory,
1dbe6383 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and the image will stabilize.
1dbe6383 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• If you are currently only sending the header (as your code implies: `wstHeader(1, 0, 0, title32,
1dbe6383 [gemini-3.1-lite] #&wstEven[p]); p += 12;`), you are missing the `wstBody` packets that contain the actual text.
1dbe6384 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe6384 [gemini-3.1-lite] #How to verify your current output
1dbe6384 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Check your `initTeletext()`: You are calling `wstHeader` followed by `wstBody`. This is
1dbe6384 [gemini-3.1-lite] #correct.
1dbe6385 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  The "Blanking" Trap: If your `wstBody` contains only spaces or nulls, the TV will show
1dbe6385 [gemini-3.1-lite] #a "clean" page. Ensure your `line40` string has visible characters.
1dbe6385 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  Timing the loop: The TV needs to receive the full page (header + 24 rows) multiple
1dbe6386 [gemini-3.1-lite] #times to "lock" the page. If your DMA is only sending one header and one body row and then
1dbe6386 [gemini-3.1-lite] #stopping, the TV's decoder will time out and clear the screen because it thinks the transmission is
1dbe6386 [gemini-3.1-lite] #broken.
1dbe6386 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe6386 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• My recommendation:*
1dbe6387 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Ensure your `wstEven` and `wstOdd` buffers contain the entire page (Header + 24 rows of
1dbe6387 [gemini-3.1-lite] #text), not just the header and one row. If you send the full set of 25 packets (1 header + 24 rows)
1dbe6387 [gemini-3.1-lite] #repeatedly via the DMA loop, the TV will "paint" the page reliably. If you send only a partial
1dbe6387 [gemini-3.1-lite] #page, the decoder will likely reject it as incomplete or corrupted.
1dbe6388 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
