1dbe6989 [nitro@ryzen5] how many scnalines can i use per frame?
1dbe69e1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #In a standard PAL 625-line system, you have a specific budget of lines per field. Since you are
1dbe69e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #generating a 576i (interlaced) or 288p (progressive) signal, the limit is strictly defined by the
1dbe69e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Vertical Blanking Interval (VBI) and the Active Picture area.
1dbe69e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. The PAL 625-Line Budget
1dbe69e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #A full PAL frame consists of 625 lines (312.5 per field).
1dbe69e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• VBI (Vertical Blanking Interval): Typically occupies lines 1–22 and 313–335. This is
1dbe69e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #where your VSYNC, equalization pulses, and WST (Teletext) data live.
1dbe69e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Active Picture: This leaves 576 lines (288 per field) for visible video data.
1dbe69e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. Your Constraints
1dbe69e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #In your code, you have defined:
1dbe69e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #const int evenLines=305;
1dbe69e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #const int oddLines=304;
1dbe69e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #This is a total of 609 lines per frame. You are currently "missing" about 16 lines compared
1dbe69e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #to a broadcast 625-line signal.
1dbe69e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. How many can you actually use?
1dbe69e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #You can technically use as many lines as your `lineFrame` buffer can hold, but you are limited by
1dbe69e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #the DMA transfer size and the vertical retrace time.
1dbe69e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Maximum Lines: You can safely use up to 576 lines (288 lines per field) for
1dbe69e8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #active video.
1dbe69e8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• The "Safe" Zone: If you are targeting standard televisions, you should respect the VBI.
1dbe69e8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   Lines 1–22 (Field 1) and 313–335 (Field 2): Reserve these for VSYNC/HSYNC/WST.
1dbe69e8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   Lines 23–310 (Field 1) and 336–623 (Field 2): Use these for your active display.
1dbe69e9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69e9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #4. Technical Limitations
1dbe69e9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• DMA Transfer Limit: The RP2350 DMA `trans_count` is a 16-bit value, so you are well
1dbe69e9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #within the limit for line count (you could theoretically drive thousands of lines if you had the
1dbe69ea [gemini-3.1-lite] #SRAM).
1dbe69ea [gemini-3.1-lite] #• SRAM Budget: Each line takes `lineWords` (27 words = 108 bytes).
1dbe69ea [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   576 lines × 108 bytes ≈ 62 KB.
1dbe69ea [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   This fits easily in the RP2350's 520KB of SRAM.
1dbe69eb [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Vertical Retrace: If you add more lines, you must ensure your `vidbit` state machine
1dbe69eb [gemini-3.1-lite] #finishes the `line` loop and returns to the `vsync` state before the TV's horizontal sweep is lost.
1dbe69eb [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you exceed the field time (20ms for 50Hz), the TV will lose "vertical lock" and the image will
1dbe69eb [gemini-3.1-lite] #roll.
