1dbe69ed [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Standardize your field count: Set your field to 312 lines (even) and 313
1dbe69ed [gemini-3.1-lite] #lines (odd).
1dbe69ed [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   312 + 313 = 625 total lines.
1dbe69ed [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Adjust your `initFrame`:
1dbe69ee [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   Use lines 1–22 for VBI/WST.
1dbe69ee [gemini-3.1-lite] #    *   Use lines 23–310 for active video.
1dbe69ee [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  Check the "Visible" Area: Most older CRT TVs overscan. If you draw on lines 23 or 310,
1dbe69ee [gemini-3.1-lite] #they may be cut off. Line 30–300 is the "safe" active area.
1dbe69ef [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69ef [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Warning on Interlacing:*
1dbe69ef [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you use `video_lace=true`, remember that the lines in the `evenFrame` and `oddFrame` are
1dbe69ef [gemini-3.1-lite] #offset. The `oddFrame` lines must be shifted vertically by 0.5 lines relative to the
1dbe69f0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #`evenFrame` to achieve true interlacing. If you are just doing "progressive scan" in an interlaced
1dbe69f0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #container (288p), you can keep the lines identical, but ensure your `initFramei` function correctly
1dbe69f0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #maps the 288 rows into the 576-line interlaced structure.
1dbe69f0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1dbe69f1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Summary: You can use up to 576 lines for active display, but keep your total
1dbe69f1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #field count to 312/313 lines* to maintain the 50Hz vertical refresh rate required by PAL
