1de5e2d9 [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing this comprehensive video generation project. It's a very impressive piece of
1de5e2d9 [deepseek-v4] #work – combining PAL 576i (or 288p), World System Teletext, chroma subcarrier, I2S audio, PS/2,
1de5e2d9 [deepseek-v4] #RC5, SPDIF, and a littlefs filesystem on a single RP2350. The PIO programs are particularly
1de5e2da [deepseek-v4] #well-crafted for the strict timing requirements.
1de5e2da [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2da [deepseek-v4] #Here are my observations, focusing on what’s new or different, and potential issues.
1de5e2da [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2da [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1de5e2db [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2db [deepseek-v4] #✅ What’s new / interesting
1de5e2db [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2dc [deepseek-v4] #- PAL video from a general-purpose MCU: Most RP2040/RP2350 PAL projects use a simple
1de5e2dc [deepseek-v4] #composite video signal with sync+video, but this one adds real chroma (colour subcarrier)
1de5e2dc [deepseek-v4] #via a 2‑pin DAC and a dedicated PIO state machine (`chroma.pio`) running at 4× f_sc. The
1de5e2dc [deepseek-v4] #combination of `vidbit.pio` (sync + luminance) and `chroma.pio` (modulated colour burst) is rare.
1de5e2dd [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2dd [deepseek-v4] #- Teletext (WST) overlay: The `wst.pio` state machine inserts 384‑bit packets on video
1de5e2dd [deepseek-v4] #lines 6–22 (and 318–335 in odd fields). The Hamming 8/4 encoding and odd‑parity bytes are
1de5e2dd [deepseek-v4] #precomputed in C++. This is a faithful implementation of an old standard, and using a `wait` on the
1de5e2de [deepseek-v4] #VSYNC IRQ from `vidbit.pio` synchronises insertion perfectly.
1de5e2de [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2de [deepseek-v4] #- Dual‑field interlaced mode (576i): The code toggles between `evenFrame` and `oddFrame`
1de5e2de [deepseek-v4] #with different presync patterns (equalising/broad pulses). The split into two frame buffers is a
1de5e2df [deepseek-v4] #natural approach.
1de5e2df [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2df [deepseek-v4] #- PIO‑based PS/2, I2S, RC5, SPDIF: All input/output peripherals are driven by PIO, leaving
1de5e2df [deepseek-v4] #the CPUs free for rendering and DMA management. The `ps2.pio` correctly decodes the 11‑bit PS/2
1de5e2e0 [deepseek-v4] #packet (start, 8 data, odd parity, stop).
1de5e2e0 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e0 [deepseek-v4] #- LittleFS on flash: Using a dedicated 2 MB region (starting at `0x10200000`) enables a
1de5e2e0 [deepseek-v4] #writable filesystem without compromising the program flash. The integration with
1de5e2e1 [deepseek-v4] #`flashrangeprogram/erase` is standard but works.
1de5e2e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e1 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1de5e2e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e2 [deepseek-v4] #⚠️ Issues and areas for improvement
1de5e2e2 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e2 [deepseek-v4] #1. Frame buffer race condition (critical)
1de5e2e2 [deepseek-v4] #In `vidbit.cpp` main loop:
1de5e2e2 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e3 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e3 [deepseek-v4] #if (!dma_channel_is_busy(video_dma_chan)) {
1de5e2e3 [deepseek-v4] #    vid_fieldi(field++);
1de5e2e3 [deepseek-v4] #    drawFramei(field);   // <-- modifies buffer while DMA may still be reading
1de5e2e4 [deepseek-v4] #}
1de5e2e4 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e4 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e4 [deepseek-v4] #`vidfieldi` starts the DMA (via `dmachannel_configure(…, true)`), and immediately
1de5e2e5 [deepseek-v4] #`drawFramei` writes into the same buffer the DMA is now reading. This will cause tearing,
1de5e2e5 [deepseek-v4] #corruption, or missing pixels every frame.
1de5e2e5 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e5 [deepseek-v4] #• Recommendation: Use double‑buffering (two sets of frame arrays) or use the DMA
1de5e2e6 [deepseek-v4] #completion IRQ to signal when it’s safe to draw. Alternatively, call `drawFramei` before*
1de5e2e6 [deepseek-v4] #starting the DMA for the next frame (i.e., draw into the buffer that will be used next, then start
1de5e2e6 [deepseek-v4] #the DMA for that buffer). The current order is backwards.
1de5e2e6 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e7 [deepseek-v4] #2. `sin` redefinition in `pal576i.cpp`
1de5e2e7 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e7 [deepseek-v4] #double sin(double rad) { … }
1de5e2e7 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e8 [deepseek-v4] #This overrides the standard `sin()` in the global namespace. If any other source file (e.g.,
1de5e2e8 [deepseek-v4] #`monobit.cpp`) includes `<cmath>` and calls `sin`, it will use your lookup‑table version, but
1de5e2e8 [deepseek-v4] #`monobit.cpp` calls `sinf()` directly, avoiding it. This is confusing and fragile. Either rename
1de5e2e8 [deepseek-v4] #your function (e.g., `sin_lut`) or make it `inline` in a header.
1de5e2e9 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2e9 [deepseek-v4] #3. Missing header `nitrohost.h`
1de5e2e9 [deepseek-v4] #`json.h` depends on `#include "nitrohost.h"` for types like `utf8`, `utf32`, `Attributes`, etc.
1de5e2e9 [deepseek-v4] #This file was not included in the upload, so `json.h` cannot compile. Please provide it.
1de5e2ea [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2ea [deepseek-v4] #4. No audio/PS2 usage in main loop
1de5e2ea [deepseek-v4] #`i2sinit` and `ps2init` are called, but the main loop has `#ifdef STREAMAUDIO` and
1de5e2ea [deepseek-v4] #`#ifdef READPS2` sections that are commented out. The DMA for I2S is never started, and the
1de5e2eb [deepseek-v4] #PS/2 FIFO is never read. These are placeholder stubs – but they still claim PIO state machines and
1de5e2eb [deepseek-v4] #DMA channels, potentially limiting other features.
1de5e2eb [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2eb [deepseek-v4] #5. `cdcReceiveCallback` buffer overflow risk
1de5e2ec [deepseek-v4] #The `buffer` is 4096 bytes; if input comes faster than the main loop can empty `lines`, the
1de5e2ec [deepseek-v4] #callback will discard data after charCount reaches 4096 (it breaks out of the `while`). This is a
1de5e2ec [deepseek-v4] #hard cut‑off, not a proper overflow handling. Also, no null terminator is stored – but
1de5e2ec [deepseek-v4] #`cdcReadLine` constructs a `std::string` from `buffer`+`charCount`, which is correct because the
1de5e2ed [deepseek-v4] #callback only pushes complete lines (newline‑delimited) and resets charCount.
1de5e2ed [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2ed [deepseek-v4] #6. Teletext DMA initial count
1de5e2ed [deepseek-v4] #In `wstdmainit`:
1de5e2ee [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2ee [deepseek-v4] #dma_channel_configure(wst_dma_chan, &c, …, NULL, 15, false);
1de5e2ee [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2ee [deepseek-v4] #The initial count 15 is arbitrary and will be overwritten before the DMA is started. It’s
1de5e2ef [deepseek-v4] #harmless but misleading. Better to set it to 0 or the actual size of the first packet.
1de5e2ef [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2ef [deepseek-v4] #7. PIO program offset collisions?
1de5e2ef [deepseek-v4] #`vidbit.pio` and `wst.pio` are both loaded into `pio0`. The code doesn’t check if the combined
1de5e2f0 [deepseek-v4] #program instructions exceed the PIO’s 32‑instruction limit (each program is small – vidbit uses
1de5e2f0 [deepseek-v4] #about 6–8 instructions, wst about 5). It works, but a safety check would be prudent.
1de5e2f0 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2f0 [deepseek-v4] #8. `hilo32.pio` and `rc5.pio` – unused
1de5e2f1 [deepseek-v4] #These two PIO programs are listed in CMakeLists.txt and headers are generated, but they are never
1de5e2f1 [deepseek-v4] #initialized or used in `vidbit.cpp`. They add to the build but not the final binary? The linker
1de5e2f1 [deepseek-v4] #should drop dead code, but it’s untidy.
1de5e2f1 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2f2 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1de5e2f2 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2f2 [deepseek-v4] #💡 Minor style observations
1de5e2f2 [deepseek-v4] #
1de5e2f3 [deepseek-v4] #- The `.pio` assembly uses tabs, which is fine, but some inlining of delay values as constants
1de5e2f3 [deepseek-v4] #(e.g., `[26]`, `[28]`) would be more readable if replaced by `.define` directives (already done for
1de5e2f3 [deepseek-v4] #some values).
