1deb64d5 [deepseek-v4] #The shared files constitute a complete embedded project—vidbit—for an RP2350-based PAL
1deb64d5 [deepseek-v4] #video signal generator with additional teletext, chroma, audio, and PS/2 input features. Below is a
1deb64d5 [deepseek-v4] #professional review of the content, highlighting novel aspects, potential improvements, and
1deb64d6 [deepseek-v4] #observations.
1deb64d6 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64d6 [deepseek-v4] #Project Overview
1deb64d6 [deepseek-v4] #- Purpose: Generate PAL 576i (and 288P) video with software-rendered graphics, World System
1deb64d7 [deepseek-v4] #Teletext (WST), colour subcarrier, I²S audio output, and PS/2 keyboard input.
1deb64d7 [deepseek-v4] #- Hardware Target: Raspberry Pi Pico 2 (RP2350) with a custom DAC ladder for luminance and
1deb64d7 [deepseek-v4] #chrominance.
1deb64d7 [deepseek-v4] #- Build System: CMake with Ninja (Windows `.bat`) and shell scripts (Linux `.sh`). All PIO
1deb64d7 [deepseek-v4] #programs are compiled via `picogeneratepio_header`.
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #Standout Elements
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #1. PIO Programs
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #- vidbit.pio – Line-synchronised video timing using a main line loop, sync pulses, back
1deb64d8 [deepseek-v4] #porch, active video (864 pixels), and front porch. Uses `out pindirs` with variable delay to drive
1deb64d9 [deepseek-v4] #a single-bit output (luma).
1deb64d9 [deepseek-v4] #- chroma.pio – 2-bit DAC output for PAL colour burst and modulated chroma. Runs at ~17.7
1deb64d9 [deepseek-v4] #MHz (4× f_sc) and generates two full colour cycles per 8‑bit FIFO entry. The approach of encoding
1deb64d9 [deepseek-v4] #2‑bit phase pairs is novel and efficient.
1deb64da [deepseek-v4] #- wst.pio – Teletext data insertion triggered by an IRQ from the video PIO. Each word
1deb64da [deepseek-v4] #carries 384 bits at 6.9375 Mbps. This integration is rarely seen in hobbyist projects.
1deb64da [deepseek-v4] #- rc5.pio – Pulse-width measurement for an infrared sensor (flame detector) using 32‑bit
1deb64da [deepseek-v4] #counters. Interesting addition for data acquisition.
1deb64da [deepseek-v4] #- i2s.pio – 16‑bit stereo I²S output at 48 kHz, using bit‑banged timing at 150 MHz.
1deb64db [deepseek-v4] #- ps2.pio – PS/2 keyboard decoder with parity and stop‑bit handling.
1deb64db [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64db [deepseek-v4] #2. DMA‑Driven Rendering
1deb64db [deepseek-v4] #- The main loop uses DMA to stream pre‑rendered framebuffers (`evenFrame`, `oddFrame`, or
1deb64dc [deepseek-v4] #`progressiveFrame`) into the PIO TX FIFO.
1deb64dc [deepseek-v4] #- Teletext data is also DMA’d from separate arrays (`wstEven`, `wstOdd`) and synchronised via video
1deb64dc [deepseek-v4] #line IRQs.
1deb64dc [deepseek-v4] #- Chroma data is transferred via a ring‑buffered DMA channel (`colorWord` array) to maintain
1deb64dc [deepseek-v4] #continuous subcarrier phase.
1deb64dd [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64dd [deepseek-v4] #3. Rendering and Typography
1deb64dd [deepseek-v4] #- monobit.cpp – Implements a 864‑pixel wide monochrome framebuffer with C64‑style bitmap
1deb64dd [deepseek-v4] #font. Functions `rect`, `plot`, `text` operate directly on the framebuffer.
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #- pal576i.cpp – Interlaced rendering using two separate framebuffers (even/odd fields).
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #Drawing functions are duplicated with `i` suffix (`ploti`, `recti`). This duplication could be
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #refactored into a field‑aware abstraction.
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #4. Filesystem and Utility
1deb64de [deepseek-v4] #- fs.cpp – LittleFS file system on external (or internal) flash at `0x10200000` (2 MiB
1deb64df [deepseek-v4] #offset). Provides wear‑leveled storage.
1deb64df [deepseek-v4] #- json.h – A custom JSON parser / serializer (ECMA‑404) used for configuration or data
1deb64df [deepseek-v4] #exchange. Note: the implementation uses deprecated `wstringconvert` (C++17) and lacks proper
1deb64df [deepseek-v4] #UTF‑8 handling for `wchart`. Consider replacing with a standards‑compliant library (e.g.,
1deb64df [deepseek-v4] #`nlohmann/json` or a hand‑rolled UTF‑8 parser).
1deb64e0 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e0 [deepseek-v4] #5. Build and Hardware
1deb64e0 [deepseek-v4] #- build.bat / build.sh – Cross‑platform CMake invocation. The `.bat` copies `.uf2` to `E:`
1deb64e0 [deepseek-v4] #drive (likely Pico mounted as USB mass storage). The `.sh` copies to `/Volumes/RP2350` (macOS).
1deb64e0 [deepseek-v4] #- CMakeLists.txt – Correctly includes SDK, PIO generators, and disables deprecated reset
1deb64e1 [deepseek-v4] #methods. Note: `PICOSTDIOUSBENABLERESETVIAVENDOR_INTERFACE` is spelled with
1deb64e1 [deepseek-v4] #`INTERFACE` (should be `INTERFACE`? The SDK uses `INTERFACE`, but both are defined – harmless).
1deb64e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e1 [deepseek-v4] #Potential Issues & Suggestions
1deb64e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e2 [deepseek-v4] #Code Quality
1deb64e2 [deepseek-v4] #- Global mutable state – Large arrays (`evenFrame`, `oddFrame`, `colorWord`) are defined as
1deb64e2 [deepseek-v4] #`uint32_t [...]` without `constexpr` or `const`. Their contents are modified at runtime. Ensure
1deb64e2 [deepseek-v4] #alignment (`alignas(1024)`) for DMA is respected (already done for `colorWord`).
1deb64e3 [deepseek-v4] #- Spin lock in interrupt – `cdcReceiveCallback` calls `spinlockblocking` from a USB
1deb64e3 [deepseek-v4] #callback. This is safe as long as the lock is not held for long, but the critical section should be
1deb64e3 [deepseek-v4] #minimal. The current buffer handling may drop data if the lock is contended.
1deb64e3 [deepseek-v4] #- Deprecated `std::wstringconvert` – `json.h` uses
1deb64e3 [deepseek-v4] #`std::wstringconvert<std::codecvtutf8<wchart>>`. This class is deprecated in C++17 and
1deb64e4 [deepseek-v4] #removed in C++20. Replace with a simple UTF‑8 to UTF‑32 conversion (e.g., manual byte‑by‑byte
1deb64e4 [deepseek-v4] #decode) or use a library.
1deb64e4 [deepseek-v4] #- Potential name collision – `NotAnInt` and `NotANumber` are macros defined in `json.h`;
1deb64e4 [deepseek-v4] #they could conflict with other code. Use `constexpr` or `enum` instead.
1deb64e4 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #Hardware / PIO
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #- IRQ handshake mismatch – `vidbit.pio` sets IRQ 0 at the start of active video (`irq set
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #0`). `wst.pio` waits for IRQ 0. `chroma.pio` waits for IRQ 4 and clears IRQ 4. There is no mention
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #of IRQ 4 being set elsewhere. Either `chroma.pio` is intended to be triggered by a different
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #mechanism, or the IRQ number is wrong. Consider adding a `wait`/`irq` handshake in the video PIO
1deb64e5 [deepseek-v4] #for chroma.
1deb64e6 [deepseek-v4] #- `vidinit` sets `smconfigsetset_pins` with 1 pin, but `vidbit.pio` uses both `set
1deb64e6 [deepseek-v4] #pins` and `set pindirs` on the same pin – this is fine because `pindirs` controls direction, `pins`
1deb64e6 [deepseek-v4] #controls output level.
1deb64e6 [deepseek-v4] #- Teletext line count – `wstEven` has 305+12*2 = 329 words, but the DMA transfer count is
1deb64e7 [deepseek-v4] #set to `wstWords` (329) for even and `wstWords-1` (328) for odd. This may cause a line length
1deb64e7 [deepseek-v4] #mismatch. Verify that the number of words exactly fills the required lines (including the
1deb64e7 [deepseek-v4] #header/body lines) and that the odd field has one fewer line (304 vs 305).
1deb64e7 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e8 [deepseek-v4] #Performance
1deb64e8 [deepseek-v4] #- Chroma generation uses a pre‑computed sine table (`sin4[4096]`). The `sin` function in
1deb64e8 [deepseek-v4] #`pal576i.cpp` uses a lookup with `int i4=rad*2048/M_PI;` – this introduces a multiplication and
1deb64e8 [deepseek-v4] #division per pixel. For real‑time chroma modulation, consider using a direct digital synthesis
1deb64e9 [deepseek-v4] #(DDS) approach with incremental phase.
1deb64e9 [deepseek-v4] #- The main loop busy‑waits for DMA completion and polls debug flags. This is acceptable for a demo
1deb64e9 [deepseek-v4] #but could be improved with DMA interrupt callbacks for lower CPU usage.
1deb64e9 [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64e9 [deepseek-v4] #Conclusion
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #The vidbit project is a sophisticated, feature‑rich video generator that demonstrates deep
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #integration of PIO, DMA, and custom rendering. The code is well‑structured overall, with clear
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #separation of modules. Main areas for refinement are the JSON parser’s portability, the
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #teletext/chroma IRQ coordination, and the rendering duplication between progressive and interlaced
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #modes. The inclusion of teletext and chroma colour is particularly impressive for a
1deb64ea [deepseek-v4] #microcontroller‑based video system.
1deb64eb [deepseek-v4] #
1deb64eb [deepseek-v4] #If you have specific questions or would like assistance with any part of the code (e.g., improving
1deb64eb [deepseek-v4] #the JSON parser, refactoring rendering into a single abstraction, or fixing the IRQ handshake),
1deb64eb [deepseek-v4] #please let me know.
1deb64eb [deepseek-v4] #
