1e16f39d [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because 432 is not a power of 2 (it sits between 256 and 512), you cannot use the hardware ring to
1e16f39d [gemini-3.1-pro] #wrap perfectly back to the start of this specific buffer. If you set it to 9 (512 bytes), the DMA
1e16f39d [gemini-3.1-pro] #will read past the end of your 432-byte array and into uninitialized memory before wrapping.
1e16f39d [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e16f39e [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. The Ring Direction Boolean*
1e16f39e [gemini-3.1-pro] #In your current code, you have:
1e16f39e [gemini-3.1-pro] #`channelconfigset_ring(&c, true, 9);`
1e16f39e [gemini-3.1-pro] #The boolean parameter specifies which address gets wrapped. `true` applies the ring to the
1e16f39f [gemini-3.1-pro] #write address. Since you are writing to the PIO TX FIFO (where `write_increment` is already
1e16f39f [gemini-3.1-pro] #`false`), this ring setting essentially does nothing. If you ever want to ring a source buffer,
1e16f39f [gemini-3.1-pro] #that parameter must be `false` (apply to the read address).
