1e17007b [gemini-3.1-pro] #I see the clever workaround you are aiming for with `colorPumpStride=128`! Bumping the array size
1e17007b [gemini-3.1-pro] #to a power of 2 is the standard way to force compatibility with the DMA ring hardware.
1e17007b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e17007b [gemini-3.1-pro] #However, there are a few parameter corrections needed to make the DMA ring function properly, and a
1e17007c [gemini-3.1-pro] #logical "gotcha" regarding the video timing that we should discuss.
1e17007c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e17007c [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. The Ring Parameters (Both DMA channels)
1e17007c [gemini-3.1-pro] #The `channelconfigsetring` function takes `(config, write, sizebits)`:
1e17007d [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `write`: You currently have this set to `true`. This tells the DMA to wrap the
1e17007d [gemini-3.1-pro] #write address. Since you are writing to the PIO's TX FIFO (a single, non-incrementing
1e17007d [gemini-3.1-pro] #address), wrapping it does nothing. You need to wrap the read address (your memory array),
1e17007d [gemini-3.1-pro] #so this must be `false`.
1e17007e [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `size_bits`: This is calculated in bytes, not words.
1e17007e [gemini-3.1-pro] #    *   Colorpump: 128 words × 4 bytes = 512 bytes. 2⁹ = 512. The size should be
1e17007e [gemini-3.1-pro] #`9` (not `7`).
1e17007e [gemini-3.1-pro] #    *   Chroma: `colorWord` is 256 words (128 even + 128 odd) × 4 bytes = 1024 bytes. 2^10
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #= 1024. The size should be `10` (not `9`).
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is what those lines should look like:
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #// In chroma_dma_init:
1e17007f [gemini-3.1-pro] #channel_config_set_ring(&c, false, 10); // 1024 byte ring on read address
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #// In colorpump_dma_init:
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #channel_config_set_ring(&c, false, 9);  // 512 byte ring on read address
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170080 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. The "Stride" Drift Issue
1e170081 [gemini-3.1-pro] #While making `colorTest` 128 words satisfies the DMA hardware, it introduces a desync with your PIO
1e170081 [gemini-3.1-pro] #state machine.
1e170081 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170081 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Your `colorpump.pio` is pre-loaded with `863` in the `y` register, meaning it consumes exactly
1e170081 [gemini-3.1-pro] #864 pixels (which is exactly 108 words) every time `irq 5` fires for a new video
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #line.
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #If your DMA ring is 128 words long, here is what happens:
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Line 1: PIO consumes words 0 through 107.
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Line 2: PIO consumes words 108 through 127, the DMA wraps to 0, and the PIO consumes
1e170082 [gemini-3.1-pro] #words 0 through 87.
1e170083 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Line 3: PIO consumes words 88 through 127... and so on.
1e170083 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170083 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because 108 does not divide evenly into 128, your color pattern will shift horizontally by 20 words
1e170083 [gemini-3.1-pro] #(160 pixels) on every single scanline.
1e170084 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e170084 [gemini-3.1-pro] #How to fix the drift:
1e170084 [gemini-3.1-pro] #If your goal is to have a static 1-line color test pattern that repeats perfectly on every
