1e171840 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Since the hardware DMA ring is strictly limited to power-of-2 boundaries, you cannot natively loop
1e171840 [gemini-3.1-pro] #a 108-word buffer. However, if you want to repeatedly send a small buffer without allocating a full
1e171840 [gemini-3.1-pro] #frame of memory, there are three excellent ways to handle this.
1e171840 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e171840 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here are the best alternatives, ranked by how well they fit your current architecture:
1e171841 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e171841 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. The "Padded Ring" (Hardware Only, Zero CPU)
1e171841 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Since you are already controlling the exact pixel count inside your PIO state machine, you can
1e171841 [gemini-3.1-pro] #"trick" the DMA ring into working perfectly by padding your buffer.
1e171842 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• The Buffer: Size your `colorTest` array to 128 words (which allows a perfect hardware
1e171842 [gemini-3.1-pro] #ring of 2⁹ / 512 bytes). Fill the first 108 words with your color data, and the remaining 20 words
1e171842 [gemini-3.1-pro] #with zeros (or any dummy data).
1e171842 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• The PIO: Modify `colorpump.pio` so that after it finishes its active loop of 864 pixels
1e171843 [gemini-3.1-pro] #(108 words), it enters a second, brief loop. This second loop executes 160 times (the remaining 20
1e171843 [gemini-3.1-pro] #words × 8 pixels) doing nothing but `out null, 4` to silently consume the padded data.
1e171843 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• The Result: The DMA hardware ring wraps perfectly at 128 words, the PIO stays perfectly
1e171843 [gemini-3.1-pro] #synced to your video lines via `irq 5`, and the CPU does absolutely nothing.
1e171844 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e171844 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. DMA Chaining (The "Official" Microcontroller Way)
1e171844 [gemini-3.1-pro] #If you strictly want to keep your buffer at 108 words, you can use a second DMA channel to act as a
1e171844 [gemini-3.1-pro] #"rewind mechanism."
1e171845 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• How it works: You set up an unused DMA channel (let's call it the Control Channel). You
1e171845 [gemini-3.1-pro] #configure your Color DMA channel so that when it finishes transferring its 108 words, it
1e171845 [gemini-3.1-pro] #automatically triggers the Control Channel.
1e171845 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• The Control Channel: This channel is configured to transfer exactly one 32-bit
1e171846 [gemini-3.1-pro] #word. It reads the memory address of `colorTest` and writes it directly into the
1e171846 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`READADDRTRIG` register of the Color DMA channel.
