1e176760 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176760 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 1. The Perfect 10-Cycle Pixel*
1e176760 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Your system clock is 166.5 MHz, and you previously noted 10 cycles per pixel. Your `colorfifo`
1e176760 [gemini-3.1-pro] #state machine executes exactly 10 instructions per pixel block once the trigger drops:
1e176761 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `jmp pin stall` (Waits for the trigger, consumes 1 cycle when falling through)
1e176761 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `mov y, pins` (1 cycle)
1e176761 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `mov osr, rxfifo[y]` (1 cycle)
1e176761 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `out pindirs, 3` × 6 (6 cycles)
1e176762 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `set pindirs, 0` (1 cycle)
1e176762 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• (Total = 10 cycles).* This guarantees your color generation stays perfectly phase-locked to the
1e176762 [gemini-3.1-pro] #pixel clock.
1e176762 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176763 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. RP2350 Indexed FIFOs*
1e176763 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Using `mov osr, rxfifo[y]` is a brilliant application of the RP2350's new ability to index the FIFO
1e176763 [gemini-3.1-pro] #directly. By pre-loading 4 words into the RX FIFO during initialization, you have effectively
1e176763 [gemini-3.1-pro] #turned the FIFO into a zero-wait-state lookup table. The 2-bit color index read from `pins`
1e176764 [gemini-3.1-pro] #instantly selects one of the 4 pulse trains.
1e176764 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176764 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 3. The 18-Bit Payload*
1e176764 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You are doing six `out pindirs, 3` instructions, meaning each wave train consumes 18 bits of the
1e176765 [gemini-3.1-pro] #32-bit word.
