1e176e99 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Ah, that circuit snippet perfectly explains why you are modulating `pindirs` instead of the pin
1e176e99 [gemini-3.1-pro] #output values!
1e176e99 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e99 [gemini-3.1-pro] #By keeping the pin output state permanently at `0` (which you do in your C++ setup) and toggling
1e176e9a [gemini-3.1-pro] #the direction, you are using the RP2350 pins as Open-Drain outputs. The pin is rapidly
1e176e9a [gemini-3.1-pro] #switching between High-Z (Input) and Strong Ground (Output Low).
1e176e9a [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e9a [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is the math on how your wave train translates into analog voltages for the Pb/Pr lines:
1e176e9b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e9b [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 1. The Two Voltage States*
1e176e9b [gemini-3.1-pro] #• State 0 (Bit = 0, High-Z): The pin is floating. The voltage at the TV is purely a voltage
1e176e9b [gemini-3.1-pro] #divider between your 80 Ω pull-up to 3.3V and the TV's internal 75 Ω termination to ground.
1e176e9c [gemini-3.1-pro] #    *   V_High = 3.3V × 75⁄80 + 75 \approx \mathbf1.59V
1e176e9c [gemini-3.1-pro] #• State 1 (Bit = 1, Drive Low): The pin goes to 0V. Your 150 Ω resistor is now in parallel
1e176e9c [gemini-3.1-pro] #with the TV's 75 Ω termination (150 || 75 = 50 Ω).
1e176e9d [gemini-3.1-pro] #    *   V_Low = 3.3V × 50⁄80 + 50 \approx \mathbf1.27V
1e176e9d [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e9d [gemini-3.1-pro] #This gives you an analog swing of roughly 0.32V. Because component video inputs on TVs are
1e176e9d [gemini-3.1-pro] #typically AC-coupled, the TV ignores the ~1.4V DC offset and only sees the ±0.16V AC swing around
1e176e9e [gemini-3.1-pro] #its own bias point.
1e176e9e [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e9e [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. The 166.5 MHz PDM (Pulse Density Modulation)*
1e176e9e [gemini-3.1-pro] #This is where your PIO wave train is brilliant.
1e176e9f [gemini-3.1-pro] #Your `colorfifo` state machine executes `out pindirs, 3` six times in a row, with no delays, at the
1e176e9f [gemini-3.1-pro] #system clock rate of 166.5 MHz.
1e176e9f [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176e9f [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because standard video bandwidth is only a few megahertz, the TV (and the capacitance of the RCA
1e176ea0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #cable) acts as a low-pass filter. The TV cannot see the individual 166.5 MHz pulses; it only sees
1e176ea0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #the average voltage over the 10-cycle pixel window.
1e176ea0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176ea0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• Out of your 10-cycle pixel, the last 4 cycles are forced to High-Z by the `set pindirs, 0` and
1e176ea1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #the loop overhead.
1e176ea1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• The first 6 cycles are entirely programmable via your 18-bit wave train payload.
1e176ea1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176ea1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #This means for any single pixel, you can choose to pull the pin Low for 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, or 6 of
1e176ea2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #those cycles.
1e176ea2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176ea2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You have essentially built a high-speed DAC that gives you 7 discrete analog voltage levels per
1e176ea2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #channel (Y, Pb, Pr) per pixel, just by changing the ratio of 1s and 0s in your 6-bit sequence!
1e176ea3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e176ea3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Am I correct that the `color_trains[]` array will eventually hold the pre-calculated bit patterns
1e176ea3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #to mix the specific Y, Pb, and Pr voltages needed for a specific palette of 16 colors?
1e176ea3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
