1e190171 [gemini-3.1-pro] #A couple of quick observations on this latest version before you fire it up on the hardware:
1e190171 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e190172 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 1. Solid Color vs. Noise*
1e190172 [gemini-3.1-pro] #I noticed that the `noise2()` loop is still active inside `colorpump_init()`:
1e190172 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e190172 [gemini-3.1-pro] #for(int i=0;i<colorpumpCount;i++){
1e190173 [gemini-3.1-pro] #    colorTest[i]=noise2();
1e190173 [gemini-3.1-pro] #}
1e190173 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e190173 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because of this loop, your screen will display 16-color static (snow) rather than a solid color. If
1e190174 [gemini-3.1-pro] #your goal for this initial test is to see a single, solid color across the whole screen (for
1e190174 [gemini-3.1-pro] #example, your grey at index 0), you should comment out that `for` loop. Without the loop,
1e190174 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`colorTest` defaults to all `0`s, which will continuously feed `color_trains[0]` to the output.
1e190174 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e190175 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. State Machine ID Overlap*
1e190175 [gemini-3.1-pro] #At the top of your file, you have:
1e190175 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e190175 [gemini-3.1-pro] #int ColorPumpStateMachine=1;
1e190176 [gemini-3.1-pro] #int ChromaStateMachine=1;
