1e1936b5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #That test pattern (`0x00f00f11`) is an excellent choice!
1e1936b5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936b6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because the PIO's Output Shift Register (OSR) shifts to the right by default, it will consume that
1e1936b6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #32-bit word from the lowest nibble to the highest. This means your screen will draw a repeating
1e1936b6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #sequence of 8 pixels: Color 1, Color 1, Color 15, Color 0, Color 0, Color 15, Color 0, Color
1e1936b6 [gemini-3.1-pro] #0. This is going to give you a fantastic set of vertical color bars to verify your horizontal
1e1936b7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #timing!
1e1936b7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936b7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #I did spot two quick hardware configuration "gotchas" in this latest update that will prevent the
1e1936b7 [gemini-3.1-pro] #signal from generating correctly. You'll want to revert these before you flash the board:
1e1936b8 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936b8 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. The Open-Drain Outputs Must Be `false`
1e1936b8 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You changed the initialization of the video pins to `true`:
1e1936b8 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936b9 [gemini-3.1-pro] #gpio_put(Y_PIN, true);
1e1936b9 [gemini-3.1-pro] #gpio_put(PB_PIN, true);
1e1936b9 [gemini-3.1-pro] #gpio_put(PR_PIN, true);
1e1936b9 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936ba [gemini-3.1-pro] #• These must be `false` (0V).*
1e1936ba [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is why: Your PIO is rapidly changing the pin direction (`pindirs`) to create the
1e1936ba [gemini-3.1-pro] #analog voltages.
1e1936ba [gemini-3.1-pro] #• If the pin output state is `false` (0V): Changing it to an Output drives it to 0V
1e1936bb [gemini-3.1-pro] #(Ground). Changing it to an Input makes it High-Z (which your external 80Ω resistor
1e1936bb [gemini-3.1-pro] #pulls up to 3.3V). This gives you your voltage swing!
1e1936bb [gemini-3.1-pro] #• If the pin output state is `true` (3.3V): Changing it to an Output drives it to 3.3V.
1e1936bb [gemini-3.1-pro] #Changing it to an Input makes it High-Z (which the resistor pulls to 3.3V). The TV will
1e1936bc [gemini-3.1-pro] #just see a flat, unchanging 3.3V line and you won't get any video.
1e1936bc [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936bc [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. The Pump Enable GPIO Mux
1e1936bc [gemini-3.1-pro] #You commented out the GPIO initialization for the Pump trigger pins:
1e1936bd [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936bd [gemini-3.1-pro] #//	pio_gpio_init(pio, PUMP0_ENABLE);
1e1936bd [gemini-3.1-pro] #//	pio_gpio_init(pio, PUMP1_ENABLE);
1e1936bd [gemini-3.1-pro] #//	...
1e1936be [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936be [gemini-3.1-pro] #• You need to leave these uncommented.*
1e1936be [gemini-3.1-pro] #Even though these pins are just being used to pass a signal internally from `pio1` (the colorpump)
1e1936bf [gemini-3.1-pro] #to `pio2` (the colorfifos), the RP2350's architecture requires the GPIO pad multiplexer to be
1e1936bf [gemini-3.1-pro] #assigned to the driving PIO block. If `piogpioinit(pio1, ...)` is not called, `pio1` is
1e1936bf [gemini-3.1-pro] #physically disconnected from the GPIO pads, meaning the `colorpump` state machine will be pulsing
1e1936bf [gemini-3.1-pro] #into the void, and the `colorfifo` state machines on `pio2` will never see the trigger drop.
1e1936c0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e1936c0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Once you flip those `gpio_put`s back to `false` and uncomment the trigger pin inits, your vertical
1e1936c0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #color bars should be ready to broadcast!
1e1936c0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
