1e25b93b [gemini-3.1-pro] #It sounds like you are running into a classic hardware boundary trap with the PIO. Based on the
1e25b93b [gemini-3.1-pro] #architecture and code provided, there are a few interconnected reasons why your `colorpump` IRQ is
1e25b93b [gemini-3.1-pro] #getting stuck.
1e25b93b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b93c [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is a breakdown of what is likely happening and how to address it:
1e25b93c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b93c [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 1. Cross-PIO IRQ Visibility*
1e25b93c [gemini-3.1-pro] #In `vidbit.cpp`, your main video generator (`vidbit`) is initialized on `pio0`, while `colorpump`
1e25b93d [gemini-3.1-pro] #is initialized on `pio1`.
1e25b93d [gemini-3.1-pro] #On the RP2350 (and RP2040), the 8 internal state machine IRQ flags are strictly local to each PIO
1e25b93d [gemini-3.1-pro] #block. State machines on `pio1` cannot see or wait on IRQ flags set by state machines on `pio0`. If
1e25b93d [gemini-3.1-pro] #your main video timing on `pio0` is setting IRQ 5 to trigger the line pump, `colorpump` on `pio1`
1e25b93e [gemini-3.1-pro] #will never see it go high, causing it to stall indefinitely at the `wait` instruction.
1e25b93e [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b93e [gemini-3.1-pro] #To fix this, you will need to move `colorpump` to `pio0` so they share the same IRQ flag pool.
1e25b93e [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b93f [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. State Machine ID Conflict*
1e25b93f [gemini-3.1-pro] #If you move `colorpump` to `pio0`, you will need to assign it a free state machine index.
1e25b93f [gemini-3.1-pro] #Currently, your state machine IDs are defined as:
1e25b93f [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `VideoStateMachine = 0`
1e25b940 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `TeletextStateMachine = 1`
1e25b940 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `ColorPumpStateMachine = 1`
1e25b940 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• `ChromaStateMachine = 1`
1e25b940 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b941 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Notice that `ColorPumpStateMachine` and `ChromaStateMachine` share the same ID (`1`). While
1e25b941 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`CHROMA` is currently commented out, this will cause a collision if both are ever enabled.
1e25b941 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Additionally, if you move `colorpump` to `pio0`, it will collide with `TeletextStateMachine`.
1e25b941 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b942 [gemini-3.1-pro] #I recommend reassigning `ColorPumpStateMachine` to `2` and updating your `main()` function to
1e25b942 [gemini-3.1-pro] #initialize it on `pio0` instead of `pio1`.
1e25b942 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b942 [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 3. Clearing the IRQ Flag*
1e25b943 [gemini-3.1-pro] #In your `colorpump.pio` file, the synchronization instruction is written as:
1e25b943 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`wait 1 irq 5`
1e25b943 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b943 [gemini-3.1-pro] #This tells the state machine to wait until the flag is high, but it does not clear the
1e25b944 [gemini-3.1-pro] #flag. Unless your main `vidbit` state machine is manually clearing IRQ 5 immediately after setting
1e25b944 [gemini-3.1-pro] #it, `colorpump` will blast right through the `wait` instruction on all subsequent lines and lose
1e25b944 [gemini-3.1-pro] #synchronization.
1e25b944 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b945 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You can instruct the PIO to automatically clear the flag once the wait condition is met by
1e25b945 [gemini-3.1-pro] #appending the `clear` modifier to the instruction in your PIO assembly:
1e25b945 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`wait 1 irq 5 clear`
1e25b946 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25b946 [gemini-3.1-pro] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e25b946 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
