1e25ccbe [gemini-3.1-pro] #It is great that the state machine is running now! By the way, the way you perfectly balanced all
1e25ccbe [gemini-3.1-pro] #four branches of `colorpump` to exactly 10 cycles to phase-lock with the 10-cycle `colorfifo` loop
1e25ccbf [gemini-3.1-pro] #is a brilliant piece of PIO design.
1e25ccbf [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccbf [gemini-3.1-pro] #Since it is running but there is no color, the issue now lies in how the data is moving (or not
1e25ccbf [gemini-3.1-pro] #moving) through the FIFOs and DMA. There are four missing links in the data pipeline preventing the
1e25ccc0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #color signals from reaching the pins.
1e25ccc0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here is how to fix them:
1e25ccc0 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. Enable Autopull for `colorpump`
1e25ccc1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #In `vidbit.cpp`, your `colorpump_init` function configures the pins but forgets to enable
1e25ccc1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`autopull`. Without this, the state machine never pulls data from the TX FIFO. It just shifts out
1e25ccc1 [gemini-3.1-pro] #`0`s endlessly, and your DMA channel stalls after transferring the very first word.
1e25ccc2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Add this line to `colorpump_init`:
1e25ccc2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc2 [gemini-3.1-pro] #sm_config_set_out_shift(&config6, true, true, 32); // shift right, autopull ON, 32 bits
1e25ccc3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. Empty the OSR after loading the ISR
1e25ccc3 [gemini-3.1-pro] #In `colorpump_init`, you manually load `863` into the ISR using a `pull` and `mov`. However, this
1e25ccc4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #leaves `863` sitting in the OSR. When the state machine starts its loop, it will accidentally
1e25ccc4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #output the bits of `863` as your first 8 pixels, throwing the DMA completely out of sync with your
1e25ccc4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #lines.
1e25ccc4 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #You need to empty the OSR immediately after loading the ISR so that the first pixel triggers a
1e25ccc5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #fresh autopull from the DMA. Add the `out` execution here:
1e25ccc5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1e25ccc5 [gemini-3.1-pro] #pio_sm_put_blocking(pio, sm, 863);	// load ISR with count
