1e3cc01f [deepseek-v4] #Your files present an interesting approach to generating component video with RP2350 PIO state
1e3cc01f [deepseek-v4] #machines. I’ll comment on a few aspects I found notable, plus point out potential issues.
1e3cc01f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc01f [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3cc01f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #`colorpump.pio`
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #- The state machine uses `out pins, 2` then `out x, 2` to set the color index. After that, it
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #decrements `x` and jumps to set one of four trigger lines (GP7, GP11, GP13, GP14).
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #- Potential problem: The `out x, 2` instruction loads the same source (OSR) that
1e3cc020 [deepseek-v4] #was just used for `out pins, 2`. In PIO, `out` shifts bits from OSR. After the first `out pins, 2`,
1e3cc021 [deepseek-v4] #the OSR has advanced by 2 bits; the second `out x, 2` reads the next two bits, not the same
1e3cc021 [deepseek-v4] #index. If the intention is to use the same index for both the output pins and the jump, you would
1e3cc021 [deepseek-v4] #need to reload or use a `mov` instruction beforehand. This misalignment could cause incorrect
1e3cc021 [deepseek-v4] #colour selection.
1e3cc021 [deepseek-v4] #- Alternative: Use `out x, 2` first, then `mov isr, x` or store the value in `y` before
1e3cc022 [deepseek-v4] #outputting to pins.
1e3cc022 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc022 [deepseek-v4] #- The `set pins, 15` after the trigger pulse returns to all‑low (since 15 = 0b1111, all four
1e3cc022 [deepseek-v4] #side‑set pins low? Check pin mapping: if side‑set pins are GPIO7,11,13,14, then setting pins = 15
1e3cc022 [deepseek-v4] #sets those bits; but you might want to clear all triggers after the pulse. The `nop [1]` and `set
1e3cc023 [deepseek-v4] #pins, 15` sequence creates a short low pulse on the selected trigger, but the last state is high on
1e3cc023 [deepseek-v4] #all four. That may keep subsequent colourfifo state machines in a `jmp pin stall` loop if they are
1e3cc023 [deepseek-v4] #edge‑sensitive or level‑sensitive? Better to set pins back to a known idle state (e.g., all high?
1e3cc023 [deepseek-v4] #or all low? depends on active‑low triggering). Clarify the trigger polarity.
1e3cc024 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc024 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3cc024 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc024 [deepseek-v4] #`colorfifo.pio`
1e3cc025 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc025 [deepseek-v4] #- Uses `fifo` side‑set? The `.fifo txget` directive is non‑standard in official PIO syntax. I
1e3cc025 [deepseek-v4] #assume you mean to use `side‑set` or `out` for FIFO control? Actually, PIO assembler doesn't have a
1e3cc025 [deepseek-v4] #`.fifo` directive. You probably intended `.side_set 1` or something else. Please clarify the
1e3cc026 [deepseek-v4] #intended pin mapping and side‑set usage.
1e3cc026 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc026 [deepseek-v4] #- `mov y, pins` reads the current GPIO pins. Which pins? The `pins` register reflects the actual
1e3cc026 [deepseek-v4] #pin levels. If colour indices come from `colorpump` via dedicated GPIO pairs, this works. However,
1e3cc027 [deepseek-v4] #the timing of reading `pins` relative to the trigger needs to be tight to avoid races.
1e3cc027 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc027 [deepseek-v4] #- The `out pindirs, 3` repeated six times uses 18 bits from OSR. But the FIFO (txget) presumably
1e3cc028 [deepseek-v4] #holds 32 bits. The remaining bits are unused. That's fine. However, the constant `set pindirs, 0`
1e3cc028 [deepseek-v4] #at the end might need to be `set pindirs, 0` to set all pins to input (tristate). That would stop
1e3cc028 [deepseek-v4] #driving the resistor ladder. For analog video, you might want a known drive strength or a pull‑down
1e3cc028 [deepseek-v4] #state, not high‑impedance. Consider whether the resistor network expects a fixed output impedance
1e3cc029 [deepseek-v4] #or tristate is okay.
1e3cc029 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc029 [deepseek-v4] #- The stall loop `jmp pin stall` waits while the trigger pin is high (if pin == true). With
1e3cc029 [deepseek-v4] #`colorpump` setting the trigger high only for one PIO word cycle, the stall will be short. But
1e3cc02a [deepseek-v4] #beware that multiple colourfifo state machines might see the same trigger – they need a shared
1e3cc02a [deepseek-v4] #index bus and per‑channel triggers.
1e3cc02a [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc02b [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3cc02b [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc02b [deepseek-v4] #Signal Chain (`vidpump.md`)
1e3cc02b [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc02c [deepseek-v4] #- `pixelpump` → `onebit` → `threepin` is a three‑stage pipeline. The inter‑state machine
1e3cc02c [deepseek-v4] #synchronisation via `irq` (clear/set) is good. However, note that `threepin` uses `jmp y--, train`
1e3cc02c [deepseek-v4] #which loops for the full line pixel count. The `pull block` at the start of `threepin` waits for a
1e3cc02c [deepseek-v4] #pixel count from the previous stage. Ensure the FIFO depth and back‑pressure are adequate to avoid
1e3cc02c [deepseek-v4] #stalls.
1e3cc02d [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc02d [deepseek-v4] #- In `onebit`, you use `out pins, 1` to read pixel data from OSR. But the `pins` output is used as
1e3cc02d [deepseek-v4] #feedback via a loopback pin (GP46). That loopback pin then drives `jmp pin` to select between two
1e3cc02d [deepseek-v4] #waveform tables. This is clever, but note that `out pins, 1` changes the output
1e3cc02d [deepseek-v4] #immediately; the loopback pin will reflect that value on the next clock cycle. Ensure the
1e3cc02e [deepseek-v4] #pipeline timing accounts for one cycle delay, otherwise the wrong waveform may be selected for the
1e3cc02e [deepseek-v4] #current pixel.
1e3cc02e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc02f [deepseek-v4] #- The two waveform tables (`y` and `x`) are loaded once per line? Actually `onebit` loads them
1e3cc02f [deepseek-v4] #before the pixel loop, so they remain constant for the whole line. This is fine for a monochrome or
1e3cc02f [deepseek-v4] #fixed‑palette display, but for per‑pixel colour the waveform would need to change per pixel. Your
1e3cc02f [deepseek-v4] #`colorpump`+`colorfifo` approach is separate – does that replace `onebit`? The description says
1e3cc030 [deepseek-v4] #"pixelpump → onebit → threepin" for 1‑bit video, while `colorpump` seems to be for a fully coloured
1e3cc030 [deepseek-v4] #component signal. You may have two distinct modes; please clarify.
1e3cc030 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc030 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3cc030 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc031 [deepseek-v4] #General Observations
1e3cc031 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc031 [deepseek-v4] #1. Clock Frequency: 166.5 MHz is chosen because 166.5 × 64 = 10656 exactly? That’s 166.5
1e3cc031 [deepseek-v4] #MHz = 166,500,000 Hz. 64 μs line × 10 cycles/pixel = 166.5? Actually 10656 cycles per line / 64 μs
1e3cc031 [deepseek-v4] #= 166.5 MHz. Good choice for PAL.
1e3cc032 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc032 [deepseek-v4] #2. Pin Naming: In `colorpump` you refer to `set pins, 14` etc., but the RP2350 has GPIO
1e3cc032 [deepseek-v4] #numbers, not logical bits. Which actual GPIOs correspond to these bits? Ensure the side‑set base
1e3cc032 [deepseek-v4] #and pin mapping are configured correctly in C code.
1e3cc032 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc033 [deepseek-v4] #3. Interrupt Synchronisation: Using IRQ 0 for line timing is standard. The `irq clear 0`
1e3cc033 [deepseek-v4] #after waiting is right. But `pixelpump` pushes two colour tables before the first line; however,
1e3cc033 [deepseek-v4] #the `wait 1 irq 0` happens after that. That's okay, but consider that the first IRQ may
1e3cc034 [deepseek-v4] #come while you are still initialising. Maybe start with `irq wait` only inside the loop.
1e3cc034 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc034 [deepseek-v4] #4. Resistor Network: The schematic shows composite video via resistors, but the PIO code
1e3cc034 [deepseek-v4] #drives multiple pins simultaneously for component (Y/Pb/Pr). The `threepin` state machine drives
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #three pins as pindirs. For component video, you would usually have three separate DAC pins.
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #However, `out pindirs, 3` controls direction for three consecutive pins. If you want different
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #resistor values per channel, you may need separate pins per colour component.
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #5. Housekeeping Cycles: In `colorfifo`, you have 6 output instructions followed by a set to
1e3cc035 [deepseek-v4] #zero, making a 7‑pulse train per colour. But the prose says "6 cycles + 4 housekeeping". The code
1e3cc036 [deepseek-v4] #shows 6 `out pindirs` but then `set pindirs, 0` (that's a simple 0). The "4 housekeeping" may refer
1e3cc036 [deepseek-v4] #to the stall loop, `mov y, pins`, etc. Clarify the actual cycle count.
1e3cc036 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc036 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3cc037 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc037 [deepseek-v4] #Summary
1e3cc037 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc038 [deepseek-v4] #Your design is ambitious and leverages the RP2350's dual‑core and multiple PIOs well. The main
1e3cc038 [deepseek-v4] #issues to review are the bit‑alignment in `colorpump`, the trigger polarity, and the loopback
1e3cc038 [deepseek-v4] #timing in `onebit`. With careful testing these can be resolved. Good luck with the project!
1e3cc038 [deepseek-v4] #
