1e3cc2a6 [deepseek-v4] #The shared design presents several novel aspects but also raises questions about compatibility with
1e3cc2a6 [deepseek-v4] #the RP2350 PIO instruction set and timing consistency.
1e3cc2a6 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2a6 [deepseek-v4] #• New or different elements observed:*
1e3cc2a7 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2a7 [deepseek-v4] #1. Unusual PIO instructions – The `colorfifo` program uses `.fifo txget` and `txget` (not
1e3cc2a7 [deepseek-v4] #`pull`/`push`). Standard RP2350 PIO does not support a `txget` mnemonic or `.fifo` directive; these
1e3cc2a7 [deepseek-v4] #appear to be custom extensions or possibly typos. The RP2350 retains the same PIO instruction set
1e3cc2a8 [deepseek-v4] #as RP2040, so this would likely fail assembly on official tools.
1e3cc2a8 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2a8 [deepseek-v4] #2. Pixel timing discrepancy – The `threepin` program outputs 10 `out pindirs,3`
1e3cc2a8 [deepseek-v4] #instructions, followed by `set pindirs,0` (1 cycle), `out null,2` (2 cycles), and `jmp y--, train`
1e3cc2a8 [deepseek-v4] #(1 cycle). That totals 14 cycles per pixel, not the stated 10 cycles. The `out null,2` and
1e3cc2a9 [deepseek-v4] #`set` likely add overhead, breaking the 10‑cycle pixel window required for PAL at 166.5 MHz (which
1e3cc2a9 [deepseek-v4] #yields 10,656 cycles per line).
1e3cc2a9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2a9 [deepseek-v4] #3. One‑bit video with loopback – The `onebit` PIO uses a feedback pin (GP46) via `jmp pin`
1e3cc2aa [deepseek-v4] #to select between two precomputed 32‑bit waveform blocks (for black/white). This is an inventive
1e3cc2aa [deepseek-v4] #way to produce two distinct analog levels without per‑pixel FIFO pressure, though it relies on a
1e3cc2aa [deepseek-v4] #single pin to reflect the pixel value being output. Propagation delay might limit speed.
1e3cc2aa [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2aa [deepseek-v4] #4. Resistor‑ladder analog output – Using three GPIO pins with tristate control (`pindirs`)
1e3cc2ab [deepseek-v4] #to generate analog video levels via weighted resistors is a known approach (common in VGA), but
1e3cc2ab [deepseek-v4] #integrating it with PIO’s `out pindirs,3` to cycle through binary‑weighted patterns for PAL
1e3cc2ab [deepseek-v4] #luminance/chroma component is somewhat novel. However, the resistor schematic lists CHROMA330 and
1e3cc2ac [deepseek-v4] #CHROMA100 separately, possibly to combine chrominance into composite? The design seems to target
1e3cc2ac [deepseek-v4] #component video (Pb/Pr) or a hybrid composite‑component scheme, which is unusual.
1e3cc2ac [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2ac [deepseek-v4] #5. Separate colorpump + colorfifo for color subcarrier – The `colorpump` drives 1‑of‑4
1e3cc2ad [deepseek-v4] #side-set lines to trigger a `colorfifo` that preloads four pulse trains. This likely implements PAL
1e3cc2ad [deepseek-v4] #color burst generation via a dedicated PIO machine, which is a clean way to offload timing from the
1e3cc2ad [deepseek-v4] #main video pipeline.
1e3cc2ad [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2ae [deepseek-v4] #6. FIFO chain: pixelpump → onebit → threepin – This three‑stage pipeline uses FIFO
1e3cc2ae [deepseek-v4] #handshakes for flow control. Each stage modifies the data stream (binary pixel bits → waveform
1e3cc2ae [deepseek-v4] #words → pin drive patterns). Such layered PIO chains are less common than single‑stage solutions.
1e3cc2af [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cc2af [deepseek-v4] #• Overall assessment:*
1e3cc2af [deepseek-v4] #The architecture is creative but contains several unverified details (cycle counts, non‑standard
1e3cc2af [deepseek-v4] #instructions). If the `txget` / `.fifo` are part of a custom PIO assembler or a misunderstanding,
1e3cc2af [deepseek-v4] #fixing those will be essential. The timing issues in `threepin` need recalculation to achieve
1e3cc2b0 [deepseek-v4] #exactly 10 cycles per pixel. The one‑bit feedback technique is clever but should be tested for
1e3cc2b0 [deepseek-v4] #stability at 166.5 MHz. Adjusting these points could yield a viable RP2350‑based PAL component
