1e3cde2c [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing these well-documented files. The architecture is quite novel compared to
1e3cde2c [deepseek-v4] #typical PIO video generators for the RP-series — most examples (e.g., Pimoroni’s PicoVGA or the
1e3cde2d [deepseek-v4] #official VGA demo) rely on a single PIO state machine directly driving RGB lines from a FIFO filled
1e3cde2d [deepseek-v4] #by DMA, with a 1‑bit or 2‑bit colour depth. Your approach is different in several ways:
1e3cde2d [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde2d [deepseek-v4] #1. Colour palette via separate PIO machines
1e3cde2e [deepseek-v4] #   `colorpump` and `colorfifo` implement a distributed palette lookup: one SM encodes a 2‑bit index
1e3cde2e [deepseek-v4] #and triggers a pulse on one of four side‑set pins, while another SM reads that index from GPIO and
1e3cde2e [deepseek-v4] #outputs the corresponding 3‑channel pulse train (6 cycles each) from a preloaded RX FIFO. This
1e3cde2e [deepseek-v4] #decouples pixel fetch from colour generation and allows each `colorfifo` to handle its own palette
1e3cde2f [deepseek-v4] #without CPU intervention per pixel.
1e3cde2f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde2f [deepseek-v4] #2. Chained FIFO pipeline
1e3cde2f [deepseek-v4] #   The `vidpump` chain (`pixelpump → onebit → threepin`) uses FIFO passing between three SMs to
1e3cde2f [deepseek-v4] #separate line timing, pixel‑bit expansion, and pin driving. This is a clever way to match a 32‑bit
1e3cde30 [deepseek-v4] #wide data stream to a 3‑bit physical interface while maintaining precise timing.
1e3cde30 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde30 [deepseek-v4] #3. 10‑cycle pixel period
1e3cde30 [deepseek-v4] #   At 166.5 MHz, 10 cycles per pixel matches an 864‑pixel active line (8640 cycles) plus 2016
1e3cde30 [deepseek-v4] #cycles for sync/blanking, which is PAL‑compatible. The `threepin` program achieves exactly 10
1e3cde31 [deepseek-v4] #cycles using 8× `out pindirs` + `set pindirs,0` + `out null,2` — good.
1e3cde31 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde31 [deepseek-v4] #4. Use of a GPIO loopback
1e3cde31 [deepseek-v4] #   `onebit` reads pixel state from a loopback pin (`GPIO 46`) to select which 32‑bit waveform train
1e3cde32 [deepseek-v4] #to push downstream. This implies that the pixel bits come from another source (perhaps another SM
1e3cde32 [deepseek-v4] #or a memory‑mapped pin). The loopback approach is unusual but could simplify synchronisation.
1e3cde32 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde32 [deepseek-v4] #5. Side‑set triggers
1e3cde33 [deepseek-v4] #   `colorpump` pulses one of four side‑set pins (values 14,13,11,7) that are likely wired to the
1e3cde33 [deepseek-v4] #`jmp` pin inputs of the `colorfifo` machines. This creates a lightweight interrupt‑like mechanism
1e3cde33 [deepseek-v4] #across SMs without using the system IRQ controller.
1e3cde33 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde34 [deepseek-v4] #Potential improvements / notes
1e3cde34 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde34 [deepseek-v4] #- FIFO depth and CPU involvement
1e3cde34 [deepseek-v4] #  Both `colorpump` and `pixelpump` use `pull block`, meaning the CPU must actively push data to
1e3cde35 [deepseek-v4] #keep them running. For a full framebuffer (576i, 625 lines × 864 pixels), this would require either
1e3cde35 [deepseek-v4] #a very fast CPU loop or DMA. DMA could fill the FIFOs from a pre‑rendered palette table or pixel
1e3cde35 [deepseek-v4] #buffer, freeing the CPU.
1e3cde36 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde36 [deepseek-v4] #- Synchronisation between `colorpump` and `colorfifo`
1e3cde36 [deepseek-v4] #  The `jmp pin stall` in `colorfifo` busy‑waits until the trigger pin goes high? (The comment says
1e3cde36 [deepseek-v4] #“jmp pin 2” but the instruction `jmp pin stall` tests the JMP pin configured in SM configuration,
1e3cde36 [deepseek-v4] #not a side‑set pin number). If the trigger pulse from `colorpump` is shorter than one SM cycle at
1e3cde37 [deepseek-v4] #166.5 MHz, it might be missed. Using a higher‑priority side‑set (SIDE_SET) or a SET instruction
1e3cde37 [deepseek-v4] #could be more reliable.
1e3cde37 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde37 [deepseek-v4] #- Interlaced PAL support
1e3cde37 [deepseek-v4] #  The `vidbit` document mentions 576i. Interlace requires odd/even field timing and field/frame
1e3cde38 [deepseek-v4] #sync pulse variation. Your `pixelpump` uses a single `irq 0` per line; you would likely need a
1e3cde38 [deepseek-v4] #second IRQ or a counter to toggle the field sync once per frame. The current design appears to be
1e3cde38 [deepseek-v4] #progressive; adding interlaced support would require extra logic.
1e3cde38 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde39 [deepseek-v4] #- Resistor DAC linearity
1e3cde39 [deepseek-v4] #  The schematic shows a simple resistor ladder for LUMA (150 Ω) and two chroma resistors (330 Ω and
1e3cde39 [deepseek-v4] #100 Ω) combined with a 120 Ω output resistor and 75 Ω load. The three PIO output pins (three
1e3cde3a [deepseek-v4] #pindirs) presumably drive LUMA and two chroma lines. The coding for colour may need to account for
1e3cde3a [deepseek-v4] #the resistor weighting; this is a common approach but must be calibrated for proper colour levels.
1e3cde3a [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde3a [deepseek-v4] #- One‑bit expansion flexibility
1e3cde3b [deepseek-v4] #  `onebit` pushes a fixed 32‑bit train for every 0 or 1 pixel. Because each pixel consists of 10
1e3cde3b [deepseek-v4] #cycles, the train must encode the correct waveform for that colour across all 10 cycles. This
1e3cde3b [deepseek-v4] #limits colour depth to two colours per scanline unless you reload the trains every line (which your
1e3cde3b [deepseek-v4] #`pixelpump` does: it pulls two colour patterns before starting each line). That’s a sensible
1e3cde3c [deepseek-v4] #trade‑off for a 2‑colour composite video system.
1e3cde3c [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde3c [deepseek-v4] #Overall, this is a well‑thought‑out design that pushes the boundaries of PIO‑based video
1e3cde3c [deepseek-v4] #generation. The separation of concerns between palette lookup, pixel expansion, and pin driving is
1e3cde3d [deepseek-v4] #architecturally elegant and could be extended to higher colour depths or more complex video
1e3cde3d [deepseek-v4] #standards. I’d be interested to see a full system diagram showing how the different PIOs are
1e3cde3d [deepseek-v4] #connected physically (especially the side‑set triggers) and how the CPU or DMA feeds the FIFOs.
1e3cde3e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3cde3e [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing — this is definitely a fresh approach compared to the usual “big FIFO + one
1e3cde3e [deepseek-v4] #SM” pattern.
1e3cde3e [deepseek-v4] #
