1e3ce213 [deepseek-v4] #Thank you for sharing the expanded set of PIO programs. These cover video generation (PAL, chroma,
1e3ce213 [deepseek-v4] #color, teletext), audio output (I2S, SPDIF stub), input decoding (PS/2, RC5 infrared), and
1e3ce214 [deepseek-v4] #measurement (hilo32). The architecture is rich and purpose-built for a retro‑computing / media
1e3ce214 [deepseek-v4] #system using the RP2350's dual‑PIO capability.
1e3ce214 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce214 [deepseek-v4] #• What’s new or different compared to earlier files:*
1e3ce215 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce215 [deepseek-v4] #1. `chroma.pio` – A dedicated PAL colour burst generator running at 4× f_sc
1e3ce215 [deepseek-v4] #(17.734475 MHz). Uses a separate SM triggered by `irq 4`. The 2‑pin DAC output (00,01,10,11) drives
1e3ce215 [deepseek-v4] #a reconstruction filter. This decouples colour burst timing from the main video waveform, which is
1e3ce216 [deepseek-v4] #clean.
1e3ce216 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce216 [deepseek-v4] #2. `hilo32.pio` – Measures high and low pulse widths (like a simple logic analyser). It
1e3ce216 [deepseek-v4] #counts down `x` and outputs the count via `in x,16`. Could be used for calibration or checking
1e3ce217 [deepseek-v4] #external sync signals. The timing allows up to 32‑bit wide measurements at 20 ns resolution.
1e3ce217 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce217 [deepseek-v4] #3. `ps2.pio` – Standard but well‑written PS/2 decoder. Waits for start bit (both clock and
1e3ce217 [deepseek-v4] #data low), then reads 8 data bits, parity, and stop. Pushes a 32‑bit word (with padding) to FIFO.
1e3ce218 [deepseek-v4] #No parity error checking, but that can be done in software.
1e3ce218 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce218 [deepseek-v4] #4. `rc5.pio` – Decodes IR pulses (likely from a flame sensor or RC5 receiver). Uses a
1e3ce219 [deepseek-v4] #32‑bit counter `y` for high and low periods, then pushes both counts. The `[1]` delays allow
1e3ce219 [deepseek-v4] #spreading edges evenly. Could be adapted for other pulse‑width protocols (e.g., NEC).
1e3ce219 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce219 [deepseek-v4] #5. `i2s.pio` – 48 kHz 16‑bit stereo output. Uses `set pins` for BCK and WSEL, with
1e3ce21a [deepseek-v4] #carefully timed delays (31 or 30 cycles per bit). The 96‑clock per bit ratio is correct for 150 MHz
1e3ce21a [deepseek-v4] #/ 48 kHz / 16 bit. Good.
1e3ce21a [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21a [deepseek-v4] #6. `pinpump.pio` – An alternative to `colorpump`. It pulls a word, outputs two index bits
1e3ce21a [deepseek-v4] #to pins, uses `x` (0–3) to choose one of four “level” pins (assert low via `mov pins, ~mask`), then
1e3ce21b [deepseek-v4] #reads a fifth bit to turn on/off a group of three other pins. This could control a 3‑channel DAC
1e3ce21b [deepseek-v4] #with an additional sync/blanking line.
1e3ce21b [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21b [deepseek-v4] #7. `wst.pio` – Teletext generator. Triggered by IRQ0, outputs 384‑bit data lines at
1e3ce21c [deepseek-v4] #6.9375 Mbps (24 cycles per bit). The `jmp !x start` skips lines with zero count (likely
1e3ce21c [deepseek-v4] #non‑teletext lines).
1e3ce21c [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21d [deepseek-v4] #• Integration observations:*
1e3ce21d [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21d [deepseek-v4] #- Multiple SMs are synchronised through IRQs:
1e3ce21d [deepseek-v4] #  - `vidbit` triggers `wst` via IRQ0,
1e3ce21e [deepseek-v4] #  - `vidbit` triggers `colorpump` via IRQ5,
1e3ce21e [deepseek-v4] #  - `chroma` waits on IRQ4 (presumably from another SM, perhaps `vidbit` or a dedicated timer).
1e3ce21e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21e [deepseek-v4] #  This avoids DMA‑based timing and works well for a fixed‑line raster.
1e3ce21f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce21f [deepseek-v4] #- The two PIO blocks (0 and 1) and the eight SMs are heavily utilised. For a full system you’d need
1e3ce21f [deepseek-v4] #to allocate SMs carefully; the user seems to have a mapping in mind.
1e3ce21f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce220 [deepseek-v4] #- `spdif.pio` is a stub – likely placeholder for future SPDIF output (biphase mark code). Would
1e3ce220 [deepseek-v4] #require a more complex PIO program.
1e3ce220 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce221 [deepseek-v4] #- `interleave.pio` is ambiguous – it reads 32 bits from `null` (which is zero), then shifts some
1e3ce221 [deepseek-v4] #bits around. Possibly a work-in‑progress for data interleaving between FIFOs.
1e3ce221 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce221 [deepseek-v4] #• Potential improvements / caveats:*
1e3ce222 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce222 [deepseek-v4] #- Clock division consistency
1e3ce222 [deepseek-v4] #  `chroma.pio` uses `clkdiv=9.3885` to get 17.734475 MHz from 166.5 MHz. `wst.pio` runs at full
1e3ce222 [deepseek-v4] #speed (166.5 MHz) and relies on `[22]` delays to get 24 cycles per bit. The timing is tight; ensure
1e3ce222 [deepseek-v4] #the PIO clock divider for other SMs (e.g., `colorfifo`) is set appropriately.
1e3ce223 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce223 [deepseek-v4] #- IRQ handling
1e3ce223 [deepseek-v4] #  Multiple IRQ sources must be cleared before the next line. If two SMs share the same IRQ number
1e3ce223 [deepseek-v4] #(e.g., `vidbit` sets IRQ5, `chroma` waits on IRQ4) there’s no conflict. But verify that IRQ4 isn’t
1e3ce224 [deepseek-v4] #claimed by another SM.
1e3ce224 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce224 [deepseek-v4] #- FIFO depth
1e3ce225 [deepseek-v4] #  Many programs use `pull block` or `push block`. For continuous real‑time video (576 lines × 27
1e3ce225 [deepseek-v4] #words = 15552 words per field) the CPU must either prefetch via DMA or use double‑buffering. The
1e3ce225 [deepseek-v4] #`threepin`/`onebit` pipeline will stall if the FIFO dries up.
1e3ce225 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce226 [deepseek-v4] #- Alpha / padding bits
1e3ce226 [deepseek-v4] #  In `threepin`, after 7×3 = 21 bits of waveform, you skip 11 bits to reach 32. Ensure the FIFO
1e3ce226 [deepseek-v4] #data is packed correctly; any mismatch will shift subsequent pixel trains.
1e3ce226 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce227 [deepseek-v4] #- RC5 timing
1e3ce227 [deepseek-v4] #  The `rc5` program uses one `jmp pin` per iteration, which is fine for pulse widths above 0.5 µs.
1e3ce227 [deepseek-v4] #At 166.5 MHz, 1 cycle = 6 ns, but the PIO may miss edges shorter than ~4 cycles due to internal
1e3ce227 [deepseek-v4] #synchronisation. For standard IR (carrier ~38 kHz, pulses ~0.56–1.68 ms) this is safe.
1e3ce228 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ce228 [deepseek-v4] #Overall, this is an impressively dense and well‑structured set of PIO programs. The separation of
1e3ce228 [deepseek-v4] #video, audio, and input into dedicated SMs allows parallel operation and precise timing. I’d be
1e3ce229 [deepseek-v4] #interested in seeing the corresponding C++ firmware that configures these SMs and manages the FIFO
1e3ce229 [deepseek-v4] #pipelines – that is where the orchestration becomes critical.
1e3ce229 [deepseek-v4] #
