1e3e289d [deepseek-v4] #Your system pushes the RP2350’s PIO to its limit: 166.5 MHz, multiple state machines, PAL timing,
1e3e289d [deepseek-v4] #and several color‑encoding strategies. Below I highlight what I see as the core ideas, potential
1e3e289e [deepseek-v4] #pitfalls, and suggestions for integration.
1e3e289e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e289e [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3e289e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e289f [deepseek-v4] #Two distinct color pipelines
1e3e289f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e289f [deepseek-v4] #1. `colorpump` + `colorfifo` (4‑color mode, indexed)
1e3e289f [deepseek-v4] #- Goal: Pre‑load 4 colour pulse trains and output one per pixel based on a 2‑bit index from
1e3e28a0 [deepseek-v4] #the incoming pixel data.
1e3e28a0 [deepseek-v4] #- How it works:
1e3e28a0 [deepseek-v4] #  - `colorpump` reads from its own TX FIFO (presumably filled by the CPU with 2‑bit pixel values
1e3e28a0 [deepseek-v4] #per line), writes the 2‑bit index to GPIO pins, then triggers one of four PIO channels
1e3e28a1 [deepseek-v4] #(`colorfifo`) via a low pulse on a side‑set pin.
1e3e28a1 [deepseek-v4] #  - Each `colorfifo` holds 4 (or more) 32‑bit words in its RX FIFO. When triggered, it moves
1e3e28a1 [deepseek-v4] #`pins[0..1]` into `y`, fetches `rxfifo[y]`, and outputs that 3‑lane pulse train.
1e3e28a2 [deepseek-v4] #- Issues:
1e3e28a2 [deepseek-v4] #  - Pin count: 4 separate `colorfifo` state machines each need their own output pins –
1e3e28a2 [deepseek-v4] #that’s 12 pins (3 each) plus the trigger pins from `colorpump`. The files mention GP42‑GP47, which
1e3e28a2 [deepseek-v4] #fits, but check if they are on the same PIO block to allow `mov y, pins` to read the shared index.
1e3e28a3 [deepseek-v4] #  - Timing: The trigger pulses from `colorpump` must be short enough not to interfere with
1e3e28a3 [deepseek-v4] #neighbouring pulses. The current `set pins, 7` etc. are active‑low pulses – ensure they align with
1e3e28a3 [deepseek-v4] #the pixel clock.
1e3e28a3 [deepseek-v4] #  - FIFO depth: Each `colorfifo`’s RX FIFO holds 4 entries by default. If you pre‑load 4
1e3e28a4 [deepseek-v4] #pulse trains, that’s fine. But if you want more colours (e.g. 16), you’d need more FIFO slots or
1e3e28a4 [deepseek-v4] #interleaving.
1e3e28a4 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28a5 [deepseek-v4] #2. `pixelpump` → `onebit` → `threepin` (serial bit‑plane approach)
1e3e28a5 [deepseek-v4] #- Goal: Build a two‑colour (1‑bit) pixel stream by switching between two pre‑loaded
1e3e28a5 [deepseek-v4] #waveform `x` and `y` based on the pixel value read from the third state machine.
1e3e28a5 [deepseek-v4] #- How it works:
1e3e28a6 [deepseek-v4] #  - `pixelpump` pumps 27 words per line (864 pixels) into the FIFO chain.
1e3e28a6 [deepseek-v4] #  - `onebit` loads two 32‑bit pulse patterns into `y` and `x` (typical PAL waveform pair, e.g. luma
1e3e28a6 [deepseek-v4] #levels). For each pixel, it outputs 1 bit, reads that bit from a loopback pin, and pushes the
1e3e28a6 [deepseek-v4] #appropriate waveform word into the next FIFO.
1e3e28a7 [deepseek-v4] #  - `threepin` receives these waveform words and outputs 10 (or 7) groups of 3‑bit `pindirs` to
1e3e28a7 [deepseek-v4] #drive three pins (e.g. RGB or YPbPr).
1e3e28a7 [deepseek-v4] #- Issues:
1e3e28a7 [deepseek-v4] #  - Pipeline depth: Three state machines with FIFO passes – possible stalls if any FIFO
1e3e28a8 [deepseek-v4] #becomes full or empty. The `push block / pull block` will eventually pause the chain, but the
1e3e28a8 [deepseek-v4] #timing must be exact to keep line rate.
1e3e28a8 [deepseek-v4] #  - Loopback pin: `onebit` uses a pin to read the current pixel state – that pin must be
1e3e28a9 [deepseek-v4] #driven by a state machine (likely a fourth) or a CPU‑toggled GPIO. The file says “GPIO 46”, but
1e3e28a9 [deepseek-v4] #it’s not clear how that pin is set per pixel.
1e3e28a9 [deepseek-v4] #  - Word length: `threepin` currently outputs 7 groups of 3‑bit directions (21 bits) then
1e3e28a9 [deepseek-v4] #skips 11 bits, totalling 32 bits. That matches the 10‑cycle pixel period (7 cycles for waveform, 3
1e3e28aa [deepseek-v4] #dummy). But you have a `set pindirs, 0` after output – that turns off the pins for the remaining
1e3e28aa [deepseek-v4] #cycles, which is correct for analog reconstruction? Ensure the DAC resistors see a clean high‑Z or
1e3e28aa [deepseek-v4] #pull‑down during the inactive part.
1e3e28aa [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28ab [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3e28ab [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28ab [deepseek-v4] #PAL timing generator (`vidbit.pio`)
1e3e28ab [deepseek-v4] #- This is a solid H‑sync, back porch, active line, front porch loop counting 10656 cycles.
1e3e28ac [deepseek-v4] #- Note the use of `irq set 5` at the end of the back porch – presumably to trigger `colorpump` or
1e3e28ac [deepseek-v4] #the pixel source. This synchronises the pixel pipeline.
1e3e28ac [deepseek-v4] #- However, the pixel pipeline runs on a different state machine. The IRQ5 is set after the back
1e3e28ad [deepseek-v4] #porch, but `colorpump` waits on `irq 5` – this is the correct handshake. But the pixel data must
1e3e28ad [deepseek-v4] #already be waiting. The CPU or a DMA controller should fill `pixelpump`’s FIFO before the IRQ
1e3e28ad [deepseek-v4] #fires.
1e3e28ad [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28ae [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3e28ae [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28ae [deepseek-v4] #Chroma burst (`chroma.pio`)
1e3e28ae [deepseek-v4] #- A separate 4× subcarrier state machine. It uses `wait irq 4` to start at the right point
1e3e28af [deepseek-v4] #(probably during back porch). It outputs 2‑pin DAC values (00,01,10,11) to generate the 4.43 MHz
1e3e28af [deepseek-v4] #burst. Ensure the pin outputs are combined through the resistor network described in `vidbit.md`.
1e3e28af [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28af [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3e28b0 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b0 [deepseek-v4] #Suggested integration
1e3e28b0 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b1 [deepseek-v4] #Given you have two colour strategies, I think you could unify them:
1e3e28b1 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b1 [deepseek-v4] #- Option A (component output): Use the `pixelpump/onebit/threepin` chain for three 1‑bit
1e3e28b1 [deepseek-v4] #colour channels (R, G, B) – i.e., each channel gets its own `onebit` and `threepin`. This gives
1e3e28b2 [deepseek-v4] #8‑colour analogue video via resistor DACs. Or extend to multiple bits per channel using additional
1e3e28b2 [deepseek-v4] #state machines.
1e3e28b2 [deepseek-v4] #- Option B (indexed palette): Stick with `colorpump/colorfifo` for a fixed palette of 4
1e3e28b2 [deepseek-v4] #colours, each with full flexibility of waveform shape. This is simpler for teletext or retro
1e3e28b3 [deepseek-v4] #graphics.
1e3e28b3 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b3 [deepseek-v4] #• Potential improvements*:
1e3e28b3 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b4 [deepseek-v4] #1. Avoid multiple FIFO passes: Instead of three state machines, you could combine
1e3e28b4 [deepseek-v4] #`pixelpump` and `onebit` into one state machine that loads two patterns and outputs directly to
1e3e28b4 [deepseek-v4] #pins. But that loses modularity.
1e3e28b5 [deepseek-v4] #2. Check pin direction timing: Every `out pindirs, 3` updates the pin direction (pin as
1e3e28b5 [deepseek-v4] #output). You should ensure that between lines the pins are set to input (or pulled low) to prevent
1e3e28b5 [deepseek-v4] #glitches during H‑sync.
1e3e28b5 [deepseek-v4] #3. Adjust `threepin` cycle count: You have 7 `out pindirs` but earlier you wrote “10 pixel
1e3e28b6 [deepseek-v4] #cycles” – the comment in `colorfifo.pio` also says “6 cycles + 4 housekeeping”. Align these: if a
1e3e28b6 [deepseek-v4] #pixel is 10 cycles, you need 10 `out pindirs` grouped, not 7. The current `threepin` does 7 + 1
1e3e28b6 [deepseek-v4] #(set) + 11 dummy = 19? Actually 7×3=21 bits, then `set pindirs,0` takes a cycle, then `out null,11`
1e3e28b6 [deepseek-v4] #consumes 11 cycles? But `out null` doesn’t advance the program counter in the same way – check PIO
1e3e28b7 [deepseek-v4] #manual: `out null` does consume a cycle but does not change any output. So total = 7+1+1+1+11=21
1e3e28b7 [deepseek-v4] #cycles? This is inconsistent with 10‑cycle pixel. You probably want exactly 10 cycles per pixel: 6
1e3e28b7 [deepseek-v4] #waveform groups + 1 zero group + 3 no‑op (or `set pindirs,0` and two `nop`). The comment in
1e3e28b7 [deepseek-v4] #`colorfifo.pio` says “6 cycles + 4 housekeeping” – that’s 10 cycles total. Revise `threepin`
1e3e28b8 [deepseek-v4] #accordingly.
1e3e28b8 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b8 [deepseek-v4] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e3e28b9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28b9 [deepseek-v4] #Summary
1e3e28b9 [deepseek-v4] #- You have two clever but separate frameworks. Decide which one to use for the final video mode (or
1e3e28b9 [deepseek-v4] #combine them with a mux).
1e3e28ba [deepseek-v4] #- Pay attention to exact cycle counts – a single cycle error in a 10‑cycle pixel will cause colour
1e3e28ba [deepseek-v4] #shift.
1e3e28ba [deepseek-v4] #- IRQ sync is delicate: ensure the pixel source state machine knows exactly when to start pushing
1e3e28ba [deepseek-v4] #data after the back porch. Use DMA or CPU carefully.
1e3e28bb [deepseek-v4] #
1e3e28bb [deepseek-v4] #Would you like me to suggest a concrete cycle‑accurate rewrite of `threepin` for the 10‑cycle
1e3e28bb [deepseek-v4] #pixel, or help integrate the two colour approaches?
1e3e28bb [deepseek-v4] #
