1e3ea981 [deepseek-v4] #Yes, adding a second GPIO pin (driven as a digital output) with a resistor to the video output can
1e3ea981 [deepseek-v4] #contribute additional brightness levels. In your circuit, you already have one luma pin (LUMA)
1e3ea981 [deepseek-v4] #through 150 Ω. Adding a second pin (GREY) through another 150 Ω creates a simple two‑bit
1e3ea981 [deepseek-v4] #resistor DAC.
1e3ea981 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea982 [deepseek-v4] #How it works
1e3ea982 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea982 [deepseek-v4] #Assume:
1e3ea982 [deepseek-v4] #- 3.3 V supply
1e3ea983 [deepseek-v4] #- 120 Ω pull‑up to video out
1e3ea983 [deepseek-v4] #- Two GPIO pins, each with a 150 Ω resistor to the output
1e3ea983 [deepseek-v4] #- When a pin is high (3.3 V), it adds current through its resistor toward the output node.
1e3ea984 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea984 [deepseek-v4] #The output voltage for each combination of pin states is determined by the parallel/series network.
1e3ea984 [deepseek-v4] #With both pins high, you get the maximum white level; both low gives black (zero output, because
1e3ea984 [deepseek-v4] #the pull‑up is the only path). The three intermediate states (one pin high, the other low) give two
1e3ea985 [deepseek-v4] #distinct intermediate voltages if the resistors are equal? Actually, if both resistors are equal,
1e3ea985 [deepseek-v4] #the two cases (only LUMA high, only GREY high) produce the same output voltage because the
1e3ea985 [deepseek-v4] #circuit is symmetric. So you would only get three distinct levels: 0, 1, and 2 (with both
1e3ea985 [deepseek-v4] #high). That’s still a meaningful increase from one bit (two levels).
1e3ea986 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea986 [deepseek-v4] #Making it more useful: weighted resistors
1e3ea986 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea987 [deepseek-v4] #To get four evenly‑spaced levels (i.e., 2‑bit greyscale), use binary‑weighted resistors.
1e3ea987 [deepseek-v4] #For example:
1e3ea987 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea987 [deepseek-v4] #- LUMA pin: 150 Ω (most significant bit – contributes roughly 2/3 of the total current when
1e3ea988 [deepseek-v4] #high)
1e3ea988 [deepseek-v4] #- GREY pin: 300 Ω (least significant bit – contributes half the current of LUMA)
1e3ea988 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea988 [deepseek-v4] #Then the output voltage will have four distinct steps: 0, V1, V2, V1+V2 (roughly linear). This
1e3ea989 [deepseek-v4] #gives meaningful brightness variation.
1e3ea989 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea989 [deepseek-v4] #Example voltage calculation (with 150 Ω and 300 Ω)
1e3ea989 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98a [deepseek-v4] #- Pull‑up: 120 Ω to 3.3 V
1e3ea98a [deepseek-v4] #- When a pin is high, it connects through its resistor to 3.3 V. When low, it’s effectively open
1e3ea98a [deepseek-v4] #(or 0 V through a small output impedance – assume ideal digital output).
1e3ea98a [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98b [deepseek-v4] #For the four states:
1e3ea98b [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98b [deepseek-v4] #╭────────────────┬────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────╮
1e3ea98c [deepseek-v4] #│  LUMA (150 Ω)  │  GREY (300 Ω)  │  Equivalent R to 3.3 V (aside from 120 Ω)  │  Output voltage (into 75 Ω load)  │
1e3ea98c [deepseek-v4] #├────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────┤
1e3ea98c [deepseek-v4] #│  low           │  low           │  only 120 Ω pull‑up                        │  ≈ 0.98 V (sync level?)           │
1e3ea98c [deepseek-v4] #│  low           │  high          │  120 Ω ∥ 300 Ω                             │  ≈ 1.54 V                         │
1e3ea98d [deepseek-v4] #│  high          │  low           │  120 Ω ∥ 150 Ω                             │  ≈ 1.79 V                         │
1e3ea98d [deepseek-v4] #│  high          │  high          │  120 Ω ∥ 150 Ω ∥ 300 Ω                     │  ≈ 2.22 V                         │
1e3ea98d [deepseek-v4] #╰────────────────┴────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────╯
1e3ea98d [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98e [deepseek-v4] #Those are distinct and usable for luma (assuming 75 Ω termination). The steps are not perfectly
1e3ea98e [deepseek-v4] #linear but are meaningful.
1e3ea98e [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98e [deepseek-v4] #Conclusion
1e3ea98f [deepseek-v4] #
1e3ea98f [deepseek-v4] #Yes, adding a grey pin through a resistor contributes to brightness. For meaningful levels,
1e3ea98f [deepseek-v4] #use binary‑weighted resistors (e.g., 150 Ω and 300 Ω) rather than equal values. Even with
1e3ea990 [deepseek-v4] #equal resistors you get three levels, which is still an improvement over one bit.
1e3ea990 [deepseek-v4] #
