1e3f1d34 [deepseek-v4] #If you prefer separate machines, ensure each machine outputs both direction and data for its pin.
1e3f1d34 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f1d34 [deepseek-v4] #• Conclusion*: `grey.pio` is a start but needs `out pins` and the `.fifo txget` directive.
1e3f1d34 [deepseek-v4] #For a tristate system, always control both direction and data to avoid undefined output levels.
1e3f1d34 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f1d35 [roha]  ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.4 ⛲  deepseek-v4 🐋 🪠 0.7° $0.005 91.74KB 16.46s
1e3f27d3 [deepseek-v4] #Your updated `grey.pio` now uses `.fifo txget` and depends on initial C++ setting the pin output
1e3f27d3 [deepseek-v4] #high. This approach is entirely valid for a tristate DAC: the pin drives high (3.3 V) whenever its
1e3f27d3 [deepseek-v4] #direction is 1, and is high‑Z when direction is 0. Since the output data register stays high, you
1e3f27d3 [deepseek-v4] #get two logic states: high or high‑Z. Combined with the LUMA pin (also controlled similarly), you
1e3f27d4 [deepseek-v4] #achieve four distinct luma levels as described earlier.
1e3f27d4 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d4 [deepseek-v4] #• However, I see a critical timing issue with the pixel trigger handling.*
1e3f27d4 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d5 [deepseek-v4] #The `stall` loop problem
1e3f27d5 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d5 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d5 [deepseek-v4] #stall:
1e3f27d6 [deepseek-v4] #    jmp    pin stall      ; wait while pin is high
1e3f27d6 [deepseek-v4] #    mov    y, pins
1e3f27d6 [deepseek-v4] #    mov    osr, rxfifo[y]
1e3f27d6 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1     ; 6 cycles of pattern
1e3f27d7 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27d7 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27d7 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27d7 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27d8 [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27d8 [deepseek-v4] #    set    pindirs, 0
1e3f27d8 [deepseek-v4] #.wrap
1e3f27d9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27d9 [deepseek-v4] #- The first instruction spins as long as the trigger pin is high.
1e3f27d9 [deepseek-v4] #- When the trigger pin goes low, execution falls through to the pixel output.
1e3f27da [deepseek-v4] #- After 7 cycles (6 `out` + 1 `set`), the program wraps back to `stall:`.
1e3f27da [deepseek-v4] #- If the trigger pin is still low at that moment, the `jmp pin stall` will immediately
1e3f27da [deepseek-v4] #fall through again, causing a second pixel output without waiting for the next line.
1e3f27da [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27db [deepseek-v4] #For a 10‑cycle pixel, the pin likely stays low for the entire pixel period (≈60 ns). After your
1e3f27db [deepseek-v4] #7‑cycle output, there are still 3 cycles left in the pixel. The pin is still low, so the program
1e3f27db [deepseek-v4] #will instantly start a new pixel – breaking the horizontal timing.
1e3f27db [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27db [deepseek-v4] #Fix: Wait for pin to go high again
1e3f27dc [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27dc [deepseek-v4] #Insert a loop that waits for the trigger pin to return high before accepting the next trigger. For
1e3f27dc [deepseek-v4] #example:
1e3f27dd [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27dd [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27dd [deepseek-v4] #stall:
1e3f27dd [deepseek-v4] #    jmp    pin stall       ; wait while pin high
1e3f27de [deepseek-v4] #    mov    y, pins
1e3f27de [deepseek-v4] #    mov    osr, rxfifo[y]
1e3f27de [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27de [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27df [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27df [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27df [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27df [deepseek-v4] #    out    pindirs, 1
1e3f27e0 [deepseek-v4] #    set    pindirs, 0
1e3f27e0 [deepseek-v4] #wait_high:
1e3f27e0 [deepseek-v4] #    jmp    pin wait_high   ; wait while pin low
1e3f27e1 [deepseek-v4] #.wrap
1e3f27e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e1 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e1 [deepseek-v4] #Now the state machine will not start the next pixel until the trigger pin has gone high and
1e3f27e1 [deepseek-v4] #low again. This matches the expected behaviour of a pulse‑triggered pixel.
1e3f27e2 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e2 [deepseek-v4] #Additional notes
1e3f27e2 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e2 [deepseek-v4] #- Your C++ initialisation sets the pin to output high. That remains unchanged – the PIO only
1e3f27e3 [deepseek-v4] #toggles direction. This is correct.
1e3f27e3 [deepseek-v4] #- The `rxfifo[y]` is pre‑loaded with four 32‑bit words. Each word’s lower 6 bits control the 6 `out
1e3f27e3 [deepseek-v4] #pindirs` instructions. The 7th cycle forces direction 0 (high‑Z). The remaining 3 cycles are now
1e3f27e3 [deepseek-v4] #consumed by the `waithigh` loop? Actually after `set` you have 1 cycle, then the `waithigh`
1e3f27e3 [deepseek-v4] #loop will spin until pin goes high. That could take variable cycles – not constant. But that’s fine
1e3f27e4 [deepseek-v4] #because the next pixel must not start until the trigger pin rises again, which should happen at the
1e3f27e4 [deepseek-v4] #end of the pixel (after 10 cycles total). The waiting loop adds a variable delay but it is bounded
1e3f27e4 [deepseek-v4] #by the time the pin stays low. If the pin is driven low for exactly 10 cycles by the caller, then
1e3f27e4 [deepseek-v4] #the `wait_high` loop will wait for the remaining 3 cycles (since the 7 `out`+`set` cycles already
1e3f27e5 [deepseek-v4] #consumed 7). That will give the exact 10‑cycle timing.
1e3f27e5 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e5 [deepseek-v4] #   Actually, you could also replace the `set pindirs,0` with a `nop` and let the `wait_high` loop
1e3f27e5 [deepseek-v4] #consume the remaining cycles. But as long as the trigger pin timing is precise, this works.
1e3f27e6 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e6 [deepseek-v4] #Summary
1e3f27e6 [deepseek-v4] #
1e3f27e6 [deepseek-v4] #- Using initial high output + direction‑only control is a valid, efficient way to drive a tristate
1e3f27e7 [deepseek-v4] #DAC.
1e3f27e7 [deepseek-v4] #- Add the `wait_high` loop to prevent premature re‑triggering.
1e3f27e7 [deepseek-v4] #- Otherwise the PIO code is sound for producing a 6‑cycle pulse (or any pattern) followed by high‑Z
1e3f27e7 [deepseek-v4] #for the rest of the pixel.
1e3f27e8 [deepseek-v4] #
