1e523dcf [deepseek-v4] #The `greyline.pio` program is new to the collection. It implements a simple grey‑level output for
1e523dcf [deepseek-v4] #the luma pin (GP18) using a 6‑cycle per pixel pulse‑train, selected from four pre‑loaded patterns
1e523dcf [deepseek-v4] #in the RX FIFO. This matches the “colorfifo” concept described in `colorpump.md`, but for a
1e523dcf [deepseek-v4] #single‑bit (monochrome) output.
1e523dd0 [deepseek-v4] #
1e523dd0 [deepseek-v4] #Program flow:
1e523dd0 [deepseek-v4] #1. `set pindirs, 0` – tristate the output pin (high‑impedance, pulled high by external
1e523dd0 [deepseek-v4] #resistor as noted in comments).
1e523dd1 [deepseek-v4] #2. `wait 1 irq 5` – pause until the video timing state machine (`vidbit.pio`) asserts IRQ 5
1e523dd1 [deepseek-v4] #at the start of each active‑video pixel.
1e523dd1 [deepseek-v4] #3. `mov y, pins` – read two input pins (presumably GPIO 0 and 1) as an index 0–3 selecting
1e523dd1 [deepseek-v4] #one of four pre‑loaded pulse trains.
1e523dd2 [deepseek-v4] #4. `mov osr, rxfifo[y]` – fetch the 32‑bit pattern from the RX FIFO using the `txget` fifo
1e523dd2 [deepseek-v4] #encoding.
1e523dd2 [deepseek-v4] #5. Six consecutive `out pindirs, 1` – shift out the lower 6 bits of the pattern, one bit
1e523dd3 [deepseek-v4] #per PIO cycle, driving the pin as output (1 = on, 0 = off) for a 6‑cycle sub‑pixel sequence.
1e523dd3 [deepseek-v4] #6. `.wrap` – restart the loop, tristating the pin again.
1e523dd3 [deepseek-v4] #
1e523dd3 [deepseek-v4] #Integration with existing code:
1e523dd4 [deepseek-v4] #- In `vidbit.cpp`, `greyinit()` pre‑loads four patterns from `pdmpatterns[]` (0..5 bits
1e523dd4 [deepseek-v4] #each, padded to 32 bits) into the greyline SM’s RX FIFO.
1e523dd4 [deepseek-v4] #- The two‑bit index comes from the colorpump PIO state machine, which drives GPIO 0 and 1
1e523dd4 [deepseek-v4] #with a 2‑bit colour index for each pixel (see `colorpump.pio`). Thus the greyline SM outputs a
1e523dd5 [deepseek-v4] #different 6‑step greyscale waveform for each of the four colour indices.
1e523dd5 [deepseek-v4] #- The 6‑cycle‑per‑pixel structure matches the `colorfifo.pio` design, enabling a simple form of
1e523dd5 [deepseek-v4] #monochrome PWM (6 levels) for each pixel.
1e523dd5 [deepseek-v4] #
1e523dd6 [deepseek-v4] #Potential issues / checks:
1e523dd6 [deepseek-v4] #- The `txget` encoding consumes an RX FIFO entry each pixel. The RX FIFO is 4‑deep; it will drain
1e523dd6 [deepseek-v4] #in 4 pixels. The C++ code only pre‑loads 4 entries once during init. After those 4 entries are
1e523dd7 [deepseek-v4] #consumed, the SM will begin reading stale data (or stall if the FIFO empties and the SM is not
1e523dd7 [deepseek-v4] #configured to stall). The preloading must be repeated per frame or per line unless the
1e523dd7 [deepseek-v4] #entries are re‑filled by DMA. The current `grey_init` only does one‑time preload; the SM will run
1e523dd7 [deepseek-v4] #out after 4 pixels. This is a critical bug. Either a DMA channel should feed the RX FIFO
1e523dd8 [deepseek-v4] #repeatedly with the same 4 patterns (ring buffer), or the preloading must happen in a loop. Since
1e523dd8 [deepseek-v4] #the program uses `.fifo txget` (RX FIFO), it cannot be refilled by the same SM; it must be refilled
1e523dd8 [deepseek-v4] #externally (e.g., by CPU or another DMA). The current design will fail after the fourth pixel.
1e523dd8 [deepseek-v4] #
1e523dd9 [deepseek-v4] #- The `set pindirs, 0` tristates the pin between pixels. Ensure that the pin’s pull‑up or resistor
1e523dd9 [deepseek-v4] #network maintains the desired high level during the tristate period. The comment says “c++
1e523dd9 [deepseek-v4] #initialises tristate pin output as high” – likely an external pull‑up resistor to 3.3V.
1e523dd9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e523dda [deepseek-v4] #- The SM clock divider is not set in the C++ code (default is 1). At 166.5 MHz, 6 cycles per pixel
1e523dda [deepseek-v4] #takes ~36 ns, which is fine for a single pixel’s grey level. However, the SM must be synchronised
1e523dda [deepseek-v4] #to the `vidbit` state machine’s IRQ5 timing – `vidbit.pio` sets IRQ5 once per pixel during the
1e523ddb [deepseek-v4] #active video portion. The frequency of IRQ5 matches the SM’s speed, so no clock division is needed.
1e523ddb [deepseek-v4] #
1e523ddb [deepseek-v4] #Summary:
1e523ddb [deepseek-v4] #The `greyline.pio` program is a neat, minimal implementation of a 4‑colour, 6‑step greyscale
1e523ddb [deepseek-v4] #modulator. The main issue is that the RX FIFO is only pre‑loaded once, causing the output
1e523ddc [deepseek-v4] #to fail after the first 4 pixels of a frame. A DMA ring buffer feeding the same 4 words repeatedly
1e523ddc [deepseek-v4] #would solve this. Alternatively, the SM could be redesigned to read from a simple counter and not
1e523ddc [deepseek-v4] #require FIFO refill – but that would lose the ability to change patterns per colour index
1e523ddc [deepseek-v4] #dynamically.
1e523ddd [deepseek-v4] #
