1e53e925 [claude-haiku-4-5] #Technical Notes
1e53e925 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e925 [claude-haiku-4-5] #1. Indexed RX FIFO Usage (greyline.pio confirmation)
1e53e925 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e926 [claude-haiku-4-5] #Your `.fifo txget` directive is correct. The datasheet (11.4.9) confirms:
1e53e926 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e926 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e926 [claude-haiku-4-5] #mov osr, rxfifo[y]        ; RP2350 v1 only
1e53e927 [claude-haiku-4-5] #mov osr, rxfifo[<index>]  ; Index 0-3
1e53e927 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e927 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e927 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Requires:* `SHIFTCTRLFJOINRX_GET` set (pioasm handles this automatically).
1e53e928 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e928 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Your greyinit() issue: You're using `piosmputblocking()` to preload
1e53e928 [claude-haiku-4-5] #patterns, but with `.fifo txget`, the system write goes to indexed RX FIFO storage*, not
1e53e928 [claude-haiku-4-5] #the normal TX FIFO. The SDK may not expose the `RXF_PUTGET` registers directly.
1e53e929 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e929 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Fix (direct register access):*
1e53e929 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e929 [claude-haiku-4-5] #// In grey_init(), replace the loop with:
1e53e92a [claude-haiku-4-5] #for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
1e53e92a [claude-haiku-4-5] #    pio->sm[sm].rxf_putget[i] = (uint32_t)pdm_patterns[i];
1e53e92a [claude-haiku-4-5] #}
1e53e92a [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92a [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92b [claude-haiku-4-5] #This assumes `rxf_putget` array exists in the SDK headers. If not, you'll need:
1e53e92b [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92b [claude-haiku-4-5] ##define RXF_PUTGET(sm, idx) (pio_hw_t*)(pio0)->sm[sm].__base + 0x128 + (idx * 4)
1e53e92c [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92c [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92c [claude-haiku-4-5] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e53e92c [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92c [claude-haiku-4-5] #2. Timing Critique: greyline.pio
1e53e92d [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92d [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e92d [claude-haiku-4-5] #.program greyline
1e53e92d [claude-haiku-4-5] #.fifo txget
1e53e92e [claude-haiku-4-5] #set pindirs, 0           ; 1 cycle
1e53e92e [claude-haiku-4-5] #wait 1 irq 6             ; 1+ cycles (stalls if IRQ not set)
1e53e92e [claude-haiku-4-5] #mov y, pins              ; 1 cycle (reads GP46-47)
1e53e92e [claude-haiku-4-5] #mov osr, rxfifo[y]       ; 1 cycle (indexed fetch)
1e53e92f [claude-haiku-4-5] #out pindirs, 1           ; 6 times × 1 cycle = 6 cycles
1e53e92f [claude-haiku-4-5] #set pindirs, 0           ; 1 cycle
1e53e92f [claude-haiku-4-5] #                         ; Total: ~10-12 cycles
1e53e92f [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e930 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e930 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Constraint: You have 10 cycles/pixel* (166.5 MHz / 10656 cycles per 64µs line).
1e53e930 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e930 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- The 6 × `out pindirs, 1` instructions consume 6 cycles.
1e53e931 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- `wait 1 irq 6` can stall, consuming extra cycles if IRQ6 is delayed.
1e53e931 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- Risk: If IRQ6 isn't asserted every 10 cycles precisely, you'll slip timing.
1e53e931 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e931 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Recommendation:* Verify that `vidbit.pio` asserts IRQ6 with cycle-exact timing via `irq
1e53e932 [claude-haiku-4-5] #set 6` in the active pixel region.
1e53e932 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e932 [claude-haiku-4-5] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1e53e932 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e933 [claude-haiku-4-5] #3. colorfifo.pio vs. colorpump.pio Coordination
1e53e933 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e933 [claude-haiku-4-5] #From your markdown:
1e53e933 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e934 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e934 [claude-haiku-4-5] #; colorfifo waits on jmp pin 2, then reads indexed RX FIFO
1e53e934 [claude-haiku-4-5] #; colorpump outputs 2-bit color index on pins, pulses side-set to trigger colorfifo
1e53e934 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e935 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e53e935 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Architecture looks sound*, but:
