1e79ec1b [claude-haiku-4-5] #Here are the main approaches to enumerate Windows COM ports in C++:
1e79ec1b [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec1c [claude-haiku-4-5] #• 1. Registry Query (Most Common)*
1e79ec1c [claude-haiku-4-5] #Query `HKEYLOCALMACHINE\HARDWARE\DEVICEMAP\SERIALCOMM` for serial port mappings.
1e79ec1c [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec1c [claude-haiku-4-5] #• 2. WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation)*
1e79ec1d [claude-haiku-4-5] #Query Win32_SerialPort class for detailed port information.
1e79ec1d [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec1d [claude-haiku-4-5] #• 3. SetupAPI*
1e79ec1d [claude-haiku-4-5] #Use device setup functions to enumerate serial devices with full control over filtering and
1e79ec1e [claude-haiku-4-5] #properties.
1e79ec1e [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec1e [claude-haiku-4-5] #• 4. Direct Registry Enumeration*
1e79ec1e [claude-haiku-4-5] #Walk `HKEYLOCALMACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Enum\PCI` or USB paths for connected
1e79ec1f [claude-haiku-4-5] #devices.
1e79ec1f [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec1f [claude-haiku-4-5] #• 5. COM Port Brute Force*
1e79ec1f [claude-haiku-4-5] #Simply attempt to open `COM1` through `COM256` and catch failures (crude but functional).
1e79ec20 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec20 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Recommendation for your use case:*
1e79ec20 [claude-haiku-4-5] #Given the UF2/microcontroller context, SetupAPI or Registry query would be most
1e79ec20 [claude-haiku-4-5] #reliable. SetupAPI is more robust for detecting newly connected devices.
1e79ec21 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e79ec21 [claude-haiku-4-5] #Which approach interests you? I can provide working code if you'd like to implement one.
1e79ec21 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
