1e7c865f [claude-haiku-4-5] #Impressive architecture. This is a sophisticated RP2350-based PAL video generator with multiple
1e7c865f [claude-haiku-4-5] #signal pipelines. Key observations:
1e7c8660 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8660 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Signal Pipeline Architecture:*
1e7c8660 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- `pixelpump` → `onebit` → `threepin` chain creates component video
1e7c8660 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- Pixel bit-trains fed through state machine FIFO as waveform data
1e7c8661 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- 27 words × 32 bits = 864 pixel line width
1e7c8661 [claude-haiku-4-5] #- 10656 cycles/line @ 166.5 MHz = 64µs PAL line period ✓
1e7c8661 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8661 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Novel Aspects:*
1e7c8662 [claude-haiku-4-5] #1. Indexed RX FIFO (`mov osr, rxfifo[y]`) in `onebit.pio` — lookup table driven by pixel
1e7c8662 [claude-haiku-4-5] #state (GPIO46 loopback). This is RP2350 v1 exclusive.
1e7c8662 [claude-haiku-4-5] #2. Tri-state output via `pindirs` in `threepin.pio` — elegant resistor DAC control (3 pins
1e7c8662 [claude-haiku-4-5] #= 8 levels per channel).
1e7c8663 [claude-haiku-4-5] #3. IRQ-gated line synchronisation — `wait 1 irq 0` keeps pipelines aligned across frames.
1e7c8663 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8663 [claude-haiku-4-5] #• Questions / Observations:*
1e7c8663 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8664 [claude-haiku-4-5] #1. onebit loopback (GPIO46): Is this pin physically wired back to SM input, or virtual (PIO
1e7c8664 [claude-haiku-4-5] #internal)? If physical, EMI risk; if virtual, need `smconfigsetjmppin()` in C code.
1e7c8664 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8664 [claude-haiku-4-5] #2. threepin pindirs loop: 10 × `out pindirs, 3` = 30 bits + 2 skip = 32. This drives
1e7c8665 [claude-haiku-4-5] #direction (Hi-Z vs pull-down) for 3-pin resistor DAC. Current implementation appears to output
1e7c8665 [claude-haiku-4-5] #pre-computed waveforms. Is the waveform stored as bit-packed 3-bit samples in FIFO?
1e7c8665 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8665 [claude-haiku-4-5] #3. CDC comms in vidbit.cpp: The `cdcReadLine()` / `flush()` pattern with
1e7c8666 [claude-haiku-4-5] #`tudcdcwrite()` looks solid. Suggest adding flow control check before `tud_task()`:
1e7c8666 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8666 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8666 [claude-haiku-4-5] #if (!tud_cdc_connected()) {
1e7c8667 [claude-haiku-4-5] #    running = false;
1e7c8667 [claude-haiku-4-5] #}
1e7c8667 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8667 [claude-haiku-4-5] #
1e7c8668 [claude-haiku-4-5] #4. Frame buffer memory: `progressiveFrame` / `evenFrame` / `oddFrame` arrays are large (27
1e7c8668 [claude-haiku-4-5] #words × 305+ lines). Are these in SRAM or PSRAM? If SRAM, watch heap fragmentation during video
1e7c8668 [claude-haiku-4-5] #updates.
