1e7d27d1 [deepseek-v4] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  deepseek-v4 🐋 🪠 0.7° $0.134 1.196MB 10.14s
1e7d27d1 [deepseek-v4] #Based on the files you shared, the term "hub" most likely refers to the HUB75
1e7d27d2 [deepseek-v4] #interface used in the `hub75` example. That example demonstrates driving a RGB LED matrix panel
1e7d27d2 [deepseek-v4] #(1/32‑scan) using PIO.
1e7d27d2 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d2 [deepseek-v4] #What is HUB75?
1e7d27d3 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d3 [deepseek-v4] #HUB75 is a standard connector interface for large RGB LED panels (commonly found in advertising
1e7d27d3 [deepseek-v4] #displays, scoreboards, and decorative lighting). It gets its name from the 75‑pin connector (often
1e7d27d3 [deepseek-v4] #two rows of pins) used to connect the panel to a controller.
1e7d27d4 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d4 [deepseek-v4] #Key characteristics of the HUB75 interface (from the readme and code):
1e7d27d4 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d4 [deepseek-v4] #- 6 colour‑data lines (R0, G0, B0 for the upper half of the screen; R1, G1, B1 for the
1e7d27d5 [deepseek-v4] #lower half)
1e7d27d5 [deepseek-v4] #- 5 row‑select lines (A, B, C, D, E) to select one of 32 rows
1e7d27d5 [deepseek-v4] #- Clock (CLK) – shifts data into the panel’s shift registers
1e7d27d5 [deepseek-v4] #- Strobe (STB) / Latch – latches the shifted row data into the output
1e7d27d6 [deepseek-v4] #- Output Enable (OEn) – turns the LEDs on/off, used for PWM dimming
1e7d27d6 [deepseek-v4] #- Ground pins
1e7d27d6 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d6 [deepseek-v4] #The Pio example (`hub75.c` and `hub75.pio`) implements the complete timing to drive such a panel:
1e7d27d7 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d7 [deepseek-v4] #- Two PIO state machines are used:
1e7d27d7 [deepseek-v4] #  - One to shift pixel data for RGB888 (or RGB565) into the panel’s shift registers.
1e7d27d7 [deepseek-v4] #  - Another to control row selection, latch, and output‑enable timing.
1e7d27d8 [deepseek-v4] #- The algorithm uses bit‑plane PWM: it sends the same frame 8 times, each time outputting a
1e7d27d8 [deepseek-v4] #different bit of the colour data, while the other state machine controls the PWM pulse width (1, 2,
1e7d27d8 [deepseek-v4] #4, … 128 units) to build up 8‑bit colour depth.
1e7d27d8 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d9 [deepseek-v4] #Practical use
1e7d27d9 [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27d9 [deepseek-v4] #If you have a HUB75‑compatible 64×32 or 128×64 RGB panel (often 1/16 or 1/32 scan), you can use
1e7d27d9 [deepseek-v4] #this example with minimal wiring changes. The readme gives the exact pin mapping, and the image
1e7d27da [deepseek-v4] #file `mountains128x64rgb565.h` is a pre‑converted test image.
1e7d27da [deepseek-v4] #
1e7d27da [deepseek-v4] #In summary, “hub” in this context means the standard HUB75 interface for driving large RGB
1e7d27da [deepseek-v4] #LED matrices using PIO‑based state machines. Let me know if you want a deeper dive into the code or
1e7d27db [deepseek-v4] #help adapting it to a different panel size.
1e7d27db [deepseek-v4] #
