1e951484 [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.098 313.5KB 67.14s
1e951484 [kimi-k2.6] #This is the first time I have seen this particular project. It is a sophisticated, multi-layered
1e951484 [kimi-k2.6] #RP2350 video stack — significantly more involved than typical PIO VGA examples. A few observations
1e951485 [kimi-k2.6] #on what stands out, and a handful of items you may want to verify.
1e951485 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951485 [kimi-k2.6] #What is novel here
1e951485 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951486 [kimi-k2.6] #• RP2350 v1 PIO extensions used heavily. You are exploiting `FJOINRXGET` / `.fifo
1e951486 [kimi-k2.6] #txget` for hardware lookup tables in `greyline.pio` and `colorfifo.pio`. Using `mov osr, rxfifo[y]`
1e951486 [kimi-k2.6] #as a palette/PDM index is exactly the kind of thing the RP2350 datasheet hints at but few
1e951486 [kimi-k2.6] #implementations actually use.
1e951487 [kimi-k2.6] #• Multi-stage pixel pipeline. The `pixelpump → onebit → threepin` chain is an unusual
1e951487 [kimi-k2.6] #architecture. Decoupling the pixel source, bit-selector, and pin driver into separate state
1e951487 [kimi-k2.6] #machines lets you swap colour depths or output standards without rewriting the timing-critical
1e951487 [kimi-k2.6] #front end.
1e951487 [kimi-k2.6] #• PAL 576i with chroma in PIO. Generating the 4.43361875 MHz subcarrier (or 4× it at ~17.73
1e951488 [kimi-k2.6] #MHz) from a 166.5 MHz sysclk inside `chroma.pio` is ambitious. The 2-bit resistor DAC with a
1e951488 [kimi-k2.6] #reconstruction filter is a pragmatic low-parts-count approach.
1e951488 [kimi-k2.6] #• WST teletext injection. Doing World System Teletext encoding in the blanking interval —
1e951488 [kimi-k2.6] #including Hamming 8/4 and parity — is rare in hobby firmware. The `wst.pio` program is pleasingly
1e951489 [kimi-k2.6] #minimal.
1e951489 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951489 [kimi-k2.6] #Things worth a second look
1e951489 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95148a [kimi-k2.6] #1.  `hilo32.pio` counter initialisation.
1e95148a [kimi-k2.6] #    `set x, 0` followed by `jmp x--, nothi` will fall through immediately because X is zero on the
1e95148a [kimi-k2.6] #first test. The decrement wraps X to `0xFFFFFFFF`, but the loop only runs once before falling
1e95148a [kimi-k2.6] #through to `hi`. If you intended a timeout or pulse-width measurement, you probably want `set x,
1e95148b [kimi-k2.6] #31` (the largest immediate available to `SET`) or seed X from another register.
1e95148b [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95148b [kimi-k2.6] #2.  `interleave.pio` appears truncated.
1e95148b [kimi-k2.6] #    The program ends mid-instruction (`in x, 32` with no `.wrap` or terminator). If this is
1e95148c [kimi-k2.6] #work-in-progress, disregard; otherwise the assembler will likely reject it or it will run into the
1e95148c [kimi-k2.6] #next instruction slot.
1e95148c [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95148c [kimi-k2.6] #3.  `spdif.pio` is a stub.
1e95148d [kimi-k2.6] #    Only a `nop [1]` and `.wrap` are present. Not a problem if it is a placeholder, but the comment
1e95148d [kimi-k2.6] #suggests a biphase-mark decoder is intended.
1e95148d [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95148d [kimi-k2.6] #4.  `colorpump.pio` selector decoding.
1e95148e [kimi-k2.6] #    The `set pins, 14` / `13` / `11` / `7` values are active-low one-hot patterns assuming a 4-pin
1e95148e [kimi-k2.6] #`SET` group. This is correct if the upper 4 bits of an 8-bit port are being pulled low, but the
1e95148e [kimi-k2.6] #comment mentions pins 14, 13, 11, 7 as decimal pin numbers. If those are meant as GPIO indices,
1e95148e [kimi-k2.6] #`set pins` does not map that way — it writes to the `SET` pin group base. Just verify the
1e95148f [kimi-k2.6] #`SETBASE` and `SETCOUNT` configuration in the C++ init matches the bitmask intent.
1e95148f [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95148f [kimi-k2.6] #5.  DMA ring buffer size for chroma.
1e95148f [kimi-k2.6] #    `chromadmainit` configures `channelconfigset_ring(&c, true, 10)` (1024-byte
1e951490 [kimi-k2.6] #wrap) over a `colorWords*2` array. If `colorWords` is 128, the array is 1024 bytes, which aligns
1e951490 [kimi-k2.6] #exactly. If you ever change `colorWords`, the ring size will need to stay a power-of-two match.
1e951490 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951490 [kimi-k2.6] #6.  `vidbit.cpp` missing header.
1e951491 [kimi-k2.6] #    The file includes `<colorbit.h>`, which was not in the shared set. If it defines
1e951491 [kimi-k2.6] #`colorpumpinit`, `colorpumpdma_init`, and `colorTestAddress()`, everything is consistent;
1e951491 [kimi-k2.6] #otherwise the `#ifdef COLOR` block will not compile.
1e951491 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951492 [kimi-k2.6] #General architectural notes
1e951492 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951492 [kimi-k2.6] #• Your use of IRQ flags for horizontal sync lock between `vidbit.pio`, `greyline.pio`, and the
1e951492 [kimi-k2.6] #chroma pump is clean. On RP2350 you could also use `irq next` / `irq prev` if you ever need to
1e951493 [kimi-k2.6] #synchronise across PIO blocks, though keeping everything on `pio0`/`pio1` as you have done reduces
1e951493 [kimi-k2.6] #latency.
1e951493 [kimi-k2.6] #• The `onebit.pio` approach of pushing the selected waveform back into an RX FIFO for `threepin` to
1e951493 [kimi-k2.6] #consume is a nice way to bridge two state machines without burning GPIOs for parallel data. Just
1e951494 [kimi-k2.6] #ensure the FIFO depth is sufficient — at 166.5 MHz and 864 pixels/line, the 4-entry FIFOs empty
1e951494 [kimi-k2.6] #fast unless the DMA is constantly topping them up.
1e951494 [kimi-k2.6] #• The `json.h` parser is surprisingly full-featured for an embedded project. On an RP2350 with 520
1e951494 [kimi-k2.6] #kB SRAM it is fine, but if you ever port to the smaller-RAM variants, the `std::wstring` / `utf32`
1e951495 [kimi-k2.6] #conversion buffers and `std::stringstream` usage will dominate your heap.
1e951495 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951495 [kimi-k2.6] #Overall this is one of the more advanced bare-metal RP2350 video implementations I have
1e951495 [kimi-k2.6] #encountered. The combination of indexed-FIFO palette tricks, interlaced DMA frame buffers, and
1e951496 [kimi-k2.6] #in-band PIO teletext suggests you are pushing the hardware closer to its practical limits than most
1e951496 [kimi-k2.6] #reference designs. If you want a second pair of eyes on a specific PIO timing calculation or the
1e951496 [kimi-k2.6] #chroma filter design, feel free to narrow the scope.
1e951496 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e951dda [nitro@ryzen5] lets focus on the colorpump, can i use sidepin?
1e9523a8 [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.130 318.5KB 92.32s
1e9523a8 [kimi-k2.6] #You can, but it will not shrink the program the way you might hope.
1e9523a8 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523a9 [kimi-k2.6] #Side-set values are opcode immediates — they are baked into each instruction word at
1e9523a9 [kimi-k2.6] #assembly time, not loaded from a register at run time. Because your selector is dynamic (the 2-bit
1e9523a9 [kimi-k2.6] #value in `X`), you still need the branch tree to pick which instruction runs. Each branch
1e9523a9 [kimi-k2.6] #target can carry its own hard-coded side-set pattern, so yes, the four trigger pins can be driven
1e9523aa [kimi-k2.6] #by side-set rather than by a `set pins` group. The trade-off is that you burn the entire 5-bit
1e9523aa [kimi-k2.6] #delay/side field to do it.
1e9523aa [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523aa [kimi-k2.6] #Here is what the rewrite looks like with `.side_set 4 opt` (four data bits plus one enable bit,
1e9523ab [kimi-k2.6] #leaving zero delay bits):
1e9523ab [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523ab [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523ab [kimi-k2.6] #.program colorpump
1e9523ac [kimi-k2.6] #.side_set 4 opt
1e9523ac [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523ac [kimi-k2.6] #	wait	1 irq 6		side 0b1111
1e9523ac [kimi-k2.6] #	out	pins, 2			side 0b1111	; colour index to OUT pins
1e9523ad [kimi-k2.6] #	out	x, 2			side 0b1111	; selector into X
1e9523ad [kimi-k2.6] #	jmp	x--, t3			side 0b1111
1e9523ad [kimi-k2.6] #	nop					side 0b1110	; trigger SM0 (active low)
1e9523ad [kimi-k2.6] #	jmp	done			side 0b1111
1e9523ae [kimi-k2.6] #t3:	jmp	x--, t2			side 0b1111
1e9523ae [kimi-k2.6] #	nop					side 0b1101	; trigger SM1
1e9523ae [kimi-k2.6] #	jmp	done			side 0b1111
1e9523ae [kimi-k2.6] #t2:	jmp	x--, t1			side 0b1111
1e9523af [kimi-k2.6] #	nop					side 0b1011	; trigger SM2
1e9523af [kimi-k2.6] #	jmp	done			side 0b1111
1e9523af [kimi-k2.6] #t1:	nop					side 0b0111	; trigger SM3
1e9523af [kimi-k2.6] #done:
1e9523b0 [kimi-k2.6] #	nop					side 0b1111	; all triggers high / inactive
1e9523b0 [kimi-k2.6] #.wrap
1e9523b0 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b0 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b1 [kimi-k2.6] #What this costs you
1e9523b1 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b1 [kimi-k2.6] #• No delay cycles. With four side-set data bits plus the optional-enable bit, the entire
1e9523b1 [kimi-k2.6] #5-bit side/delay field is consumed. You cannot write `[3]` or `[1]` on any instruction. If you need
1e9523b2 [kimi-k2.6] #a multi-cycle pulse you must spend extra instruction slots (`nop side 0b1110`, etc.).
1e9523b2 [kimi-k2.6] #• The branch tree is still there. Side-set does not give you a data-dependent output path;
1e9523b2 [kimi-k2.6] #it only gives you a second, parallel output that is fixed per instruction.
1e9523b2 [kimi-k2.6] #• Side-set has its own pin base. You must configure `PINCTRLSIDESETBASE` and
1e9523b3 [kimi-k2.6] #`SIDESET_COUNT` separately in the C init. The four triggers move off the `SET` pin group and onto
1e9523b3 [kimi-k2.6] #the side-set pin group.
1e9523b3 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b3 [kimi-k2.6] #Is it worth it?
1e9523b4 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b4 [kimi-k2.6] #Probably only if you are running out of pin-mapping groups. PIO gives you one `OUT` group,
1e9523b4 [kimi-k2.6] #one `SET` group, one `IN` group and one side-set group. If your `OUT` pins are already used for the
1e9523b4 [kimi-k2.6] #colour index and the `SET` pins are needed for something else (global enables, DAC levels, etc.),
1e9523b5 [kimi-k2.6] #then moving the four FIFO triggers to side-set makes routing sense. Otherwise it just costs you
1e9523b5 [kimi-k2.6] #delay bits for no gain.
1e9523b5 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b5 [kimi-k2.6] #A cleaner alternative
1e9523b6 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b6 [kimi-k2.6] #Your FIFO word already carries the selector in its lower bits. If you format the word so it also
1e9523b6 [kimi-k2.6] #carries a one-hot trigger mask, you can delete the branch tree entirely:
1e9523b6 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b7 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b7 [kimi-k2.6] #.program colorpump
1e9523b7 [kimi-k2.6] #	out	pins, 2			; bits 1:0 → colour index
1e9523b7 [kimi-k2.6] #	out	pins, 4			; bits 5:2 → one-hot trigger mask
1e9523b8 [kimi-k2.6] #.wrap
1e9523b8 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b8 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523b8 [kimi-k2.6] #This is constant-time (2 cycles), has no decode latency, and frees up both `SET` and side-set. The
1e9523b9 [kimi-k2.6] #only requirement is that your DMA buffer packs the mask into the word before the colour index. If
1e9523b9 [kimi-k2.6] #the trigger pins must live on a different GPIO range from the colour index, you can follow the `out
1e9523b9 [kimi-k2.6] #pins, 2` with an `out pindirs, 4` or remap the FIFO word so the mask goes to a second `OUT` group,
1e9523b9 [kimi-k2.6] #but on RP2350 a single `OUT` instruction can only target one contiguous range.
1e9523ba [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523ba [kimi-k2.6] #One other thing to fix
1e9523ba [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9523ba [kimi-k2.6] #Your original `colorpump.pio` has variable latency — the trigger pulse happens 4, 5, 6 or 7
1e9523bb [kimi-k2.6] #cycles after the `out pins, 2`, depending on which state machine is selected. If the `colorfifo`
1e9523bb [kimi-k2.6] #machines are all watching the same `pins[0..1]` bus, that jitter does not matter because the data
1e9523bb [kimi-k2.6] #is stable early. But if you ever use the trigger pulse to gate something that is sensitive to its
1e9523bb [kimi-k2.6] #position in the line, you will want the constant-time version, whether you use side-set or the
1e9523bc [kimi-k2.6] #FIFO-mask approach.
1e9523bc [kimi-k2.6] #
