1e95770b [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.092 313.1KB 50.42s
1e95770b [kimi-k2.6] #This is a substantial embedded graphics project. The standout novel aspects are the aggressive use
1e95770b [kimi-k2.6] #of RP2350 PIO v1 features and the distributed state-machine architecture for analog video
1e95770c [kimi-k2.6] #generation.
1e95770c [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95770c [kimi-k2.6] #• RP2350-specific PIO features*
1e95770d [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95770d [kimi-k2.6] #The most significant difference from a typical RP2040 video project is the reliance on RP2350’s
1e95770d [kimi-k2.6] #indexed RX-FIFO access. In `colorfifo.pio`:
1e95770d [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95770e [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95770e [kimi-k2.6] #.fifo txget
1e95770e [kimi-k2.6] #stall:
1e95770f [kimi-k2.6] #	jmp	pin stall
1e95770f [kimi-k2.6] #	mov	y, pins
1e95770f [kimi-k2.6] #	mov	osr, rxfifo[y]
1e957710 [kimi-k2.6] #	out	pindirs, 3
1e957710 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957710 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957710 [kimi-k2.6] #This uses the new `txget` FIFO join mode and the `mov osr, rxfifo[y]` encoding (Section 11.4.9 in
1e957711 [kimi-k2.6] #the datasheet excerpt you included). On RP2040 this was impossible; the RX FIFO was strictly a
1e957711 [kimi-k2.6] #queue. Here you are treating the four FIFO entries as a per-state-machine lookup table for
1e957711 [kimi-k2.6] #chroma/luma pulse trains. That is a genuinely new way to do palette output on this hardware.
1e957711 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957712 [kimi-k2.6] #`colorpump.pio` exploits the same idea from the other direction: one state machine decodes 4 input
1e957712 [kimi-k2.6] #bits into a color index, then triggers one of four neighbour state machines via side-set pins. The
1e957712 [kimi-k2.6] #triggered machine does the palette lookup via its local `rxfifo`. This turns the four SMs into a
1e957712 [kimi-k2.6] #parallel colour renderer.
1e957713 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957713 [kimi-k2.6] #• Analog output via pin-direction toggling*
1e957713 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957714 [kimi-k2.6] #Rather than driving voltage levels directly, `threepin.pio` and `colorfifo.pio` repeatedly issue
1e957714 [kimi-k2.6] #`out pindirs, 3`. The external resistor networks (100 Ω / 330 Ω / 150 Ω into a 75 Ω load) mean that
1e957714 [kimi-k2.6] #toggling pin direction changes the divider impedance and therefore the output voltage. Using PIO to
1e957714 [kimi-k2.6] #do this at pixel-clock rates (166.5 MHz ÷ 10 ≈ 16.65 MHz pixel cadence, or ~17.73 MHz for chroma)
1e957715 [kimi-k2.6] #is a very tight loop; the `threepin` train is 7 or 10 PIO cycles per pixel, which fits the timing
1e957715 [kimi-k2.6] #budget exactly.
1e957715 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957715 [kimi-k2.6] #• Clocking discipline*
1e957716 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957716 [kimi-k2.6] #The 166.5 MHz system clock is unusual but mathematically precise for PAL:
1e957716 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957716 [kimi-k2.6] #- 166.5 MHz ÷ 9.3885 ≈ 17.734475 MHz = 4 × PAL f_sc (4.43361875 MHz)
1e957717 [kimi-k2.6] #- 166.5 MHz ÷ 10656 = 15.625 kHz line rate
1e957717 [kimi-k2.6] #- 64 µs line period matches PAL spec exactly
1e957717 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957717 [kimi-k2.6] #Most hobby projects approximate this; you have hit the exact ratios.
1e957718 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957718 [kimi-k2.6] #• Interlaced DMA management*
1e957718 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957718 [kimi-k2.6] #`vidbit.cpp` manages even/odd fields separately via `evenFrame[]` and `oddFrame[]` arrays with
1e957719 [kimi-k2.6] #distinct preambles (equalising pulses and broad sync). The DMA channel is re-pointed per-field in
1e957719 [kimi-k2.6] #`vid_fieldi()`, and the C++ renderers (`drawFramei`) know which field they are drawing. This is
1e957719 [kimi-k2.6] #correct 576i, not just progressive scan pretending to be interlaced.
1e957719 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771a [kimi-k2.6] #• Architecture summary*
1e95771a [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771a [kimi-k2.6] #The overall pipeline is:
1e95771b [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771b [kimi-k2.6] #- CPU renders 1-bit glyphs/vectors into field buffers
1e95771b [kimi-k2.6] #- DMA feeds `vidbit.pio` for sync/active video
1e95771b [kimi-k2.6] #- DMA (or direct FIFO writes) feeds `chroma.pio` for the colour subcarrier burst
1e95771c [kimi-k2.6] #- `colorpump.pio` + `colorfifo.pio` (PIO1 SMs) inject colour information during active video via
1e95771c [kimi-k2.6] #the resistor DAC
1e95771c [kimi-k2.6] #- `i2s.pio` handles audio independently on PIO1
1e95771c [kimi-k2.6] #- `ps2.pio` handles keyboard input
1e95771d [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771d [kimi-k2.6] #That is a lot of responsibility placed in PIO; the CPU is essentially just a framebuffer composer.
1e95771d [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771e [kimi-k2.6] #• Notable gaps*
1e95771e [kimi-k2.6] #
1e95771e [kimi-k2.6] #You include references to `colorbit.h` and `colorpumpdmainit()` in `vidbit.cpp`, but the
1e95771e [kimi-k2.6] #corresponding `colorbit.cpp` or `colorpump.cpp` implementation was not in the shared files. The
1e95771f [kimi-k2.6] #`colorpump.md` is also truncated. If you want feedback on the DMA setup or the palette encoding,
1e95771f [kimi-k2.6] #those pieces would be needed.
1e95771f [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957720 [kimi-k2.6] #Likewise, `spdif.pio` is currently a placeholder (`nop [1]`), and `interleave.pio` looks
1e957720 [kimi-k2.6] #experimental.
1e957720 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957720 [kimi-k2.6] #• Bottom line*
1e957721 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e957721 [kimi-k2.6] #The novelty here is not just “video from a Pico,” but specifically a component-capable,
1e957721 [kimi-k2.6] #palette-indexed, interlaced PAL renderer built around RP2350’s indexed-FIFO instructions. That
1e957721 [kimi-k2.6] #is a step beyond the usual bit-banged or resistor-DAC approaches on RP2040.
1e957722 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b0 [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.111 341.3KB 30.20s
1e9610b1 [kimi-k2.6] #The delta from the previous share is focused on two architectural changes:
1e9610b1 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b1 [kimi-k2.6] #• 1. `monobit.h` — `bitsPerPixel` back to 1*
1e9610b1 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b2 [kimi-k2.6] #Was `4`, now `1`. That drops `lineWords` from 108 to 27 and halves the active-video DMA bandwidth.
1e9610b2 [kimi-k2.6] #With the CPU now emitting only a 1-bit mask, color must be coming entirely from the PIO side rather
1e9610b2 [kimi-k2.6] #than a software framebuffer. That aligns the C++ renderer with a hardware-colormap or
1e9610b2 [kimi-k2.6] #attribute-clash style architecture.
1e9610b3 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b3 [kimi-k2.6] #• 2. `vidbit.cpp` — `COLOR` out, `COLORTRAIN` in*
1e9610b3 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b3 [kimi-k2.6] #The active color path is now `COLORTRAIN` via `colortraininit(pio1, ColorTrainStateMachine)`,
1e9610b4 [kimi-k2.6] #while the previous `colorpumpinit` / `colorpumpdmainit` block is still present but
1e9610b4 [kimi-k2.6] #guarded by the now-undefined `COLOR` macro. A few side effects:
1e9610b4 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b4 [kimi-k2.6] #- The field-swap routines (`vidfieldi`, `vidfield`) still contain dead `#ifdef COLOR`
1e9610b5 [kimi-k2.6] #references to `colorpumpdmachan` and `colorTestAddress()`. If you plan to keep both paths
1e9610b5 [kimi-k2.6] #for testing, that is fine; if `COLORTRAIN` is the permanent replacement, those orphaned blocks
1e9610b5 [kimi-k2.6] #could be removed to avoid confusion.
1e9610b5 [kimi-k2.6] #- The `color_trains[]` array (16 entries, 39-bit patterns) remains in memory but is no longer
1e9610b6 [kimi-k2.6] #referenced by the active code path. If `colortrain.pio` uses it, the linkage is not visible in the
1e9610b6 [kimi-k2.6] #current share.
1e9610b6 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b6 [kimi-k2.6] #• Consistency note*
1e9610b7 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b7 [kimi-k2.6] #`vidbit.pio` still asserts `irq next clear 6` at the end of active video, and `colorpump.pio` still
1e9610b7 [kimi-k2.6] #waits on `irq 6`. If `COLORTRAIN` uses a different sync mechanism (or a different PIO program
1e9610b7 [kimi-k2.6] #entirely), that handshake may now be unused on the PIO1 side.
1e9610b8 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e9610b8 [kimi-k2.6] #If you have `colortrain.pio` / `colortrain.cpp` to share, the full data flow (how the 1-bit pixel
1e9610b8 [kimi-k2.6] #mask gets mapped to the 16-entry pulse train table) would be clearer.
1e9610b8 [kimi-k2.6] #
