1e961b1e [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.135 343.3KB 76.04s
1e961b1e [kimi-k2.6] #That three-instruction sequence is a conditional cross-PIO trigger based on a control field
1e961b1e [kimi-k2.6] #in the DMA bitstream.
1e961b1e [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #╭────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #│  Instruction       │  PIO encoding                              │  What it does                                                                                                                                                                                    │
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #├────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #│  `out y, 2`        │  `OUT` dest=Y, count=2                     │  Shifts 2 bits from the **OSR** (Output Shift Register) into scratch register **Y**. If autopull is enabled and the shift threshold is reached, the OSR automatically refills from the TX FIFO.  │
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #│  `jmp !y, noirq`   │  `JMP` condition=!Y                        │  Tests whether **Y == 0**. If true (the 2 bits were `00`), the program counter jumps to `noirq:`, **skipping** the IRQ. If false, execution falls through.                                       │
1e961b1f [kimi-k2.6] #│  `irq next set 6`  │  `IRQ` clear=0, wait=0, idx=NEXT, index=6  │  Asserts **IRQ flag 6** in the **next higher-numbered PIO block** (e.g. from PIO0 to PIO1). It does **not** wait for the flag to be cleared; it fires and immediately continues.                 │
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #╰────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #• Composite effect*
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #It reads a 2-bit token from the video DMA stream. If that token is non-zero, it pings the
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #neighbouring PIO (where your chroma/colour state machines live) by setting flag 6. A state machine
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #in the other block can be waiting with:
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b20 [kimi-k2.6] #wait 1 irq 6
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #…to synchronize the start of its line processing with the main video timing.
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #• In your `vidbit.pio` context*
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #Your frame buffer is a packed FIFO stream: vsync preamble → line counter → pixel counter → bitmap.
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #That `out y, 2` (or `out y, 1` in the actual file) is plucking a flag from the first word(s) of
1e961b21 [kimi-k2.6] #each line’s data to tell PIO1 whether this scanline carries active colour/pump data or should be
1e961b22 [kimi-k2.6] #skipped (blanking lines). The `next` modifier is what lets the sync generator on PIO0 wake
1e961b22 [kimi-k2.6] #the colour hardware on PIO1 with cycle-accurate timing.
1e961b22 [kimi-k2.6] #
