1e963726 [kimi-k2.6] #`colortrain.pio` is new, and it significantly simplifies the colour path compared with the earlier
1e963727 [kimi-k2.6] #`colorpump`+`colorfifo` pair.
1e963727 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e963727 [kimi-k2.6] #• What it does*
1e963727 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e963728 [kimi-k2.6] #╭────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1e963728 [kimi-k2.6] #│  Feature               │  PIO mechanism                 │  Purpose                                                                                                        │
1e963728 [kimi-k2.6] #├────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1e963728 [kimi-k2.6] #│  `.fifo txget`         │  `FJOIN_RX_GET`                │  Turns the RX FIFO into a 4-entry random-access lookup table readable by the state machine.                     │
1e963728 [kimi-k2.6] #│  `mov osr, rxfifo[y]`  │  Indexed GET (RP2350 v1 only)  │  Fetches one of four pre-loaded pulse trains in a single cycle.                                                 │
1e963729 [kimi-k2.6] #│  `wait 1 irq 6`        │  Cross-PIO flag                │  Line-start synchronisation with `vidbit.pio` (which fires `irq next set 6` at the beginning of active video).  │
1e963729 [kimi-k2.6] #│  `out pindirs, 3` × 6  │  3-pin tristate DAC            │  Outputs six phases of chroma/luma waveform per pixel, exactly like the older `colorfifo.pio`.                  │
1e963729 [kimi-k2.6] #╰────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1e963729 [kimi-k2.6] #
1e96372a [kimi-k2.6] #In short, this replaces the previous five-state-machine colour subsystem (one `colorpump` selector
1e96372a [kimi-k2.6] #+ four `colorfifo` renderers) with one state machine that does its own palette lookup.
1e96372a [kimi-k2.6] #
1e96372a [kimi-k2.6] #• Cycle matching*
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #The inner loop (`mov y, pins` → `mov osr, rxfifo[y]` → six `out pindirs, 3`) is 8 instructions plus
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #the wrap, which appears intended to lock to vidbit’s active-video cadence. Both machines run from
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #the same 166.5 MHz clock, so if they start together they stay phase-locked for the entire line.
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #
1e96372b [kimi-k2.6] #• Two things to watch*
1e96372c [kimi-k2.6] #
1e96372c [kimi-k2.6] #1. Missing `.wrap_target`
