1eab57db [gemini-3.1-lite] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  gemini-3.1-lite 🌟 🪠 0.7° $0.000 488B 3.76s
1eab57dc [gemini-3.1-lite] #In the context of the Raspberry Pi RP2040’s PIO (Programmable I/O) peripheral, DREQ
1eab57dc [gemini-3.1-lite] #stands for Data Request.
1eab57dc [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57dc [gemini-3.1-lite] #What is it?
1eab57dd [gemini-3.1-lite] #DREQ is a hardware signaling mechanism used to coordinate data transfers between the PIO state
1eab57dd [gemini-3.1-lite] #machines and the RP2040’s DMA (Direct Memory Access) controller.
1eab57dd [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57dd [gemini-3.1-lite] #Because PIO state machines operate independently of the CPU, they often need to move large amounts
1eab57de [gemini-3.1-lite] #of data (e.g., sending a frame buffer to an LCD or reading samples from an ADC) without CPU
1eab57de [gemini-3.1-lite] #intervention. DREQ signals tell the DMA controller that the PIO peripheral is ready to perform a
1eab57de [gemini-3.1-lite] #transfer.
1eab57de [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57df [gemini-3.1-lite] #How it works
1eab57df [gemini-3.1-lite] #Each PIO state machine has two FIFO (First-In, First-Out) buffers:
1eab57df [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  TX FIFO: Holds data waiting to be sent out by the state machine.
1eab57df [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  RX FIFO: Holds data received by the state machine waiting to be read.
1eab57e0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The DREQ signal acts as a "handshake" based on the status of these FIFOs:
1eab57e0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• For TX (Outbound): The PIO state machine asserts a DREQ when its TX FIFO is not full
1eab57e1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #(i.e., it has space to accept more data). This signals the DMA controller: "I have room, please
1eab57e1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #send me more data."
1eab57e1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• For RX (Inbound): The PIO state machine asserts a DREQ when its RX FIFO is not empty
1eab57e1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #(i.e., it has data waiting to be read). This signals the DMA controller: "I have data ready,
1eab57e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #please come and collect it."
1eab57e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Why is it important?
1eab57e2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Without DREQ, the DMA controller would have to "guess" when to transfer data, which would likely
1eab57e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #result in buffer overflows or underflows, leading to corrupted data or missed samples. By using
1eab57e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #DREQ, the transfer is hardware-flow-controlled. The DMA controller remains idle until the
1eab57e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #PIO peripheral explicitly signals that it is ready, ensuring perfectly synchronized data movement.
1eab57e3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Mapping DREQ
1eab57e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The RP2040 has a specific DREQ mapping table. Each state machine’s TX and RX FIFOs are mapped to
1eab57e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #specific DREQ signals (labeled `DREQPIOxTXy` or `DREQPIOxRXy`). When configuring a
1eab57e4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #DMA channel, you set the `dreq` parameter to the specific signal corresponding to the state machine
1eab57e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and FIFO you are targeting.
1eab57e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e5 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Example (C/Pico SDK):*
1eab57e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #// Configure DMA to transfer data to PIO TX FIFO
1eab57e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #dma_channel_config c = dma_channel_get_default_config(dma_chan);
1eab57e6 [gemini-3.1-lite] #channel_config_set_dreq(&c, pio_get_dreq(pio, sm, true)); // 'true' for TX
1eab57e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab57e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #In summary, DREQ is the essential bridge that allows the DMA controller to feed data to (or drain
1eab57e7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #data from) the PIO state machines efficiently and automatically.
1eab57e8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
