1eab5f42 [gemini-3.1-lite] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  gemini-3.1-lite 🌟 🪠 0.7° $0.000 3.230KB 4.53s
1eab5f42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #To set JMP pins in PIO using C++, you must configure the `jmp_pin` field within the state
1eab5f42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #machine configuration. The JMP pin determines which physical GPIO pin the `jmp pin, ...`
1eab5f42 [gemini-3.1-lite] #instruction checks to decide whether to branch.
1eab5f43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Here is the standard way to configure this using the Pico SDK in C++.
1eab5f43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f43 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The Configuration Process
1eab5f44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #You should use the `piosmconfig` structure and the `smconfigsetjmppin`
1eab5f44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #function.
1eab5f44 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f45 [gemini-3.1-lite] ##include "hardware/pio.h"
1eab5f45 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #void configure_pio_jmp_pin(PIO pio, uint sm, uint pin_number) {
1eab5f46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// 1. Get the default configuration for the state machine
1eab5f46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	pio_sm_config c = pio_get_default_sm_config();
1eab5f46 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// 2. Set the JMP pin
1eab5f47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// This tells the state machine which physical pin to check
1eab5f47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// when executing the "jmp pin" instruction.
1eab5f47 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	sm_config_set_jmp_pin(&c, pin_number);
1eab5f48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// 3. Initialize the state machine with this configuration
1eab5f48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	// (Assuming you have a loaded program offset)
1eab5f48 [gemini-3.1-lite] #	pio_sm_init(pio, sm, offset, &c);
1eab5f49 [gemini-3.1-lite] #}
1eab5f49 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f49 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f49 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Important Considerations
1eab5f4a [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f4a [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Pin Mapping: The `pinnumber` passed to `smconfigsetjmp_pin` is the GPIO
1eab5f4a [gemini-3.1-lite] #pin number relative to the chip (e.g., GPIO 0, GPIO 1, etc.).
1eab5f4a [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Pin Direction: Even though the JMP instruction is reading the state of a pin, you must
1eab5f4b [gemini-3.1-lite] #ensure that the pin is configured correctly in your PIO program's `side-set` or `out` settings if
1eab5f4b [gemini-3.1-lite] #necessary, though for a pure input JMP, you simply need to ensure the pin is assigned to the PIO
1eab5f4b [gemini-3.1-lite] #peripheral.
1eab5f4b [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  Instruction Behavior: When your PIO assembly code executes `jmp pin, label`, the state
1eab5f4c [gemini-3.1-lite] #machine checks the logic level of the pin you configured. If the pin is high, the jump is
1eab5f4c [gemini-3.1-lite] #taken; if low, the program continues to the next instruction.
1eab5f4c [gemini-3.1-lite] #4.  Multiple State Machines: Each state machine has its own `jmp_pin` setting. Configuring
1eab5f4c [gemini-3.1-lite] #it for one state machine does not affect others.
1eab5f4d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f4d [gemini-3.1-lite] #Example PIO Assembly Context
1eab5f4d [gemini-3.1-lite] #For the C++ code above to be useful, your `.pio` file would contain an instruction that utilizes
1eab5f4d [gemini-3.1-lite] #that pin:
1eab5f4e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f4e [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f4e [gemini-3.1-lite] #.program my_program
1eab5f4e [gemini-3.1-lite] #    ; This will jump to 'target' if the configured JMP pin is HIGH
1eab5f4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #    jmp pin, target
1eab5f4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #    ; Otherwise, do something else
1eab5f4f [gemini-3.1-lite] #    set pins, 0
1eab5f50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    jmp start
1eab5f50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #target:
1eab5f50 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    set pins, 1
1eab5f51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #    jmp start
1eab5f51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f51 [gemini-3.1-lite] #When to use `smconfigsetjmppin`
1eab5f52 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Dynamic Conditionals: If you are building a protocol where you need to poll an external
1eab5f52 [gemini-3.1-lite] #signal (like a clock or a data-ready line) without involving the CPU.
1eab5f52 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Mode Selection: If you have a physical switch connected to a GPIO, you can use `jmp pin`
1eab5f52 [gemini-3.1-lite] #to have the PIO state machine change its behavior based on the hardware state.
1eab5f53 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1eab5f53 [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you are using the `pioaddprogram` helper functions generated by `pioasm`, remember that
1eab5f53 [gemini-3.1-lite] #the `smconfig` is usually applied during the initialization phase before
1eab5f53 [gemini-3.1-lite] #`piosmsetenabled(pio, sm, true)` is called.
1eab5f54 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
