1ed1cf25 [gemini-3.1-lite] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  gemini-3.1-lite 🌟 🪠 0.7° $0.000 1.704KB 3.79s
1ed1cf25 [gemini-3.1-lite] #An S/PDIF (Sony/Philips Digital Interface) receiver operates by converting a serial stream of
1ed1cf25 [gemini-3.1-lite] #electrical or optical pulses back into parallel digital data (usually I2S or PCM) that a processor
1ed1cf25 [gemini-3.1-lite] #or DAC can understand.
1ed1cf25 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf26 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Because S/PDIF is a "self-clocking" protocol, the receiver must perform several distinct logical
1ed1cf26 [gemini-3.1-lite] #steps to extract the data correctly.
1ed1cf26 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf26 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. Signal Conditioning and Threshold Detection
1ed1cf27 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The incoming signal (often a Biphase Mark Code) is an analog signal that must first be converted
1ed1cf27 [gemini-3.1-lite] #into a clean digital square wave. The receiver uses a comparator to determine if the voltage is
1ed1cf27 [gemini-3.1-lite] #above or below a specific threshold. This converts the physical pulses into a logical stream of 1s
1ed1cf27 [gemini-3.1-lite] #and 0s.
1ed1cf28 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf28 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. Clock Recovery (The Phase-Locked Loop)
1ed1cf28 [gemini-3.1-lite] #S/PDIF does not send a separate clock signal. Instead, the clock information is embedded within the
1ed1cf28 [gemini-3.1-lite] #transitions of the data itself. The receiver uses a Phase-Locked Loop (PLL) to track these
1ed1cf29 [gemini-3.1-lite] #transitions. The PLL "locks" onto the frequency of the incoming transitions, allowing the receiver
1ed1cf29 [gemini-3.1-lite] #to generate a local clock that is perfectly synchronized with the sender. This is critical for
1ed1cf29 [gemini-3.1-lite] #preventing jitter.
1ed1cf29 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf2a [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. Decoding Biphase Mark Code (BMC)
1ed1cf2a [gemini-3.1-lite] #S/PDIF uses BMC, where a transition always occurs at the start of every bit period, and an
1ed1cf2a [gemini-3.1-lite] #additional transition occurs in the middle of the bit period only if the data bit is a `1`.
1ed1cf2a [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Logic: The receiver looks at the timing between transitions. If a transition occurs
1ed1cf2b [gemini-3.1-lite] #exactly at the bit boundary, it identifies the start of a new bit. If a transition occurs in the
1ed1cf2b [gemini-3.1-lite] #middle, it registers a logical `1`; if no transition occurs in the middle, it registers a logical
1ed1cf2b [gemini-3.1-lite] #`0`.
1ed1cf2b [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf2c [gemini-3.1-lite] #4. Preamble Detection (Frame Synchronization)
1ed1cf2c [gemini-3.1-lite] #The data stream is organized into "frames." To know where one frame ends and the next begins, the
1ed1cf2c [gemini-3.1-lite] #receiver looks for specific "preambles." These are special patterns that violate the standard
1ed1cf2c [gemini-3.1-lite] #Biphase Mark rules (they contain transitions that occur too close together). By detecting these
1ed1cf2d [gemini-3.1-lite] #unique patterns (labeled B, M, and W), the receiver identifies the start of a new frame and the
1ed1cf2d [gemini-3.1-lite] #start of a new sub-frame.
1ed1cf2d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf2d [gemini-3.1-lite] #5. Sub-frame and Block Extraction
1ed1cf2e [gemini-3.1-lite] #Once the receiver is synchronized to the frames, it parses the bits into the standard S/PDIF
1ed1cf2e [gemini-3.1-lite] #structure:
1ed1cf2e [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Audio Data: Extracts the actual PCM audio samples (usually 16 to 24 bits).
1ed1cf2e [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Validity Bit: Checks if the audio data is suitable for conversion.
1ed1cf2f [gemini-3.1-lite] #• User Data & Channel Status: Extracts metadata (such as sample rate, copyright
1ed1cf2f [gemini-3.1-lite] #information, or category codes).
1ed1cf2f [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Parity Bit: Performs a parity check to ensure the data was not corrupted during
1ed1cf2f [gemini-3.1-lite] #transmission.
1ed1cf30 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf30 [gemini-3.1-lite] #6. Data Formatting (The Output Stage)
1ed1cf30 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Finally, the receiver buffers the extracted audio data and reformats it into a standard digital
1ed1cf30 [gemini-3.1-lite] #audio interface format, such as I2S (Inter-IC Sound). This output is then sent to a
1ed1cf31 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Digital-to-Analog Converter (DAC) or a Digital Signal Processor (DSP) for final processing.
1ed1cf31 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1cf31 [gemini-3.1-lite] #In summary, the logic moves from raw electrical pulses → clock extraction →
1ed1cf31 [gemini-3.1-lite] #pattern-based decoding → frame synchronization → error checking →
1ed1cf32 [gemini-3.1-lite] #parallel data output.
1ed1cf32 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d28c [nitro@ryzen5] is there a simple middle man prootocol that rp2350 pio could use to send audio received
1ed1d2c7 [gemini-3.1-lite] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.6 ⛲  gemini-3.1-lite 🌟 🪠 0.7° $0.000 5.203KB 3.02s
1ed1d2c7 [gemini-3.1-lite] #For the RP2350, the PIO (Programmable I/O) is exceptionally well-suited for acting as a "bridge"
1ed1d2c8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #between an S/PDIF receiver and the rest of the system.
1ed1d2c8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2c8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #To act as a "middle man" protocol, you need something that is hardware-friendly, low-overhead, and
1ed1d2c8 [gemini-3.1-lite] #supported by most audio DACs and DSPs. The standard choice for this is I2S (Inter-IC
1ed1d2c9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Sound).
1ed1d2c9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2c9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Why I2S is the ideal "Middle Man"
1ed1d2c9 [gemini-3.1-lite] #I2S is the industry-standard interface for moving digital audio between chips. It is simple enough
1ed1d2ca [gemini-3.1-lite] #that the RP2350 PIO can generate it with very little logic.
1ed1d2ca [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2ca [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Synchronous: It uses a Clock (BCLK), a Word Select (WS/LRCK), and Data (SDATA).
1ed1d2ca [gemini-3.1-lite] #• PIO-Friendly: The PIO can easily toggle these three pins in a loop.
1ed1d2cb [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Hardware Compatibility: Almost every external DAC or codec chip on the market accepts
1ed1d2cb [gemini-3.1-lite] #I2S.
1ed1d2cb [gemini-3.1-lite] #• DMA Integration: The RP2350 can use its DMA (Direct Memory Access) controller to push
1ed1d2cb [gemini-3.1-lite] #audio samples from the S/PDIF receiver's buffer into the PIO's FIFO, meaning the CPU doesn't have
1ed1d2cc [gemini-3.1-lite] #to touch the audio data at all.
1ed1d2cc [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2cc [gemini-3.1-lite] #How the PIO Logic would work
1ed1d2cc [gemini-3.1-lite] #If you are receiving S/PDIF and want to output it as I2S, your PIO state machine would perform
1ed1d2cd [gemini-3.1-lite] #these logical steps:
1ed1d2cd [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2cd [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Wait for FIFO: The PIO waits for a 32-bit audio sample to be pushed into its TX FIFO by
1ed1d2cd [gemini-3.1-lite] #the DMA or the CPU.
1ed1d2ce [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Word Select (WS) Toggle: The PIO toggles the WS pin to indicate whether the current
1ed1d2ce [gemini-3.1-lite] #data is for the Left or Right channel.
1ed1d2ce [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  Bit-Banging Data: The PIO shifts the 32-bit word out of the FIFO one bit at a time,
1ed1d2ce [gemini-3.1-lite] #synchronized with the Bit Clock (BCLK).
1ed1d2cf [gemini-3.1-lite] #4.  Looping: The state machine repeats this process indefinitely.
1ed1d2cf [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2cf [gemini-3.1-lite] #An Alternative: TDM (Time Division Multiplexing)
1ed1d2cf [gemini-3.1-lite] #If your application requires more than two channels (e.g., 4, 8, or 16 channels), you would use
1ed1d2d0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #TDM.
1ed1d2d0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2d0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #TDM is essentially an extension of I2S. Instead of having just one Left and one Right slot per
1ed1d2d0 [gemini-3.1-lite] #frame, the frame is extended to contain multiple slots. The PIO logic remains very similar to I2S,
1ed1d2d1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #but the "Word Select" signal becomes a narrow pulse that marks the start of a much longer frame of
1ed1d2d1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #multiple audio channels.
1ed1d2d1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2d1 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Recommendation for RP2350
1ed1d2d2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #1.  Use I2S for simplicity: If you are just moving stereo audio, implement I2S. It
1ed1d2d2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #is the most robust "middle man" protocol.
1ed1d2d2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2.  Use PIO for the "Glue": Let the PIO handle the timing-critical task of shifting bits
1ed1d2d2 [gemini-3.1-lite] #out to the DAC.
1ed1d2d3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3.  Use DMA for the "Transport": Configure the DMA to move data from your S/PDIF processing
1ed1d2d3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #buffer (where you parsed the S/PDIF stream) directly into the PIO TX FIFO.
1ed1d2d3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed1d2d3 [gemini-3.1-lite] #By using I2S as your middle-man protocol, you decouple the complex S/PDIF decoding logic from the
1ed1d2d4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #physical audio output, making your system much easier to debug and more modular.
1ed1d2d4 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
