1ed2724c [gemini-3.1-lite] #To configure the DMA as a reader (pulling data from the PIO state machine into memory), the
1ed2724c [gemini-3.1-lite] #direction of the data transfer must be reversed compared to your current snippet.
1ed2724c [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed2724c [gemini-3.1-lite] #In the RP2040 DMA architecture, "reading" from the perspective of the CPU/memory means the DMA
1ed2724d [gemini-3.1-lite] #controller is acting as the bus master to move data out of the PIO's RX FIFO and into your system
1ed2724d [gemini-3.1-lite] #RAM. Here are the specific areas that require your attention:
1ed2724d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed2724e [gemini-3.1-lite] #1. FIFO Selection (Source vs. Destination)
1ed2724e [gemini-3.1-lite] #Your current code points the DMA to `&pio0->txf[sm]`. The `txf` (Transmit FIFO) is used to send
1ed2724e [gemini-3.1-lite] #data from the CPU/DMA to the PIO. To read data from the PIO, you must point the DMA
1ed2724e [gemini-3.1-lite] #source address to the `rxf` (Receive FIFO) register: `&pio->rxf[sm]`.
1ed2724f [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed2724f [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. Increment Logic
1ed2724f [gemini-3.1-lite] #The DMA controller needs to know which side of the transfer is a static register (the PIO FIFO) and
1ed2724f [gemini-3.1-lite] #which side is a memory buffer.
1ed27250 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Source (`read_increment`): Set this to `false`. You are reading from a single, fixed
1ed27250 [gemini-3.1-lite] #memory-mapped register (the FIFO).
1ed27250 [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Destination (`write_increment`): Set this to `true`. You are writing to an array or
1ed27250 [gemini-3.1-lite] #buffer in RAM, so the address must increment after every 32-bit transfer.
1ed27251 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed27251 [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. DREQ (Data Request)
1ed27251 [gemini-3.1-lite] #The DREQ signal acts as the hardware flow control. When reading from the PIO, you must use the RX
1ed27251 [gemini-3.1-lite] #DREQ. If you use the TX DREQ while trying to read, the DMA will wait for the PIO's TX FIFO to be
1ed27252 [gemini-3.1-lite] #empty (which it likely won't be, if you are only reading), causing the transfer to hang. You should
1ed27252 [gemini-3.1-lite] #use `piogetdreq(pio, sm, false)` for RX operations.
1ed27252 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed27252 [gemini-3.1-lite] #4. Memory Buffering
1ed27253 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Because you are reading into memory, ensure your target buffer is correctly aligned for the DMA.
1ed27253 [gemini-3.1-lite] #While the RP2040 DMA is quite flexible, it is best practice to ensure your buffer is word-aligned
1ed27253 [gemini-3.1-lite] #(32-bit) in memory. Additionally, if you intend to process this data while the DMA is still
1ed27253 [gemini-3.1-lite] #running, you may want to consider using a ping-pong buffer strategy or a DMA chain to prevent the
1ed27254 [gemini-3.1-lite] #CPU from accessing the same memory index that the DMA is currently writing to.
1ed27254 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed27254 [gemini-3.1-lite] #By swapping the FIFO target to `rxf`, setting the `read_increment` to `false`, and updating the
1ed27254 [gemini-3.1-lite] #`dreq` to the RX variant, the DMA will correctly pull the data captured by your PIO state machine
1ed27255 [gemini-3.1-lite] #into your designated memory buffer.
1ed27255 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
