1ed28318 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed28318 [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed28319 [gemini-3.1-lite] #2. Handling Buffer Completion
1ed28319 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Since you are using a static buffer size (`audioWordCount`), the DMA will stop once it has filled
1ed28319 [gemini-3.1-lite] #the buffer. If you want continuous audio streaming, you should consider using DMA
1ed28319 [gemini-3.1-lite] #Interrupts.
1ed2831a [gemini-3.1-lite] #• You can set up an interrupt handler using
1ed2831a [gemini-3.1-lite] #`dmachannelsetirq0enabled(spdifdmachan, true)`.
1ed2831a [gemini-3.1-lite] #• Inside the handler, you would clear the interrupt flag and re-trigger the DMA to point back to
1ed2831a [gemini-3.1-lite] #the start of your buffer (or a secondary buffer if you are implementing a
1ed2831b [gemini-3.1-lite] #ping-pong/double-buffering scheme).
1ed2831b [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed2831b [gemini-3.1-lite] #3. PIO FIFO Stalls
1ed2831b [gemini-3.1-lite] #If the PIO state machine generates data faster than the DMA can move it (or if the DMA is paused),
1ed2831c [gemini-3.1-lite] #the PIO RX FIFO will overflow. The `hilo32` program should be configured to stall the state machine
1ed2831c [gemini-3.1-lite] #when the FIFO is full. Ensure your PIO assembly includes an `in` instruction that pushes to the
1ed2831c [gemini-3.1-lite] #FIFO; the standard `piosmconfig` defaults will handle this stall behavior automatically,
1ed2831c [gemini-3.1-lite] #protecting your data integrity.
1ed2831d [gemini-3.1-lite] #
1ed2831d [gemini-3.1-lite] #Summary Checklist
