1ed2d07e [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.7 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.007 588B 40.28s
1ed2d07f [kimi-k2.6] #Deno does not currently implement the Web Serial API or provide any other built-in API for
1ed2d07f [kimi-k2.6] #accessing serial ports. You cannot use `navigator.serial` or a Deno-native equivalent out of the
1ed2d07f [kimi-k2.6] #box.
1ed2d07f [kimi-k2.6] #
1ed2d080 [kimi-k2.6] #If you need to communicate with serial devices, there are three main approaches:
1ed2d080 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ed2d080 [kimi-k2.6] #1. npm compatibility
1ed2d080 [kimi-k2.6] #   You can attempt to import the Node.js [`serialport`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/serialport)
1ed2d081 [kimi-k2.6] #package via Deno’s Node.js/npm compatibility layer. Modern versions of `serialport` use N-API for
1ed2d081 [kimi-k2.6] #their native bindings, and Deno has been expanding its N-API support, but success depends on your
1ed2d081 [kimi-k2.6] #platform and Deno version. It is not guaranteed to work without issues.
1ed2d081 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ed2d082 [kimi-k2.6] #2. FFI (Foreign Function Interface)
1ed2d082 [kimi-k2.6] #   The most robust path is to use Deno’s FFI to call the OS serial APIs directly—for example,
1ed2d082 [kimi-k2.6] #`termios` on Linux and macOS, or the Windows COM APIs. This bypasses Node native-addon
1ed2d082 [kimi-k2.6] #compatibility entirely, though it requires writing low-level bindings.
1ed2d083 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ed2d083 [kimi-k2.6] #3. Third-party modules
1ed2d083 [kimi-k2.6] #   Community modules on `deno.land/x` or JSR may wrap FFI calls into a more convenient interface,
1ed2d084 [kimi-k2.6] #but this part of the ecosystem is less mature than Node’s.
1ed2d084 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ed2d084 [kimi-k2.6] #In short, serial port access is not a first-class feature in Deno, but it is achievable through
1ed2d084 [kimi-k2.6] #interoperability or direct system calls.
1ed2d085 [kimi-k2.6] #
