1ee95a0e [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.7 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.089 298.5KB 97.62s
1ee95a0e [kimi-k2.6] #A few things stand out as genuinely novel, and a handful look like works-in-progress. Treating this
1ee95a0e [kimi-k2.6] #as an RP2350-native project (not a port from RP2040) makes sense — you are using PIO version 1
1ee95a0e [kimi-k2.6] #features that simply do not exist on the earlier silicon.
1ee95a0f [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a0f [kimi-k2.6] #• What is new or different compared to typical RP2040 PIO usage*
1ee95a0f [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a0f [kimi-k2.6] #• Indexed RX FIFO lookups (`txget` / `putget` modes).
1ee95a10 [kimi-k2.6] #    `chroma.pio`, `greyline.pio` and `colortrain.pio` all declare `.fifo txget` and use `mov osr,
1ee95a10 [kimi-k2.6] #rxfifo[y]`. On RP2350 this repurposes the RX FIFO storage as a random-read lookup table for the
1ee95a10 [kimi-k2.6] #state machine while leaving the TX path intact. That is a very different pattern from the old
1ee95a10 [kimi-k2.6] #RP2040 approach of streaming everything through the FIFOs in strict order. It is a good fit for
1ee95a11 [kimi-k2.6] #colour-burst or per-line palette tables that the CPU loads once and the SM indexes on every line.
1ee95a11 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a11 [kimi-k2.6] #• Cross-PIO IRQ synchronisation.
1ee95a11 [kimi-k2.6] #    `vidbit.pio` fires `irq next set 6 / clear 6` and `chroma.pio` waits on `irq 6`. Because RP2350
1ee95a12 [kimi-k2.6] #IRQs propagate across PIO blocks with no cycle penalty, you can lock the chroma generator to the
1ee95a12 [kimi-k2.6] #luma/sync generator even when they are on different PIO instances. Doing this cycle-accurately on
1ee95a12 [kimi-k2.6] #RP2040 was either impossible or required burning a GPIO as a sync wire.
1ee95a12 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a13 [kimi-k2.6] #• Pre-baked vertical sync in the FIFO.
1ee95a13 [kimi-k2.6] #    The `vidbit.pio` preamble is elegant: the C++ side queues the vsync pulse train as raw FIFO
1ee95a13 [kimi-k2.6] #words (`E0,E1`, `B0,B1`, etc.) followed by the line count and active width. The SM consumes it as a
1ee95a13 [kimi-k2.6] #pure dataflow program. This is a clean way to handle the equalising/broad-sync preamble without
1ee95a14 [kimi-k2.6] #consuming instruction memory on branches.
1ee95a14 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a14 [kimi-k2.6] #• Architecture observations*
1ee95a14 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a15 [kimi-k2.6] #The `pixelpump → onebit → threepin` pipeline is a nice separation of concerns:
1ee95a15 [kimi-k2.6] #• pixelpump acts as a scanline double-buffer scheduler (IRQ wait + 27 FIFO swaps).
1ee95a15 [kimi-k2.6] #• onebit resolves a single serial pixel bit into one of two 32-bit “wave trains”.
1ee95a15 [kimi-k2.6] #• threepin expands that train into actual pin-direction changes for a resistor DAC.
1ee95a16 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a16 [kimi-k2.6] #That lets you keep the CPU-side framebuffer as 1-bit or 2-bit packed data while the PIOs do the
1ee95a16 [kimi-k2.6] #cycle-exact pin wiggling.
1ee95a16 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a17 [kimi-k2.6] #• Items that look unfinished or worth a second look*
1ee95a17 [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a17 [kimi-k2.6] #• `interleave.pio` does not seem coherent yet — `c0` and `c1` are defined but never branched to,
1ee95a17 [kimi-k2.6] #`y` is consumed by `mov x, x|y` before it is initialised, and there is no `.wrap`. It reads like a
1ee95a18 [kimi-k2.6] #draft.
1ee95a18 [kimi-k2.6] #• `spdif.pio` is understandably a stub (just `nop [1]`), but the comment claims 48.4 cycles/bit @
1ee95a18 [kimi-k2.6] #48 kHz which would need a real BMC decoder. The `rc5.pio` pulse counter is more complete.
1ee95a18 [kimi-k2.6] #• `json.h` pulls in `<codecvt>` and `std::wstring_convert`. Those were deprecated in C++17 and are
1ee95a19 [kimi-k2.6] #removed in C++20. If you move to a newer toolchain it will break. The parser also leaks in
1ee95a19 [kimi-k2.6] #`parseRHS` (allocates a `JSValue` into the local `result` but never hands ownership back to the
1ee95a19 [kimi-k2.6] #caller).
1ee95a1a [kimi-k2.6] #• `threepin.pio` comment says “10 cycles per count” but the instruction path is 9 cycles (seven
1ee95a1a [kimi-k2.6] #`out pindirs, 3`, one `set pindirs, 0`, one `out null, 11`). You may already know and have
1ee95a1a [kimi-k2.6] #accounted for it elsewhere, but the mismatch jumped out.
1ee95a1a [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a1b [kimi-k2.6] #• Overall impression*
1ee95a1b [kimi-k2.6] #
1ee95a1b [kimi-k2.6] #This is one of the more aggressive uses of RP2350-specific PIO features I have seen in the wild —
1ee95a1b [kimi-k2.6] #particularly the `rxfifo[y]` lookups and cross-PIO IRQs. The video side is far enough along that
1ee95a1c [kimi-k2.6] #the pipeline is generating real timing, while the audio (`i2s.pio`) and serial (`ps2.pio`,
1ee95a1c [kimi-k2.6] #`rc5.pio`) modules look like they are being brought up alongside it. If you want another pair of
1ee95a1c [kimi-k2.6] #eyes on the cycle budget for the active region (the `out pindirs, 2 [8]` loop in `vidbit.pio`
1ee95a1c [kimi-k2.6] #versus the `threepin` train length), that would be an easy place to dig in.
1ee95a1d [kimi-k2.6] #
