1f2874c1 [kimi-k2.6] #Here is a practical, robust interface circuit. It handles the three main problems:
1f2874c1 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f2874c1 [kimi-k2.6] #• AC coupling & bias – a guitar signal swings positive and negative, but the RP2040 ADC
1f2874c1 [kimi-k2.6] #only accepts 0 V to 3.3 V.
1f2874c2 [kimi-k2.6] #• Over-voltage protection – plugging in, switching pedals, or hot pickups can create spikes
1f2874c2 [kimi-k2.6] #well outside the safe range.
1f2874c2 [kimi-k2.6] #• Impedance matching – guitar pickups like to see a high impedance, while the ADC samples
1f2874c2 [kimi-k2.6] #best from a low-impedance source.
1f2874c3 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f2874c3 [kimi-k2.6] #Two options are shown: an active buffered circuit (recommended, best performance) and a
1f2874c3 [kimi-k2.6] #passive circuit (fewer parts, acceptable for simple projects).
1f2874c3 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #Recommended: Single-Supply Op-Amp Buffer/Attenuator
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #An inverting stage gives a predictable gain below unity, a very low output impedance for the ADC,
1f2874c4 [kimi-k2.6] #and a bias point that sits cleanly at mid-rail.
