1f28a11f [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a11f [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a11f [kimi-k2.6] #How It Works
1f28a11f [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a120 [kimi-k2.6] #1. The Pico drives GPx as an output-low. This discharges Ctiming through
1f28a120 [kimi-k2.6] #Rseries.
1f28a120 [kimi-k2.6] #2. After a few microseconds, the Pico switches GPx to a high-impedance input.
1f28a120 [kimi-k2.6] #3. Ctiming now charges toward 3.3 V through the paddle potentiometer.
1f28a121 [kimi-k2.6] #4. The Pico counts how long until GPx reads high.
1f28a121 [kimi-k2.6] #   Time ∝ Resistance, so the count is proportional to paddle position.
1f28a121 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a121 [kimi-k2.6] #Because both channels can be discharged and timed in parallel on two GPIOs, a full two-paddle scan
1f28a122 [kimi-k2.6] #takes only one charge interval.
1f28a122 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a122 [kimi-k2.6] #BOM – RC Timing Version
1f28a122 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a123 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a123 [kimi-k2.6] #╭────────────┬─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1f28a123 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Ref        │ Value / Part    │ Notes                                              │
1f28a124 [kimi-k2.6] #├────────────┼─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1f28a124 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Ctiming A,B│ 4.7 nF (C0G/NP0)│ Timing capacitor. 2.2 nF–10 nF works; see below.   │
1f28a124 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Cdec       │ 100 nF          │ Decouple the 3.3 V excitation near the connector.  │
1f28a124 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Rseries    │ 1 kΩ            │ Limits current when GPIO discharges cap (min pot   │
1f28a125 [kimi-k2.6] #│            │                 │ resistance can be near 0 Ω).                       │
1f28a125 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Rpull A,B  │ 10 kΩ           │ External pull-ups for buttons (optional; Pico      │
1f28a125 [kimi-k2.6] #│            │                 │ internal pull-ups may also be used).               │
1f28a125 [kimi-k2.6] #│ Rlimit A,B │ 330 Ω           │ Series protection for button GPIOs.                │
1f28a126 [kimi-k2.6] #│ D1,D2      │ BAT54S (dual)   │ Optional clamp; keeps pin within –0.3 V … +3.6 V. │
1f28a126 [kimi-k2.6] #╰────────────┴─────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1f28a126 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a126 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a127 [kimi-k2.6] #• Choosing Ctiming*
1f28a127 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a127 [kimi-k2.6] #╭──────────┬────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1f28a127 [kimi-k2.6] #│  Value   │  Max time (≈1 MΩ)  │  Best for                                                     │
1f28a128 [kimi-k2.6] #├──────────┼────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1f28a128 [kimi-k2.6] #│  10 nF   │  ~8 ms             │  Very low noise; fine if you sample both paddles in parallel  │
1f28a128 [kimi-k2.6] #│  4.7 nF  │  ~4 ms             │  Good compromise (recommended starting point)                 │
1f28a128 [kimi-k2.6] #│  2.2 nF  │  ~2 ms             │  Faster reads; small cable capacitance matters more           │
1f28a129 [kimi-k2.6] #│  1 nF    │  ~0.9 ms           │  Use only with short, low-capacitance cables                  │
1f28a129 [kimi-k2.6] #╰──────────┴────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1f28a129 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a129 [kimi-k2.6] #A 1 m controller cable contributes roughly 50–150 pF of parasitic capacitance; 4.7 nF swamps that
1f28a12a [kimi-k2.6] #nicely without making frame deadlines tight.
1f28a12a [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12a [kimi-k2.6] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1f28a12a [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12b [kimi-k2.6] #Alternative: ADC Voltage Divider
1f28a12b [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12b [kimi-k2.6] #If you strongly prefer an analog voltage, use a divider and buffer it. A 1 MΩ source
1f28a12b [kimi-k2.6] #directly into the Pico ADC is not ideal for 12-bit accuracy because of leakage and sample-hold
1f28a12c [kimi-k2.6] #charge injection.
1f28a12c [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12c [kimi-k2.6] #Schematic
1f28a12c [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12d [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12d [kimi-k2.6] #Pico 3V3 ----------+---------------------------------------> DB9 Pin 7
1f28a12d [kimi-k2.6] #                   |
1f28a12d [kimi-k2.6] #                  Cdec
1f28a12e [kimi-k2.6] #                  100nF
1f28a12e [kimi-k2.6] #                   |
1f28a12e [kimi-k2.6] #                  GND
1f28a12e [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a12f [kimi-k2.6] #DB9 Pin 9 -------- Rpaddle (internal 0–1M) --------+--------+---> U1+
1f28a12f [kimi-k2.6] #                                                   |        |
1f28a12f [kimi-k2.6] #                                                  Rdiv    Rprot
1f28a12f [kimi-k2.6] #                                                  100k    1k
1f28a130 [kimi-k2.6] #                                                   |        |
1f28a130 [kimi-k2.6] #                                                  GND       +---> Pico ADC (GP26/27/28)
1f28a130 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a130 [kimi-k2.6] #U1: MCP6001/2 rail-to-rail op-amp wired as voltage follower
1f28a131 [kimi-k2.6] #Output of U1 drives the Pico ADC pin.
1f28a131 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a131 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a131 [kimi-k2.6] #Behaviour
1f28a132 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a132 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a132 [kimi-k2.6] #Vout = 3.3 V × Rdiv / (Rpaddle + Rdiv)
1f28a132 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a133 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a133 [kimi-k2.6] #This is non-linear (hyperbolic), so you must convert in software:
1f28a133 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a133 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a134 [kimi-k2.6] #Rpaddle = Rdiv × (3.3 / Vadc − 1)
1f28a134 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a134 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a134 [kimi-k2.6] #The op-amp gives the ADC a low-impedance source, eliminating settling-time errors.
1f28a135 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a135 [kimi-k2.6] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1f28a135 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a136 [kimi-k2.6] #Buttons
1f28a136 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a136 [kimi-k2.6] #Both paddle buttons are active-low:
1f28a136 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a137 [kimi-k2.6] #• Connect DB9 Pin 1 (Button A) and Pin 2 (Button B) to Pico GPIOs.
1f28a137 [kimi-k2.6] #• Enable the internal pull-up on each GPIO, or add an external 10 kΩ pull-up to 3.3 V.
1f28a137 [kimi-k2.6] #• Insert a 330 Ω series resistor near the Pico for short-circuit protection.
1f28a137 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a138 [kimi-k2.6] #When the button is pressed the pin is pulled to GND (DB9 Pin 8).
1f28a138 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a138 [kimi-k2.6] #━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1f28a138 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a139 [kimi-k2.6] #Wiring Summary
1f28a139 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a139 [kimi-k2.6] #╭───────────┬────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────╮
1f28a139 [kimi-k2.6] #│  DB9 Pin  │  Function  │  Connect to Pico                     │
1f28a13a [kimi-k2.6] #├───────────┼────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
1f28a13a [kimi-k2.6] #│  5        │  Pot B     │  GPIO (RC method) or ADC via buffer  │
1f28a13a [kimi-k2.6] #│  7        │  +V        │  **3V3(OUT)** — Pin 36               │
1f28a13a [kimi-k2.6] #│  8        │  GND       │  Any **GND** — e.g. Pin 38           │
1f28a13b [kimi-k2.6] #│  9        │  Pot A     │  GPIO (RC method) or ADC via buffer  │
1f28a13b [kimi-k2.6] #│  1        │  Button A  │  GPIO (with pull-up) — e.g. GP4      │
1f28a13b [kimi-k2.6] #│  2        │  Button B  │  GPIO (with pull-up) — e.g. GP5      │
1f28a13b [kimi-k2.6] #╰───────────┴────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────╯
1f28a13c [kimi-k2.6] #
1f28a13c [kimi-k2.6] #• Protection tip:* If you expect hot-plugging or ESD, add the BAT54S clamp diodes shown in
1f28a13c [kimi-k2.6] #the RC schematic on every line entering the Pico. Keep the 3.3 V excitation (DB9 Pin 7) local to
1f28a13c [kimi-k2.6] #your board; never connect this circuit to a live Atari console’s 5 V line while the Pico is
1f28a13d [kimi-k2.6] #running.
1f28a13d [kimi-k2.6] #
