1f3e74f3 [kimi-k2.6] # ꔀ nitrologic Relay 1.8.7 ⛲  kimi-k2.6 🜁 🪠 🧊 $0.018 526B 72.27s
1f3e74f3 [kimi-k2.6] #For a standard DB9 joystick VCC pin (pin 7 on Atari/Commodore/Sega-style sticks), you do not
1f3e74f3 [kimi-k2.6] #want a series resistor. Wire it directly to your regulated supply rail.
1f3e74f4 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e74f4 [kimi-k2.6] #Why no resistor?
1f3e74f4 [kimi-k2.6] #The VCC pin is a power rail, not a logic signal. A series resistor causes a voltage drop
1f3e74f4 [kimi-k2.6] #under load (`V = I·R`), which can sag the supply and make active electronics inside the pad
1f3e74f5 [kimi-k2.6] #(autofire, shift registers, etc.) behave erratically or reset.
1f3e74f5 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e74f5 [kimi-k2.6] #What to do instead
1f3e74f5 [kimi-k2.6] #╭────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1f3e74f6 [kimi-k2.6] #│  Situation                                                         │  Recommendation                                                                                                                                                                                               │
1f3e74f6 [kimi-k2.6] #├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1f3e74f6 [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Passive stick** (switches only—most Atari/Commodore joysticks)  │  You often do **not** need to connect DB9 pin 7 at all. Just tie DB9 pin 8 (GND) to your MCU ground, connect the direction/fire pins to GPIOs, and enable the MCU’s internal pull‑ups.                        │
1f3e74f6 [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Active stick** (Sega, autofire, paddles, etc.)                  │  Connect the DB9 VCC pin directly to the same voltage the stick expects—almost always **+5 V**. Do not power a 5 V device from a 3.3 V MCU rail; use a 5 V regulator if your MCU board does not provide one.  │
1f3e74f7 [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Short‑circuit / overcurrent protection**                        │  If you are worried about a short in the cable or stick, use a **PTC resettable fuse** (e.g., 100–250 mA) rather than a resistor.                                                                             │
1f3e74f7 [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Decoupling**                                                    │  Place a **100 nF ceramic capacitor** between DB9 VCC and GND right at the connector to suppress switching noise.                                                                                             │
1f3e74f7 [kimi-k2.6] #╰────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1f3e74f7 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e74f8 [kimi-k2.6] #If you meant signal pull‑ups
1f3e74f8 [kimi-k2.6] #In case you are actually asking about the direction/fire lines: enable your microcontroller’s
1f3e74f8 [kimi-k2.6] #internal pull‑ups (typically 20–50 kΩ), or add an external 10 kΩ resistor between your MCU
1f3e74f8 [kimi-k2.6] #VCC and each DB9 signal pin. Those go on the signal pins, not the VCC pin.
1f3e74f9 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e74f9 [kimi-k2.6] #• Bottom line:* Power pin = direct copper (0 Ω). Use a fuse for safety, and a decoupling
1f3e74f9 [kimi-k2.6] #cap for stability.
1f3e74f9 [kimi-k2.6] #
