1f3e955a [kimi-k2.6] #No—internal pull-ups or pull-downs will not give you usable readings from standard Atari-style
1f3e955a [kimi-k2.6] #paddles.
1f3e955b [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e955b [kimi-k2.6] #A paddle is a 1 MΩ rheostat between VCC and the signal pin. A microcontroller’s internal
1f3e955b [kimi-k2.6] #pull resistor is typically 20 kΩ–50 kΩ, and the datasheet usually specifies that value only
1f3e955b [kimi-k2.6] #as a broad range (it varies by lot, temperature, and voltage). That mismatch ruins both
1f3e955c [kimi-k2.6] #voltage-divider and timing approaches.
1f3e955c [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e955c [kimi-k2.6] #Why it fails
1f3e955c [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e955d [kimi-k2.6] #╭────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
1f3e955d [kimi-k2.6] #│  Method                        │  What happens                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
1f3e955d [kimi-k2.6] #├────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
1f3e955d [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Internal pull-down + ADC**  │  You create a divider: V_pin = VCC × R_internal / (R_paddle + R_internal). With 50 kΩ against 1 MΩ, the pin only rises to about **0.24 V** at full resistance. Nearly the entire knob travel is compressed into the bottom few percent of your ADC range, giving coarse, non-linear steps. And because R_internal is poorly specified, the same paddle position yields different values on different chips.  │
1f3e955e [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Internal pull-up**          │  The paddle does not have a ground lead inside the cable; the potentiometer connects between VCC (pin 7) and the signal pin. To use a pull-up you would have to rewire pin 7 to GND, which is non-standard. Even then, the divider is hyperbolic and most of the travel is squashed near the top of the ADC range, again with lot-to-lot variation.                                                          │
1f3e955e [kimi-k2.6] #│  **Digital timing**            │  The classic RC method needs a capacitor to ground and a known charge curve. Internal pull resistors are not precision timing elements; their value is too high and too loose to charge an external capacitor in a predictable, linear way.                                                                                                                                                                  │
1f3e955e [kimi-k2.6] #╰────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
1f3e955e [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e955f [kimi-k2.6] #What you actually need
1f3e955f [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e955f [kimi-k2.6] #For the standard RC timing method (one GPIO per paddle):
1f3e955f [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e9560 [kimi-k2.6] #• Capacitor: 47–100 nF from the signal pin to ground.
1f3e9560 [kimi-k2.6] #• Series resistor: 470 Ω–1 kΩ between the DB9 signal pin and your MCU GPIO. This limits
1f3e9560 [kimi-k2.6] #current when the GPIO drives low to discharge the capacitor and the paddle happens to be at 0 Ω.
1f3e9560 [kimi-k2.6] #• VCC on DB9 pin 7: Wired direct to your supply rail (3.3 V or 5 V).
1f3e9561 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e9561 [kimi-k2.6] #Drive the GPIO low to discharge the cap, release it to input, then count the time until the pin
1f3e9561 [kimi-k2.6] #reads high. The charge time is directly proportional to paddle resistance (t ≈ 0.7·R·C), so the
1f3e9561 [kimi-k2.6] #result is linear and repeatable across the whole knob travel.
1f3e9562 [kimi-k2.6] #
1f3e9562 [kimi-k2.6] #If you absolutely must avoid a capacitor and use the ADC, you would need an external
1f3e9562 [kimi-k2.6] #precision resistor to ground (on the order of 100 kΩ–1 MΩ) and some buffering to keep the response
1f3e9562 [kimi-k2.6] #reasonably linear—but the RC method is far simpler and matches how the original hardware worked.
1f3e9563 [kimi-k2.6] #
